<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senators Back Select Industry Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate supporters of a $1.5 billion loan  
program for U.S. steel, oil and gas producers made changes Thursday 
to ensure that funding would not come from Social Security 
reserves. 
</P>
<P>
	With those agreements, the Senate was expected Friday to pass  
legislation creating the program, which is aimed at helping to tide 
over those industries until their prices recover. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, and other conservatives criticized the  
$270 million in taxpayer spending needed to back the new loans, 
saying the money would come directly from Social Security 
surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	To address that criticism, the bill's backers agreed late in the  
day to remove the measure's ``emergency'' designation. By doing so, 
they guaranteed that lawmakers would have to cut other programs 
before they could pay for the loans. 
</P>
<P>
	Senators also agreed to other changes aimed at removing politics  
from the loan-approval process and requiring private lenders to 
share in at least 15 percent of the risk. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters said the loans would help domestic steel producers  
unable to compete with low-priced imports and U.S. oil and natural 
gas industries struggling because of sagging prices. Officials say 
the three industries have suffered tens of thousands of layoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have had a very grave time in the steel industry,'' said  
Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa. ``You can't compete against a (foreign) 
seller that will sell at any price.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The loan program for small oil and gas firms was attached at the  
insistence of Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M. Some of the steel loans 
would be available for iron producers as well. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., has promised to let the  
House vote on the measure. Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., its chief 
architect, urged colleagues to reject amendments, saying any 
changes would make it harder for Hastert to keep his commitment. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would provide $1 billion in steel loans, with companies  
eligible to borrow up to $250 million at market interest rates. 
U.S. oil and gas producers and service companies would be able to 
borrow up to $10 million each from a $500 million fund. As part of 
the agreement, supporters dropped provisions setting minimum loan 
amounts. 
</P>
<P>
	The loan measure was the first of several steel-related bills to  
reach the Senate floor. The full Senate could consider as early as 
next week a bill that would establish comprehensive quotas on 
foreign steel shipments. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
