<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 08:00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  U.S. Economy Powers Asian Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets rallied Thursday,  
buoyed by weaker-than-expected inflation data in the United States 
and the overnight surge in U.S. share prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Sentiment throughout the region also was lifted by sharp gains  
in Asia's biggest market, Tokyo, where the key 225-issue Nikkei 
Stock Average finished at a 20-month high. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei closed at 17,470.45 points, up 260.27, or 1.51  
percent -- its highest since Oct. 22, 1997, when the index closed at 
17,687.61. On Wednesday, the Nikkei had dropped 71.82 points, or 
0.42 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many investors are very optimistic, both for the U.S. economy  
and the domestic economy in Japan,'' said Tsuyoshi Nomaguchi, a 
strategist at Daiwa Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Labor Department announced Wednesday that inflation for  
May was flat, easing some traders' earlier fears that any 
indication of rising prices in the United States might prompt the 
U.S. Federal Reserve to raise interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	In reaction, the Dow Jones industrial average in New York rose  
1.8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, rising share prices in Japan also lifted the Japanese  
yen against the U.S. dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 120.04 yen in late trading, down 0.20 yen from  
late Wednesday in Tokyo and also below its overnight New York level 
of 120.43 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, which is particularly sensitive to U.S. interest  
rate moves, shares also rose sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip Hang Seng Index jumped 1.9 percent, or 253.15  
points, to finish at 13,408.27, after already rallying 1.7 percent 
Wednesday. The market will be closed Friday for a Chinese festival 
holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. interest rate moves are typically followed by Hong Kong,  
which pegs the value of its currency to the U.S. dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	In Taiwan, the key stock index surged to a 13-month high, led by  
gains in some electronics and financial stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Weighted Price Index rose 215.34 points, or 2.7 percent, at  
8,274.36. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. inflation data also powered strong rallies in Bangkok,  
Jakarta, Sydney and Manila, while Singapore, Seoul and Wellington 
chalked up smaller gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Kuala Lumpur was the only market bucking the regional  
trend, as political uncertainties weighed down share prices for a 
fourth straight day. 
</P>
<P>
	At the close of heavy trading, the Composite Index was at 787.79  
points, down 4.12 points, or 0.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Political analysts are expecting Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad  
to dissolve parliament during the annual convention of the United 
Malays National Organization, the dominant party in the ruling 
coalition, which gets underway Friday, paving the way for a snap 
election. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thai shares surged. The SET index gained 10.71 points,  
or 2.1 percent, to 520.55. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian shares soared on Wall Street's rally and the  
decline in a local interest rate. The JSX Composite Index closed up 
2.9 percent, or 19.187 points, at 681.039. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine stocks rose on renewed investor confidence.  
The PSE index rose 26.78 points, or 1.1 percent, to 2,418.08. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Singapore shares rose moderately. The Straits Times  
Index gained 13.54 points, or 0.66 percent, closing at 2,057.34. 
</P>
