<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Belgian Scare Hurts Coke Overseas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- With struggling foreign economies already hurting  
sales and its bottom line, Coca-Cola had enough headaches overseas 
before its soft drinks were linked to the hospitalization of dozens 
of people in Belgium. 
</P>
<P>
	Now some Belgians say they're kicking their Coke habits for  
good. And publicity surrounding the scare threatens to tarnish the 
soft-drink giant's image worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	But analysts say they don't expect permanent damage to Coke's  
image or its finances, largely because of the company's worldwide 
popularity and reputation for quality. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a brand with decades of good will behind it,'' said  
John Sicher, editor and publisher of Beverage Digest. ``It's not an 
accident that Coke sells so much of its product in these countries. 
It sells its product because it's been there a long time and people 
like it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Today, Belgium and France lifted bans on the sale of some of  
Coke's products. But sales of Coke, Sprite and Fanta remained 
banned in Belgium, pending further investigation into what caused 
the illnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Coke chairman M. Douglas Ivester expressed the company's regrets  
to European customers Wednesday in his first public statement about 
the scare. He said the company ``will not rest'' until consumers 
are assured of Coke's quality standards. 
</P>
<P>
	``For 113 years our success has been based on the trust that  
consumers have in that quality,'' Ivester said. ``That trust is 
sacred to us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas expansion has been key to Coke's growth over the last  
decade. Coke, with brands including Diet Coke, Sprite, Bonaqua and 
Minute Maid fruit juices, now controls half the world's market for 
carbonated soft drinks. 
</P>
<P>
	Continuing that growth has been tough lately. Economic turmoil  
in Asia, Russia and parts of Latin America has hurt sales and 
Coke's earnings. Meanwhile, Coke's plans to expand by buying two 
foreign competitors have been bogged down by antitrust challenges. 
</P>
<P>
	These were Coke's major worries overseas before Belgian  
officials banned Coke products Monday after dozens of youths were 
hospitalized for vomiting, stomach pains and nausea. 
</P>
<P>
	Luxembourg has also banned all Coke products, and other European  
nations have taken similar precautions. France ordered the 
withdrawal of all canned Coke products. And Spain on Wednesday 
froze a shipment of 8,000 bottles of Belgian-produced Coke and 
other Coca-Cola brands in the northern province of Zamora for fear 
of contamination. 
</P>
<P>
	Coke scrambled to get to the bottom of the health scare. It  
traced bad-tasting bottled drinks to a plant in Antwerp, Belgium, 
where the carbon dioxide used to inject fizz into drinks was 
substandard. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, an offensive odor on some cans was traced to a plant in  
Dunkirk, France. The odor was caused by a fungicide on wooden 
pallets used to transport cans to Belgium, which accounts for fewer 
than 1 percent of Coke's sales worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola Belgium said today it would reimburse the medical  
costs of anyone who could prove they had fallen ill through 
drinking its products. 
</P>
<P>
	The Belgian government also said today it is dropping its  
nationwide ban on some Coca-Cola soft drinks produced by Coca-Cola, 
including Nestea, Aquarius and Minute Maid fruit juices. But it 
ordered Coke, Fanta and Sprite to remain off shelves pending 
further investigation into what caused dozens of Coke drinkers to 
fall ill. 
</P>
<P>
	There was better news for Coke from Paris, where the government  
announced it was relaxing a ban on canned Coca Cola products to 
allow sales to resume from one of two Coke's French plants. 
</P>
<P>
	Also in Paris, French President Jacques Chirac said he will  
propose creating an international council to monitor food safety. 
</P>
<P>
	The issue has become especially critical following two scandals  
in Belgium -- one involving Coca-Cola and the other dioxin-infected 
meat, eggs and dairy products. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our people are increasingly concerned, worried,'' Chirac said  
at a joint news conference with President Clinton in advance of a 
meeting Friday in Germany of leaders of the world's leading 
industrial nations and Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	Coke spokesman Rob Baskin said the company is confident the  
problems have been solved. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that we're close to satisfying their needs for  
assurance,'' Baskin said. ``And we're hopeful they will allow us to 
resume distribution of our products.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coke should largely be able to wi back customers frightened by  
the health scare, said Ann Gurkin, an analyst for Davenport and 
Company. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see it impacting consumption,'' she said. ``I think it  
was two unusual events that hit at the same time. I think the 
company will do a great job at explaining what happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But workers in Brussels said Wednesday they're not sure they'll  
continue drinking Coke even if Belgium lifts the ban. 
</P>
<P>
	``No, I've stopped drinking it, and I don't think I will start  
again,'' said Natalie Sinnodt, 23, a social worker. ``I should have 
stopped anyway for diet reasons, this makes it easier.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign markets account for 70 percent of Coke's worldwide case  
volume, an important industry indicator measuring sales of units of 
24 eight-ounce servings. 
</P>
<P>
	The company has blamed slumping sales in turbulent foreign  
markets for recent losses. Profits fell 13 percent in the first 
quarter of 1999 and 14 percent for all of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoping to kickstart its foreign expansion, Coke has been trying  
to reach a $1 billion-plus deal to buy soft-drink brands owned by 
Cadbury Schweppes -- including Dr Pepper and Canada Dry -- outside 
the United States. But the deal has run afoul of regulators in 
Australia and several European countries who fear it would 
discourage competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Coke signed a $758 million deal to buy the brand  
Orangina from a French company after France had stalled the deal 
for 18 months. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
