<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> El Duque Sued for More Child Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The former wife of New York Yankees pitcher Orlando  
``El Duque'' Hernandez is suing him for an increase in 
child-support payments. 
</P>
<P>
	Norma Manso, wants a minimum of $9,500 a month -- up from the  
current $2,000 -- and has filed a lawsuit asking the payments be 
retroactive to October, when she arrived from Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a divorce decree made in Cuba two years ago,  
Hernandez agreed to pay 60 pesos a month for both of his two 
daughters, the equivalent of $3. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, Hernandez has become a millionaire, earning at least  
$1.85 million a year, according to the suit filed June 8. 
</P>
<P>
	El Duque, who defected from Cuba on a raft in December 1997,  
helped the Yankees win the World Series last year. He requested 
that his mother, ex-wife and daughters come to the United States to 
attend a ticker tape parade after the World Series victory. 
</P>
<P>
	He bought a $260,000 home in Miami for Manso and their two  
daughters, Yahumara, 9, and Stheffi, 3. He also bought his ex-wife 
a car worth about $20,000, pays for the private school tuition of 
his children, and covers their health and dental insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the documents filed, Hernandez had increased his  
monthly child support payment to $2,000 from $1,000 in January at 
his ex-wife's request but allegedly threatened to cut off payments 
and evict Manso and the children if she tried to obtain more money. 
</P>
<P>
	``Orlando has always taken care of the girls, but the money he  
gives me to support the girls isn't enough to live in this 
country,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Court documents state the family's expenses are $7,760 a month  
and they estimate vacation costs at $3,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The documents also state that Manso, a homemaker, doesn't speak  
English, is not qualified to obtain employment and has no income. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have not been able to find employment in this country, first  
because I don't have anyone to care for the girls, and second, 
because I don't know the language,'' she said. ``That's why we have 
to depend on him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Manso's attorney, Robert Spiegelman, declined to comment to The  
Miami Herald for a report Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	So did Joe Cubas, Hernandez's agent.  
</P>
<P>
	Hernandez could not be reached for comment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
