<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kevorkian Associate May Be Indicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO RANCHO, N.M. (AP) -- Prosecutors intend to seek an indictment  
against an associate of Dr. Jack Kevorkian who allegedly helped a 
woman suffering from multiple sclerosis commit suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	A grand jury will meet next month to consider assisted suicide  
charges against Dr. Georges Reding, a 74-year-old psychiatrist from 
Michigan's Kalamazoo County. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our plans right now are to take it to a grand jury,'' District  
Attorney Mike Runnels said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Assisted suicide is a felony in New Mexico under a 1963 law and  
is punishable by 18 months in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities initially thought Donna Brennan, 54, of Rio Rancho,  
N.M., died of natural causes Aug. 30. But an autopsy showed Brennan 
was given a lethal dose of a sedative sometimes used on animals. 
</P>
<P>
	Telephone and credit card records, along with a witness, place  
Reding at Brennan's house around the time of her death. 
</P>
<P>
	An attorney for Reding, Michael Schwartz, said Brennan had  
contacted the psychiatrist for counseling. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no evidence and no admission that Dr. Reding helped  
end her life,'' Schwartz told the Detroit News. ``It would be a 
foolish waste of time to seek an indictment of Georges Reding.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, Reding was charged in connection with three  
assisted-suicide deaths in Oakland County, Mich. Kevorkian also was 
charged. A prosecutor later dropped all the charges, saying there 
was insufficient evidence to win in court. 
</P>
<P>
	Less than two years later, Reding and Kevorkian were arrested on  
charges they resisted arrested and interfered with police while 
dropping a body off at a Royal Oak, Mich., hospital. Reding was 
acquitted; Kevorkian was convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevorkian remains in jail since his conviction in April on a  
second-degree murder charge. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
