<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Silver Charm's Road to Retirement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                          *AP Sports Writes    	
</P>
<P>
	The big, dappled gray horse caught the eye ... and the heart.  
</P>
<P>
	``He was such a noble horse,'' trainer Bob Baffert said. ``His  
presence was always felt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One November morning in 1997 during Breeders' Cup week at  
Hollywood Park, Baffert took Silver Charm to the track for a 
gallop. 
</P>
<P>
	He had not raced since his dramatic Triple Crown, in which he  
won the Kentucky Derby and Preakness and finished second in the 
Belmont Stakes, and he was not going to race in the Breeders' Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver Charm quickly became the center of attention that  
morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of his running style, his victories were always exciting  
-- his win in the 1998 Dubai World Cup was especially memorable -- 
and so were many of his defeats. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Saturday at Churchill Downs, Silver Charm started in the  
Stephen Foster Handicap. 
</P>
<P>
	When the 5-year-old horse turned for home, Baffert knew it was  
over. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had nothing,'' Baffert said. ``I thought, `Man, this is not  
our horse.''' He finished fourth, soundly beaten by Victory Gallop. 
</P>
<P>
	Owner Bob Lewis agreed with Baffert, and so after a fourth  
straight loss, Silver Charm was retired to breeding. 
</P>
<P>
	A ton of talent remains in Baffert's barn, despite a  
disappointing Triple Crown series this spring, but Silver Charm's 
retirement leaves a void. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver Charm was the trainer's pet.  
</P>
<P>
	``When I got to the barn, he's the first one I'd go to, and I'd  
give him his carrot,'' Baffert said. ``People would show up and ask 
for him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Horse racing, however, is not a yesterday sport. Anyone look who  
looks backward instead of ahead is in the wrong game. 
</P>
<P>
	So Baffert is busy getting some of his stars ready to race  
again. As he does, in the back of his mind is next year and the 
Triple Crown. 
</P>
<P>
	``I probably have 30 2-year-olds,'' Baffert said. ``Bob Lewis  
has two real good ones. One cost $1.8 million and the other 
$950,000 and are yet to start. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert's 2-year-old filly, Chilukki, unbeaten in two starts and  
a winner over colts in one of them, will race in the Debutante on 
June 26 at Churchill Downs. 
</P>
<P>
	The trainer's other Derby-Preakness winner (1998), Real Quiet,  
left Churchill Downs on Wednesday for California and his next start 
June 27 in the Hollywood Gold Cup. In his last two races, the 
4-year-old colt won the Pimlico Special, then the Massachusetts 
Handicap at Suffolk Down. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday, the 3-year-old filly who won 11 of 12 starts  
before finishing seventh in her debut against males in the Belmont 
Stakes, is set to start in the Monmouth Oaks on July 10 at Monmouth 
Park. 
</P>
<P>
	``She came out of the Belmont fine,'' Baffert said, then joked,  
``I'm going to put her back in cupcake races.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Excellent Meeting, the filly who finished a good fifth in the  
Derby and was eased in the Preakness, is expected to race Sunday in 
the Princess at Hollywood Park. It was reported immediately after 
the Preakness that the filly had a breathing problem, but Baffert 
said, ``She just lost interest. She's fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In April, the colts General Challenge and Prime Timber were  
Baffert's two Kentucky Derby hopes after their 1-2 finish in the 
Santa Anita Derby. Prime Timber finished fourth in the Derby, won 
by Charismatic, and General Challenge finished ninth. Neither has 
raced since. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert said that when Prime Timber was reshod a couple of weeks  
after the Derby, a little crack on the sole of the left front foot 
was found, and while the colt is in training, it will be awhile 
before he races. 
</P>
<P>
	General Challenge, who will race in the Affirmed on June 26 at  
Hollywood Park, is called goofy by his trainer. ``He has a mind 
like Dennis Rodman's,'' Baffert said. 
</P>
<P>
	Another 3-year-old coming around for Baffert is Forestry, bought  
as yearling by Aaron and Marine Jones for $1.5 million. He has won 
four straight and has five victories in seven career starts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
