<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 07:20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft To Publish Dictionary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. is publishing an English  
dictionary, building on the success of the Encarta encyclopedia 
CD-ROM that has made the software company the nation's top 
encyclopedia publisher. 
</P>
<P>
	The Microsoft Encarta World English Dictionary will be published  
Aug. 4, in time for the back-to-school selling season, The Wall 
Street Journal reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The new dictionary, developed from scratch, will be bundled into  
the Encarta Reference Suite 2000 with the encyclopedia, an atlas 
and access to an online service. 
</P>
<P>
	But unlike the Encarta encyclopedia, which is only available for  
computer use, the dictionary also will be published in traditional 
print form. St. Martin's Press will publish the American version, 
Bloomsbury Publishing PLC for the United Kingdom and Pan Macmillan 
Australia Pty. Ltd. for Australia, according to the Journal. 
</P>
<P>
	The multiple versions indicate Microsoft's efforts to make the  
Encarta dictionary a global reference book, particularly for 
English-speaking e-mail users who communicate with people from 
other countries where English words can have different meanings. 
</P>
<P>
	Redmond, Wash.-based Microsoft has not yet released a price for  
the new Encarta software package or the print version of the 
dictionary, but the company said it will be comparably priced to 
the current Encarta suite that is available for about $69 with 
rebates. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft already offers an American Heritage dictionary in its  
Bookshelf 2000 software package. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 08:11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fans Root for Women's World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- As Mikka Hansen was rising through the ranks of  
U.S. soccer, her father kept making a seemingly strange request. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why don't you play for Denmark?'' he'd say.  
</P>
<P>
	``Sure, Dad, whatever,'' Hansen would tell her father, who was  
born in Denmark, making her eligible for the national team, even 
though Mikka was born and grew up in California. ``If you get in 
touch with them ...'' 
</P>
<P>
	She wasn't serious because, well, Hansen intended to play in the  
World Cup for the United States. She progressed through the youth 
ranks and at Santa Clara, where Hansen was a college star forward. 
She played for the under-21 U.S. women's squad. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always thought I would get a chance with the U.S. team,''  
Hansen said Wednesday at a news conference to kick off the World 
Cup, which begins Saturday at Giants Stadium -- where Hansen and the 
Danes face the Americans, followed by Mexico vs. Brazil. ``I came 
up with the Olympic Development program and it helped me become the 
player I am. 
</P>
<P>
	``But once I was 22 and I knew the players who were in front of  
me, I felt maybe that was not an option. I'm a forward and the U.S. 
has Mia (Hamm, the international career goal-scoring leader) and 
Tiffeny (Milbrett). You get to the point where you realize there 
are other players for the U.S. to choose and I wanted to play on a 
national team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So Hansen did, indeed, contact Danish soccer officials last  
October. By Christmas, they confirmed she could play professionally 
in their country. On Jan. 7, she headed to Denmark and, 10 days 
later, was in her first training camp with the national team. She 
accompanied the team to Portugal, where it finished fourth in a 
strong field. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's all happened pretty fast,'' Hansen said. ``It's been a  
dream come true for my father and my grandma, who was born in 
Denmark.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Hansen, the toughest adjustment has been in communicating  
with teammates. Although everyone on the team speaks English, it is 
not the first language for anyone except Hansen. When she shouts 
out instructions or encouragement on the field, she needs to ``put 
the words in Danish, not English, and that takes time to think 
about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She also notes that the Danes play a less-aggressive style than  
the Americans, and her timing has been off because of it. But coach 
Jorgen Hvidemose believes Hansen is making the necessary 
adjustments at a satisfactory pace. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is difficult to do what she is doing,'' he said. ``She  
wants to fit into the team, and contribute to the team, but she 
also has had to make some big changes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hansen expects it will be awkward Saturday when she opposes such  
friends as Julie Foudy and Brandi Chastain and Carla Overbeck, 
veterans of the U.S. team who helped Hansen's career. But she isn't 
backing away from the opportunity. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very excited,'' she said. ``I'm proud to be a part of this  
event. And in the last six months, the media in Denmark has been 
getting excited about covering the event and having a person who 
grew up in America playing on the team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hvidemose and the other players haven't really picked Hansen's  
brains about the U.S. team, mainly because the Danes are familiar 
enough with the Americans. Oddly, in the 1995 World Cup, where the 
Americans finished third as the defending champions, and at the 
1996 Olympics, where the U.S. squad won the gold, the opening 
opponent was Denmark. 
</P>
<P>
	The Danes eagerly have questioned Hansen about playing in the  
United States; Denmark also has games at Portland, Ore., and 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's funny to be with a team that hasn't been in the U.S. very  
often,'' Hansen said. ``The things they point out, I never really 
thought about. They think everything is so glamorous and big, and 
maybe a bit overdone. 
</P>
<P>
	``But they are impressed by how the preparations have been  
handled so well for this event. We can't wait to get started.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
