<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 01:40:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bombing Suspect Said Confessed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) -- A granddaughter of a longtime suspect in  
a 1963 church bombing said she heard him admit planting the bomb 
that killed four black girls, WBRC-TV reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Teresa Stacy, 23, of Dallas, told a grand jury she heard her  
grandfather, Bobby Frank Cherry, admit his involvement in the 
Sixteenth Street Baptist Church bombing at a family gathering more 
than 10 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said he helped blow up a bunch of folks in Birmingham,''  
she told the television station Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, Ms. Stacy said, she didn't fully understand what he  
meant. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was really young back then so I didn't think too much about  
it 'til I got older and they reopened the case ... and then I found 
out about the little girls and it made me sick to my stomach,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cherry, 69, of Mabank, Texas, has repeatedly denied any role in  
bombing the black church, an act of racist violence against the 
burgeoning civil rights movement. 
</P>
<P>
	He claims he had never set foot in the area where the bombing  
occurred. FBI investigators have repeatedly questioned Cherry and 
indicated they do not believe his alibi, but have never arrested 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	Cherry, contacted Wednesday by The Associated Press, called his  
granddaughter a ``dope head'' and ``prostitute.'' He said he talked 
to her about 10 years ago, but never told her he was involved in 
the bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	``It didn't happen and I didn't talk about it,'' he said. ``I  
don't understand why she would say anything like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Attorney Doug Jones and the FBI could not be reached for  
comment Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of the Sixteenth Street church were gathered for Sunday  
services on Sept. 15, 1963, when a dynamite bomb demolished an 
outside wall. Denise McNair, 11, and three 14-year-olds, Cynthia 
Wesley, Carole Robertson and Addie Mae Collins, were killed. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI investigated the bombing for about three years without  
filing charges. The state reopened the case in the 1970s, resulting 
in the murder conviction of Ku Klux Klan member Robert Chambliss, 
who later died in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators long ago publicly identified three other men as  
suspects: Herman Cash, who died in 1994, Tommy Blanton of 
Birmingham, and Cherry. Blanton also has denied involvement. An 
investigator has said they are targets of the current probe. 
</P>
<P>
	The current investigation is at least the fourth since the  
initial probe ended. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 16:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ueberroth Group Buys Pebble Beach  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A group that includes Arnold Palmer, Clint  
Eastwood and Peter Ueberroth agreed Thursday to buy the Pebble 
Beach golf course in California for $820 million, The Associated 
Press learned. 
</P>
<P>
	The group which Ueberroth, a former baseball commissioner, put  
together also includes former United Airlines chief executive 
Richard Ferris and General Electric Pensions. 
</P>
<P>
	A news conference was expected later Thursday, but details of  
the agreement were confirmed to the AP by a participant in the 
negotiations who spoke on the condition he not be identified. 
</P>
<P>
	Ueberroth's group becomes the fourth owner of the Pebble Beach  
Co. this decade. Bank America is providing financing. 
</P>
<P>
	Marvin Davis sold it in 1990 to Minoru Isutani for a price  
estimated at $850 million, and Isutani sold it two years later to 
The Lone Cypress Co., a Japanese golf resort company, for a price 
estimated at $500 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Perocchi, formerly involved with Ueberroth and Ferris in  
Doubletree Hotels, will become chief executive officer of Pebble 
Beach. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's properties in the Monterey area include four golf  
courses -- the Pebble Beach Golf Links, Spyglass Hill Golf Course, 
The Links at Spanish Bay and Del Monte Golf Course -- along with The 
Lodge at Pebble Beach and The Inn at Spanish Bay. It also owns the 
17-Mile Drive that winds through Pebble Beach and nearby Del Monte 
Forest and plans to develop a new course and 300 homes. 
</P>
<P>
	The 99th U.S. Amateur will be played at Pebble Beach and  
Spyglass Hill on Aug. 16-22. 
</P>
<P>
	Pebble Beach was host to the U.S. Open in 1972, 1982 and 1992  
and is scheduled to be host to the 100th U.S. Open next summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Eastwood is a former mayor of nearby Carmel, Calif.  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 17:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woods in Contention in U.S. Open  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PINEHURST, N.C. (AP) -- He laughed. He pouted. He smiled. He  
frowned. He pumped his arms. He seemed ready to toss his clubs 
away. 
</P>
<P>
	All in all, a most eventful day of golf for Tiger Woods.  
</P>
<P>
	Both erratic and brilliant during Thursday's opening round of  
the U.S. Open, Woods' enormous talent emerged triumphant by the 
time he walked off Pinehurst No. 2. 
</P>
<P>
	Woods finished with two straight birdies for a 2-under 68,  
leaving him just one shot behind main rival David Duval and three 
others sharing the lead. 
</P>
<P>
	``It felt nice to end that way,'' said Woods, who broke par for  
only the third time in 14 career U.S. Open rounds. ``To hit it the 
way I did today and steal a 68, that feels pretty good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His demeanor was quite a bit different on the front nine. His  
shoulders drooped when he throttled back to a 4-iron off the tee 
and still couldn't hit the fairway. Woods muttered to himself when 
he needed two shots to get out of a bunker. More than once, he 
seemed on the verge of slamming a club to the ground in anger, only 
to pull back at the last second. 
</P>
<P>
	The lowlight came at No. 5, when Woods missed a 6-footer for par  
and drew back his club like an ax, but stopped short of hitting the 
still-rolling ball. If Woods ever wants to take up a new career, he 
might consider becoming a lumberjack. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you saw me play today, you would say there's no way he  
could have shot the number he shot today,'' Woods said. ``It was 
not a pretty round, but I scored. And the name of the game is 
scoring. That's something I've always been able to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Woods came to the sandhills of North Carolina as a favorite to  
capture his second major title. He won his last two events against 
strong fields and Pinehurst -- with its short rough, spacious 
fairways and tricky greens -- seemed a perfect fit for his power and 
creativity. 
</P>
<P>
	But Woods struggled through the front nine with a 1-over 36,  
which could have been worse if not for a 10-foot bogey save at No. 
7, when he required those two shots to get out of the sand. After 
making the turn, he missed a 3-foot birdie try and with it, a prime 
opportunity to make up ground at the par-5 10th. 
</P>
<P>
	And just when he seemed headed for his seventh straight  
above-par round at the Open, the sun broke through the clouds. 
Woods' play -- and his demeanor -- also brightened. 
</P>
<P>
	At No. 11, he hit a 9-iron to within two inches of the flag, the  
ball nearly spinning back into the cup for an eagle. He seemed 
almost embarrassed by the shot, hiding a broad grin behind his 
right hand walking up the fairway alongside caddy Steve Williams. 
The gallery erupted in its first full-throated roar of Tigermania. 
</P>
<P>
	Five straight pars followed. Included were a 10-foot save at No.  
12 and a couple of up-and-downs where Woods used his 3-wood from 
the fringe of the green like a putter. 
</P>
<P>
	``I tried to manage my game and hang in there,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	At the par-3 17th, Woods produced another magnificent shot,  
hitting a 7-iron to within six feet and knocking in the putt for 
birdie. At 18, he striped his tee shot, outdriving playing partner 
Lee Westwood by 25 yards and the other member of the threesome, 
Corey Pavin, by 50. 
</P>
<P>
	Woods was pin-high with a pitching wedge from 137 yards, leaving  
him 12 feet away. The putt curled slowly across the turtleback 
green, veering left at the last second -- and into the cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always said that to win tournaments, you've got make sure  
your bad rounds are in the red,'' Woods said. ``I did that today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This time, he was smiling.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 11:40:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bin Laden Suspected To Plan Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A week after the FBI put him on its 10 Most  
Wanted List, suspected terrorist Osama bin Laden is said by U.S. 
intelligence to be in the advanced stages of planning another 
attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the timing and location of the strike are unknown, a U.S.  
official said there have been indications in recent weeks that bin 
Laden has been moving unspecified materials that could be used in a 
terrorist operation, and that U.S. facilities in African nations 
such as Ghana or Mozambique could be targets. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have always said we expecting bin Laden to strike again,''  
deputy State Department spokesman James Foley said today. ``We take 
such threats seriously.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blamed by the United States for ordering last year's bombings of  
U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania, bin Laden is thought to be in 
Afghanistan, where the FBI said it is getting no help in bringing 
him to justice. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the difficulty of launching an operation at targets  
in the United States, bin Laden is expected to focus on targets in 
poorer countries where security is weaker, intelligence officials 
have concluded. 
</P>
<P>
	But the official stressed that there is no clear intelligence on  
the timing or target of any impending attack. 
</P>
<P>
	A State Department official confirmed there has been a pattern  
of activities by the bin Laden network that indicate continued 
planning for a terrorist attack. But he, too, had no information on 
timing or location. There has been an upsurge recently in reports 
of such planning, much as there was before last Christmas, the 
official added. 
</P>
<P>
	The official, asking not to be identified, said terrorist  
threats have been received on all continents. 
</P>
<P>
	CIA Director George Tenet said in February ``there is not the  
slightest doubt'' that bin Laden, ``his worldwide allies, and his 
sympathizers are planning further attacks against'' the United 
States ``at any time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We are anticipating bombing attempts ... but his operatives  
are also capable of kidnappings and assassinations,'' Tenet said. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC-TV quoted U.S. intelligence officials Wednesday as saying  
they believe bin Laden is suffering from Marfan's syndrome, an 
illness that would put him at risk of having a stroke. 
</P>
<P>
	But an official discounted the notion that any illness bin Laden  
suffers may be causing the exiled Saudi millionaire to accelerate 
his plans for any terrorist action. 
</P>
<P>
	Bin Laden has openly declared his hostility to the United States  
for its support of Israel and for the presence of U.S. troops in 
the Persian Gulf region. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
