<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Allen's Co. Buys Into Oxygen Media </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Cable mogul Paul G. Allen will make a $100  
million investment in Oxygen Media, the start-up cable and Internet 
company devoted to women, just as competition in the category grows 
through efforts by Time Warner Inc., Dow Jones News Service 
reports. 
</P>
<P>
	Oxygen said Wednesday that Vulcan Ventures Inc., Allen's  
investment group, would take a minority stake in Oxygen, a media 
company led by former ABC and Nickelodeon executive Geraldine 
Laybourne. 
</P>
<P>
	Oxygen will also enter into a carriage agreement with Charter  
Communications, a cable company also owned by Allen. Under the 
agreement's terms, Charter's cable systems will distribute Oxygen 
to their subscribers. Charter has 2.3 million subscribers and has 
entered into agreements to buy systems with another 3.6 million 
subscribers. 
</P>
<P>
	Oxygen expects to launch in early 2000, and has reached separate  
carriage agreements with AT&AMP;T Corp.'s Tele-Communications Inc. and 
MediaOne Group Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Allen is the co-founder of Microsoft Corp. and has taken several  
steps to amass a large cable presence. In a statement, Vulcan 
Ventures President William D. Savoy said Oxygen ``develops valuable 
new brands and builds on successful existing brands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The infant operation already has several prominent minority  
owners. Oprah Winfrey's HARPO Entertainment Group, America Online 
Inc. and ABC, which is owned by Walt Disney Co., all hold minority 
positions, along with an entity formed by TV producers Marcy 
Carsey, Tom Werner and Caryn Mandabach. 
</P>
<P>
	The move comes as competition in the women's programming  
marketplace increases. Last week, Time Warner and Advance 
Publications said they would team up to create a new television 
network and Web site targeting women. Lifetime, a cable channel 
owned by Hearst Corp. and Disney, has spent the past several months 
beefing up its programming. 
</P>
<P>
	Advance owns Conde Nast Publications, a magazine group that  
includes Vanity Fair, GQ and the New Yorker. Time Warner operates 
its large Time Inc. magazine unit and owns a suite of Turner 
Broadcasting cable channels. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
