<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Finals Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- If pressed, Marcus Camby reveals only a  
sliver of what makes his relationship with Jeff Van Gundy tick. 
</P>
<P>
	Contrary to widespread belief, Camby said Thursday, the ticking  
is not of the time bomb variety. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a great working relationship,'' said Camby, the Knicks  
forward who was reportedly angry with his coach over playing time 
earlier this season. ``We understand each other. He trusts me, I 
trust him and we just go from there. Just in the postseason with my 
minutes, I'm definitely proving I can get the job done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Camby and Latrell Sprewell both denied a rift with Van Gundy,  
who was reluctant to give them the minutes they wanted until 
Patrick Ewing's season-ending Achilles' injury forced his hand. 
</P>
<P>
	In truth, Camby may have lacked the endurance to play extended  
minutes at the beginning of the lockout-shortened season. That has 
changed in the playoffs. Camby has been one of the saviors in New 
York's improbable drive to the NBA Finals, averaging 31 minutes as 
a reserve to help the Knicks beat the Indiana Pacers in the Eastern 
Conference finals. 
</P>
<P>
	As the Knicks prepared for Game 2 of the finals following an  
89-77 loss to San Antonio on Wednesday night, Van Gundy suggested 
the ``supposedly strained relationships between myself and Marcus 
and myself and Latrell are far overblown. ... If there's problems, 
then they have problems with me, because I don't have any problems 
with them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sprewell didn't become a regular starter until Ewing was lost  
for the year with an Achilles' injury after Game 2 of the Pacers 
series. On whether he wants to be traded, Sprewell said, ``I'd 
rather not talk about that. It's not true.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Camby said he and Van Gundy talked twice about playing time  
early in the season, but ``we haven't had a problem since then.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TWIN TOWERS:* Many teams have tried to make a Twin Towers setup  
work. Few have achieved the success of the San Antonio Spurs with 
Tim Duncan and David Robinson. 
</P>
<P>
	The Houston Rockets tried it with 7-footers Ralph Sampson and  
Hakeem Olajuwon. The New York Knicks tried it briefly with Patrick 
Ewing and Bill Cartwright. In Game 1 against the Knicks, Duncan and 
Robinson showed how it's supposed to be done. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of it probably has been the roles being well defined,''  
said Robinson, who has gladly taken a secondary role in the Spurs' 
offense. ``When you have two 7-footers, the guys have got to know 
how they're going to work together. They've got to know what their 
roles are going to be on the floor. And it can be difficult 
sometimes. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're focused and you know what your job is night in and  
night out, then it's a lot easier to go do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Duncan carried the offensive load with 33 points on an  
assortment of unstoppable jumpers and layups in Game 1, Robinson 
concentrated on defense with three blocks and several altered 
shots. He also turned into a de facto point guard, a 7-footer who 
can catch the ball at the foul line and distribute it with 
efficiency. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first time I met David, I think he told me that there are  
going to be a lot of things that people are going to try to tell 
you throughout your rookie year and throughout your career,'' 
Duncan said. ``He said, `I'm going to be here for you. I'm going to 
help you if you want me to help you. But I'm not going to go out 
there and force things upon you.''' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DOUBLE SHOWDOWN:* It's a Texas vs. New York double in pro  
sports these days. 
</P>
<P>
	While the San Antonio Spurs tangle with the New York Knicks in  
the NBA Finals, the Dallas Stars and Buffalo Sabres are squaring 
off in the NHL championship round. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spurs lead the basketball series 1-0 after Wednesday night's  
89-77 victory. The Stars and Sabres were tied 2-2 heading into 
Thursday night's Game 5 of the Stanley Cup finals. 
</P>
<P>
	The only other time two states have had professional teams in  
two finals in the same year was 1973, when New York and California 
met in baseball and basketball. The Oakland Athletics defeated the 
New York Mets 4-3 in baseball's World Series. New York got even by 
beating the Los Angles Lakers 4-1 in the NBA Finals. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *LAYUPS:* Texans wasted no time gloating over the Spurs' victory  
in Game 1. On Thursday morning, a billboard already was erected 
alongside the highway leading from the San Antonio airport to 
downtown. It read, ``Spurs 1, Knicks 0.'' ... From the headline 
department, the back page of Thursday's New York Post: ''Big 
Trouble.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
