<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kellogg Co. Considers More Job Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BATTLE CREEK, Mich. (AP) -- Kellogg Co. is considering closing  
part of its historic Battle Creek cereal plant and slashing up to 
700 of the plant's 1,100 jobs as part of an ongoing effort to boost 
its sagging market share. 
</P>
<P>
	The embattled company, which saw earnings drop 30 percent last  
quarter, is trying to retain its status as the nation's largest 
cereal maker. The announcement Thursday came just months after it 
hiked prices nearly 3 percent and cut 525 white collar jobs in its 
North American operations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Streamlining our operations and avoiding future costs would  
help keep our North American cereal business cost-competitive going 
into the 21st century,'' chief executive Carlos M. Gutierrez said 
in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say the proposed move would offer limited relief to  
Kellogg, which despite recent sales' increases remains in a very 
competitive market. 
</P>
<P>
	The Battle Creek-based Kellogg owns eight of the world's top 10  
best-selling cereals, including Rice Krispies, Frosted Flakes and 
Special K, and has about 31 percent of the market, just ahead of 
rival General Mills. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Kellogg has been battered by cheaper generic and  
store-brand cereals. Busy consumers have also left cereal for foods 
such as bagels and muffins that can be eaten on the run. 
</P>
<P>
	To counter this trend, Kellogg has attempted to streamline its  
operations while at the same time investing heavily in marketing 
its products. So far, it's had limited success: While revenue for 
the first three months of 1999 rose 8 percent, earnings dropped 30 
percent, including a charge for the previously announced job cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Future prospects remain uncertain, said analyst Christopher  
Jakubik of Warburg Dillon Read in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``You still have too many players. There's still very limited  
growth in the category.'' That will make it hard for any 
cereal-maker to make a decent return on investment, he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were largely unfazed by Kellogg's announcement,  
pushing shares down 18 3/4 cents to $33.81 1/4 in trading on the New York 
Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference Thursday, Joseph Stewart, senior vice  
president of corporate affairs, said the closure recommendation was 
made because updating equipment at the aging plant -- parts of which 
date back to 1907 -- would have been too expensive. He said employee 
benefits and wages were not a factor. 
</P>
<P>
	``We expect an annual savings of $35 million to $45 million,''  
he said. ``Those funds can be reinvested in our business. ... We 
hope 1999 will be the beginning of a turnaround.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart said a final decision about the closing will not be made  
until later this year, when discussions with the union are 
complete. But he said Kellogg has no plans to replace any jobs cut 
with new positions at its other facilities, although equipment 
inside the plant may be moved to other plants. 
</P>
<P>
	Battle Creek, which makes Kellogg's Corn Flakes, is Kellogg's  
largest plant in North America -- it would drop to third if the cuts 
are made. The company invested $80 million in the facility two 
years ago, leaving many baffled about how the plant could still be 
considered outdated. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers at the plant were ordered to attend a meeting early  
Thursday, where a manufacturing vice president made a seven-minute 
presentation and told them to call a 1-800 number if they had any 
questions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'd seen it coming. The plant's been so mismanaged,'' said  
Rick Cameron, 46, who has cooked corn at the plant for 28 years. 
``They've got their mind made up. They're going to keep cutting and 
cutting.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
