<HEADLINE> 2 Sentenced for Selling Software </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Two defendants were sentenced to more than two  
years in prison in a conspiracy to resell almost $20 million worth 
of computer software that had been stolen from a manufacturing 
plant in Plymouth. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Court Judge George A. O'Toole sentenced  
59-year-old Maxine Simons of Peabody to two years and nine months 
in prison and ordered her to pay $908,000 in restitution to 
Microsoft. Gerald Coviello, 62, of Woburn was sentenced to two and 
a half years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Both were convicted by a federal jury in March of conspiracy to  
transport stolen property. 
</P>
<P>
	Simons was also convicted on 15 counts of interstate  
transportation of stolen property, two counts of attempting to 
evade federal bank reporting requirements and one count of making a 
false statement to the FBI. 
</P>
<P>
	She was the president of Crazy Bob's, a discount computer outlet  
in Wakefield which she operated with her husband, Robert. 
</P>
<P>
	Between 1994 and 1997, Crazy Bob's purchased computer products  
that had been stolen from KAO Infosystems, prosecutors said. 
Prosecutors say the stolen goods were sold by two former KAO 
employees, David LaPointe and John Costello. 
</P>
<P>
	The largest shipment of the stolen property consisted of 32,000  
Microsoft Office '97 Professional Edition CD-ROMs, each valued at 
$599. The store sold the disks to various outlets located in 
California and Great Britain. 
</P>
<P>
	LaPointe, Costello, Robert Simons and two Crazy Bob's employees,  
Mark Rosengard and William Simons, pleaded guilty to related 
federal charges. Earlier this week, Robert Simons, was sentenced to 
five years and 10 months in prison and William Simons was sentenced 
to 22 months in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	The others await sentencing.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
