<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Solicits Consumer Opinion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. has discreetly added a message  
to the Internet site visited by millions of people who use its 
Windows software urging them to write to Congress about the 
government's antitrust case. 
</P>
<P>
	The move suggests an intensified public relations campaign by  
Microsoft as trial testimony nears an end and pressure grows to 
resume settlement negotiations with government lawyers. It comes 
days after Microsoft's billionaire chairman, Bill Gates, testified 
before a sympathetic Senate panel and met privately with key 
lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	The affected Microsoft Web site draws millions of visitors each  
month to update their copies of Windows, the operating system 
software that runs most of the world's personal computers. 
</P>
<P>
	When Microsoft's lawyer showed the site to the trial judge  
during a courtroom demonstration last week, the message was not 
there. 
</P>
<P>
	This week, however, Microsoft added the note urging visitors to  
its ``Windows Update'' site to ``click here'' for details about how 
its legal fight with the Justice Department and 19 states might 
affect them and how to write about the lawsuit to their elected 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	``I suspect ... they didn't want the judge to see this,'' said  
Justice Department lawyer David Boies. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft said Thursday it added the message to Windows Update  
in what it described as a routine change. It said it wasn't trying 
to prevent U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson from seeing 
it on the page during last week's demonstration. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it had anything to do with that,'' spokesman Jim  
Cullinan said. ``... I don't think there's anything conspicuous 
about this. This was being updated in the normal part of 
business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The message already had been included for at least six months on  
other Web pages within Microsoft's vast network, but fewer people 
than expected had subscribed to the company's occasional newsletter 
about the trial. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're trying to get the word out that this is available,''  
Cullinan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Government lawyers said the new message on the site was  
inappropriate. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's another of the many ways in which they use their market  
power to advance their own causes,'' said Stephen Houck of the New 
York attorney general's office, the lawyer for the states. 
``They're using a position they've obtained as a result of what we 
believe to be illegal acts to propagate a political message, and we 
find that troubling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trial testimony was expected to end next week after more than  
five months in the courtroom. The judge has privately encouraged 
the sides to try to settle before his verdict later this year, but 
negotiations have failed in at least two face-to-face meetings 
since the trial began. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft has described Windows Update as one of the most  
compelling features of the latest version of Windows. 
</P>
<P>
	When customers using Windows 98 visit the site using Microsoft's  
own Web browser, it automatically analyzes their computers and can 
install incremental improvements and important security patches 
with a few mouse clicks. The site can even notify customers 
whenever upgrades are available, typically a few times each month. 
It will not function if customers use other versions of Windows or 
another company's Web browser. 
</P>
<P>
	Nielsen Net Ratings, a New York-based research company that  
tracks the popularity of Internet sites, said Windows Update 
received more than 3.5 million visits last month, accounting for 
more than one-third the online traffic to all of Microsoft's 
corporate Web pages -- even though only customers with the latest 
version of Windows can access the site. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department also solicits comments from the public  
about the Microsoft trial, using an e-mail address published atop a 
Web page that includes links to its own court documents and trial 
evidence. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 17:30:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov. Bush Raises $15 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush has raised at least  
$15 million in his bid to capture the White House in 2000, his 
campaign spokesman, David Beckwith, said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The $15 million total is almost double the $7.6 million Bush had  
accrued as of April 1, more than any other Republican presidential 
hopeful. Candidates are scheduled to report July 15 how much money 
they have raised through June 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush has not held many fund-raisers, relying instead on a  
network of volunteers to raise money for him. 
</P>
<P>
	When he has held fund-raising events, he's kept the costs low.  
At a $1,000-a-head event in San Antonio last month he served 
peanuts and pretzels. Little white cardboard signs read: ``Texas 
money will be saved for Iowa and New Hampshire.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
