<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 20:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                        *Robert True Donnelly    	
</P>
<P>
	JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Robert True Donnelly, who served for  
nearly a quarter-century on the Missouri Supreme Court and twice 
led it as chief justice, died Wednesday after a long illness. He 
was 74. 
</P>
<P>
	Donnelly was appointed to the Missouri Supreme Court in 1965 by  
then-Gov. Warren E. Hearnes. He served 23 years on the court and 
wrote 546 opinions. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1974, Donnelly became the first chief justice to deliver a  
State of the Judiciary address to a joint session of the 
Legislature, now a yearly tradition. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1982, one of those addresses drew attention because Donnelly,  
as head of Missouri's judicial system, publicly questioned whether 
federal courts had reached too far in mandating social changes and 
overriding state legislatures and courts. 
</P>
<P>
	Donnelly published a book, ``A Whistle in the Night,'' in 1998.  
It recounted growing up in the Depression and his combat 
experiences in Germany during World War II. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Bernard D. Gress    	
</P>
<P>
	LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- Bernard D. Gress, a retired newspaperman  
and gambling aficionado, died Tuesday after an extended illness. He 
was 68. 
</P>
<P>
	He got into newspapers in 1960 as owner-publisher of Higgins  
News Publication Co. in Higgins, Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	He later became advertising salesman for the North Platte Daily  
Telegraph, then owner of North Platte-based Central Nebraska 
Publishing Co., from 1968 to 1975. That company published the 
Central Nebraska Farmer-Stockman newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, Gress wrote and published two books, ``Casino  
Oddities'' and ``Slots of Money,'' that became best sellers in the 
casino publishing industry. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Cardinal Basil Hume    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Cardinal Basil Hume, leader of the Roman Catholic  
Church of England and Wales and one of the most admired public 
figures in Britain, died Thursday. He was 76. 
</P>
<P>
	Hume held a position of remarkable influence and respect in  
Britain, where Catholics are a minority and the established church 
is Protestant. 
</P>
<P>
	Simple things like his moving prayers at the time of Princess  
Diana's death and his passionate support for the Newcastle United 
soccer team found him a place in many non-Catholic hearts. 
</P>
<P>
	A surprise choice as Roman Catholic Primate in 1976, he was  
abbot of Ampleforth Monastery and former head of its prestigious 
school, Ampleforth College. 
</P>
<P>
	After his selection as primate, in the space of just a few  
months, he was ordained a bishop, then Archbishop of Westminster 
and cardinal. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Harold Kohn    	
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Harold Kohn, an attorney who filed some of  
the earliest class-action lawsuits accusing corporations of 
price-fixing, died Monday. He was 85. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1960s, Kohn became nationally known by winning a key case  
against General Electric, Westinghouse and two dozen other 
companies that the federal government had accused of illegal 
price-fixing. 
</P>
<P>
	Kohn's case, brought on behalf of public utilities, was the  
first to go to trial and resulted in a $29 million verdict. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1981, a jury awarded his clients $2 billion in a class-action  
suit against the timber industry. At the time, it was the largest 
verdict ever in an antitrust case. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Emma Lowery Massey    	
</P>
<P>
	LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) -- Emma Lowery Massey, who may have been the  
oldest person in the world, died Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Although she never had the records to prove her age, friends  
said they believed she was 118. And the nursing home where she 
lived since 1990 recorded her birthdate as being Jan. 15, 1881. 
</P>
<P>
	Had Mrs. Massey been able to prove her age, she would have held  
the Guinness Book of World Records' distinction of being the 
world's oldest person. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Massey was known for her high spirits and love of gospel  
music as well as listening to Bible passages on tape. She had been 
blind for about a decade. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Cecil Morgan    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Cecil Morgan, a leader of the group of state  
legislators that impeached Gov. Huey P. Long in 1929, died Monday. 
He was 100. 
</P>
<P>
	Morgan and others started talking about impeachment after Long  
tried to impose a 5-cents-a-barrel tax on oil refined in Louisiana. 
</P>
<P>
	The group, dubbed ``the dynamite squad,'' accused Long of trying  
to arrange the murder of a political opponent, bribing lawmakers, 
carrying concealed weapons and demolishing the governor's mansion 
without authorization. 
</P>
<P>
	The House eventually voted to impeach Long on eight charges, but  
Long persuaded enough senators to sign a document promising to 
never impeach him. 
</P>
<P>
	Morgan left the Legislature in 1934 after being elected judge in  
Shreveport. Two years later, he joined Standard Oil in Shreveport 
as general counsel. 
</P>
<P>
	Morgan moved to Standard's corporate office in New York in 1954,  
taking the jobs of assistant to the chairman for public affairs and 
head of government relations. 
</P>
<P>
	He left Standard Oil in 1963 to become Tulane University's law  
school dean, a position he held for five years. 

</P>
<P>
                            *J.F. Powers    	
</P>
<P>
	COLLEGEVILLE, Minn. (AP) -- J.F. Powers, a celebrated Catholic  
writer and winner of the 1963 National Book Award for his novel 
``Morte D'Urban,'' died Monday. He was 81. 
</P>
<P>
	Powers wrote three collections of short fiction and a second  
novel in 1998, ``Wheat That Springeth Green,'' for which he was a 
National Book Award finalist. Both novels follow the careers of a 
Minnesota priest, and much of his writing dealt with the conflict 
between spiritual and secular values in a materialistic society. 
</P>
<P>
	Powers also contributed regularly to The New Yorker and received  
fellowships from the Rockefeller and Guggenheim foundations. 

</P>
<P>
                            *David Sutch    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- David Sutch, who brought a chuckle to British  
politics as leader of the Monster Raving Loony Party with the 
slogan: ``Vote for insanity -- you know it makes sense,'' was found 
hanged Wednesday in his home. He was 58. 
</P>
<P>
	Known as Screaming Lord Sutch, he was Britain's longest-serving  
party leader. He never won a race, despite running in scores of 
them, but one of his party members was once elected mayor in a town 
in southwest England. 
</P>
<P>
	Sutch, who legally changed his name to add the ``Lord,'' founded  
the Monster Raving Loony Party in 1963 and first ran for Parliament 
in 1964. He went on to enter some 40 elections over more than 30 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign style of Sutch and his followers irritated more  
traditional candidates but delighted many British voters. And at 
least one of his policies -- all-day pub openings -- later became a 
reality. 
</P>
<P>
	Sutch also was a rock singer and until recently performed up to  
250 concerts a year throughout Europe. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
