<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oregon Wants NRA Program in Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- When Eddie Eagle spies children stumbling  
onto a handgun in an attic, the cartoon hero swoops down, raises 
his wing and squawks: ``STOP! Don't touch! Leave the area! Tell an 
adult!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Oregon's Legislature this month passed a measure that would make  
the state the first to adopt the National Rifle Association's Eddie 
Eagle character -- in coloring books, videos and pamphlets -- as a 
mandatory part of the school curriculum. 
</P>
<P>
	But opponents who don't necessarily have a problem with the  
message are leery of the nation's largest gun lobbying group being 
the messenger. They are urging the governor to veto the bill and 
spare schoolchildren from what they see as ``the Joe Camel of the 
gun industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's inappropriate for a school to bring the NRA into the  
classroom to teach children about guns,'' said Democratic state 
Sen. Ginny Burdick. ``I've seen how the NRA has dealt with gun 
violence. They've opposed even the most basic laws to keep people 
safe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Oregon's Eddie Eagle bill was among a few gun measures that  
received extra attention in the wake of the Columbine High School 
massacre in Colorado. Said Republican Sen. Tom Hartung: ``We need 
to do everything possible to avert misuse of firearms.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What makes this measure unique is that it goes beyond simply  
calling for some kind of gun education in schools and picks the 
NRA's Eddie Eagle specifically as the mandatory program. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're thrilled,'' said Kathy Cassidy, the NRA's Eddie Eagle  
program manager. ``Other states teach the program, but they haven't 
mandated it. The Oregon Legislature is in the forefront.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some parents don't share that enthusiasm.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want my son learning about guns from the NRA,''  
Cynthia Nawalinski, parent of a Portland second-grader. ``I don't 
think that children should be talking about guns in school. Guns 
are in movies, on TV and the media all the time. I feel the more we 
talk about guns, the more the children will be attracted to guns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. John Kitzhaber has not indicated whether he will veto the  
bill but has said through a spokesman that he is not fond of school 
mandates of any kind and is also troubled by choosing the NRA's 
Eddie Eagle out of the hundreds of gun safety programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Developed in 1988, the Eddie Eagle program has by the NRA's  
estimate reached 12 million youngsters in schools across the 
country. The message, according to the NRA's literature, ``neither 
offers nor asks for any value judgment concerning firearms. ... 
Just as Smokey Bear teaches children not to play with matches, 
Eddie Eagle teaches them that firearms are not toys, and should not 
be touched without adult supervision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The program at no time involves the use of real guns, but  
coloring book exercises, rhymes and mini-dramatizations with a 
teacher in an Eddie Eagle costume to drive the message home to even 
preschoolers. 
</P>
<P>
	Traci Rees, a risk management specialist at the Sherwood School  
District near Portland, used Eddie Eagle in kindergarten through 
fourth grade this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had Eddie Eagle come dressed in costume -- a big full-body  
costume with the mask, fake fur,'' she said. ``The children loved 
it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
