<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Polish Bid Based on Olympic Ideals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ZAKOPANE, Poland (AP) -- Suffering from a dilapidated  
infrastructure and a lack of sports facilities, this faded resort 
is counting on a unique -- and iffy -- strategy to win the 2006 
Winter Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``If no other factors than the Olympic charter and Olympic  
ideals decide, then Zakopane is one of the strongest candidates,'' 
Mayor Adam Bachleda-Curus said. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers of the Polish bid will stress the country's new  
democracy and Zakopane's tradition as a major European skiing and 
tourism destination before World War II when they get 60 minutes to 
persuade the International Olympic Committee this week in Seoul. 
</P>
<P>
	The strategy is to deflect attention from problems, such as poor  
transportation links, that make Zakopane a decided underdog against 
five challengers, led by favorites Sion, Switzerland and Turin, 
Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	A vibrant community of 30,000 at the foot of the picturesque  
High Tatras, surrounded by rocky, snowcapped peaks and magnificent 
lakes, Zakopane needs a lot of modern amenities after decades of 
neglect during communist rule. 
</P>
<P>
	It lacks sufficient sports facilities and lodging, while its  
roads and rail links need upgrading. Bachleda-Curus and other bid 
officials acknowledge the weak points, but argue that winning the 
games would help Poland improve existing facilities and build new 
sports complexes in Zakopane, nearby Nowy Targ and the historical 
city of Krakow, 60 miles away. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC changed the bidding rules in March in response to the  
bribery scandal that rocked the Olympic movement. New regulations 
barred visits by IOC members to bid cities -- a practice linked to 
bribery in the past -- and focused the procedure on each city's 
60-minute presentation in Seoul. 
</P>
<P>
	Bachleda-Curus said Zakopane has prepared a film and an  
unspecified artistic performance, presenting Poland and the bid 
city while emphasizing how the Olympic Charter calls for spreading 
Olympic ideals throughout the world. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to show Poland's successes, the great achievements we  
can be proud of in the economy, culture and sports, to show that 
Poland is a country with a 1,000-year history, playing a big 
international role,'' Bachleda-Curus said. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrzej Bac, a senior campaign official, said the presentation  
will stress how Poland has changed since toppling communism 10 
years ago to become fully democratic, with one of Europe's 
fastest-growing economies. It belongs to NATO and is negotiating to 
join the European Union. 
</P>
<P>
	``This proves that all we presented in our project can be  
executed smoothly,'' Bac said. 
</P>
<P>
	An IOC evaluation report published in January praised Zakopane's  
sports plan, but stressed that sports, accommodation and transport 
facilities need upgrading. It also raised questions about financing 
and objections from environmentalists. 
</P>
<P>
	Bachleda-Curus said Zakopane reacted to the IOC report by moving  
the downhill skiing site to a new venue in Slovakia, just across 
the border. 
</P>
<P>
	The original site was at Kasprowy Wierch mountain in the Tatra  
National Park, designated a UNICEF nature reserve in 1992. 
Environmental groups and others criticized plans to cut down trees 
and make other changes to prepare the site for Olympic skiing. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the government has promised money for sports  
facilities, improved rail links and a better highway from Zakopane 
to Krakow, the Renaissance city where figure skating and hockey 
events would be held. 
</P>
<P>
	Famous for its carved wooden houses and locals -- known as  
highlanders -- wearing woolen embroidered clothes, Zakopane was a 
leading European winter resort before World War II, playing host to 
World Nordic Ski Championships in 1929 and 1939. Development 
stopped under communist rule, but new shops, restaurants and hotels 
have opened in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	International sports events also returned, including ski jumping  
World Cups at Wielka Krokiew hill, a rare natural ski jump. 
</P>
<P>
	The High Tatras would be a new location for the Olympics, a  
point emphasized when Bachleda-Curus argues that only nine 
countries have hosted the 20 Winter Olympics to date. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it continues like this, then we could agree to have  
Olympics in Innsbruck every four years,'' he said, referring to the 
Austrian town with a rich Olympic history. ``But that would be 
against the Olympic Charter.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
