<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Russia Move Toward Troop Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HELSINKI, Finland (AP) -- The United States and Russia struggled  
today to clinch an agreement giving Russia a peacekeeping role in 
Kosovo under NATO command. U.S. officials insisted Moscow not be 
given sole control over any part of the province. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have made quite clear there would not be a separate Russian  
sector,'' Secretary of State Madeleine Albright told reporters as 
she arrived at the presidential palace to greet Finnish President 
Martti Ahtisaari and join the negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials spoke optimistically of making substantial progress  
during the second day of talks. Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon, 
who sat in on the negotiations, told reporters the United States 
had given the Russians ``a very detailed proposal on the last major 
remaining issue'' and was awaiting a Russian reply. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's one of a number of proposals that has been traded back  
and forth,'' Bacon said, noting that ``differences have narrowed'' 
during the course of today's talks. He declined to identify the 
remaining obstacle, but other officials said it was U.S. and NATO 
resistance to Moscow's demand that its peacekeepers oversee a 
separate sector of Kosovo. NATO is resisting this out of fear it 
would partition Kosovo, a development that would undermine the 
allies' goal of permitting free movement of displaced ethnic 
Albanians throughout the province, where Serbs are a minority. 
</P>
<P>
	In Moscow, former Prime Minister Victor Chernomyrdin, who helped  
broker the Kosovo peace deal, told a news conference that serious 
differences remained, although he was not directly involved in the 
talks. ``We left no doubt that the Russian contingent will never be 
subordinate to NATO commanders,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Heading the negotiations in Helsinki were Defense Secretary  
William Cohen and Russian Defense Minister Marshall Igor Sergeyev, 
joined later by Albright and Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen told reporters as he left the negotiations for an  
afternoon stroll along the city's sun-splashed inner harbor that 
``creative arrangements'' were being pursued to resolve remaining 
disputes, but he refused to discuss any details. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have not resolved all the remaining issues,'' Cohen said.  
``There can be no agreement until everything is agreed upon. 
Everything we have now is only tentative in nature.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sergeyev said today's session started by summarizing the  
progress made in Wednesday's negotiations, which lasted past 
midnight, then focus on the remaining disagreements. 
</P>
<P>
	``We shall try to do it today,'' Sergeyev said. Cohen said the  
talks could stretch into Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	President Boris Yeltsin said today that Russia won't back down  
on its demand that Russian peacekeeping troops in Kosovo control 
their own sector and he relayed that stance when he spoke by 
telephone from Moscow with Sergeyev. 
</P>
<P>
	``In principle, most of the issues have been resolved  
peacefully,'' Yeltsin said in comments broadcast on television. 
``But one question, which I would undoubtedly call the principal 
one, is sectors. In other words, they don't want to give Russia a 
sector.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the snag, President Clinton predicted a ``successful  
conclusion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The atmosphere is pretty positive and pretty hopeful,''  
Clinton told reporters on the lawn of Elysee Palace after a meeting 
with French President Jacques Chirac. ``I hope and believe they 
will reach a successful conclusion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, Clinton said the NATO allies would not abandon  
their insistence that all peacekeeping forces in Kosovo -- Russian 
or otherwise -- operate under a single command. The Russians have 
insisted that their troops not come under a NATO commander. 
</P>
<P>
	One approach being pursued is to assign the Russians their own  
``zone of responsibility,'' but to place it within one of the 
already established ``sectors'' overseen by one of five NATO 
countries -- the United States, Britain, France, Germany and Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	The talks at the presidential palace appeared to have produced a  
preliminary understanding on joint use of the airport at Pristina, 
where about 200 Russian troops have been holed up since their 
surprise arrival Saturday ahead of NATO peacekeepers. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen, asked whether he foresaw a final deal today, replied,  
``We hope so, but there are issues that remain to be resolved.'' 
Later, he told reporters the talks could drag on until Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen said that if a U.S.-Russian accord were reached in  
Helsinki, he would recommend its approval by NATO officials. He was 
due to travel to NATO headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, on Friday, 
and then visit U.S. troops in the Balkans. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
