<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Amtrak: Good Service or Free Travel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Amtrak is offering a deal it hopes few  
travelers can resist: Get good service or a free ride. 
</P>
<P>
	The national passenger rail company announced its service pledge  
Thursday as part on an effort to capture traffic from airplanes and 
autos. The pledge came on the same day airline companies announced 
voluntary steps to address growing complaints from passengers. 
</P>
<P>
	Amtrak, which must wean itself from federal operating subsidies  
by 2003, hopes its planned service improvements -- such as flowers 
in bathrooms and entertainment for children -- will boost revenues 
by $85 million over three years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Long-term success here has to do with doing it right, getting  
it right and increasing market share,'' said George Warrington, 
Amtrak's president and chief executive. ``The only way we can do it 
is to ensure a consistent set of standards.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Central to winning customers' confidence is Amtrak's new pledge:  
Amtrak will offer dissatisfied passengers a refund voucher good for 
future travel. 
</P>
<P>
	That guarantee will take effect later this year, after the  
railroad completes other service initiatives, including training 
and incentives for all 24,000 employees, enhanced food-service 
options and improved onboard amenities. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's major airlines are trying to negotiate voluntary  
protections to stave off passenger-rights directives from Congress. 
Among the improvements announced Thursday were plans to tell 
customers the lowest available ticket price and handle bumped 
passengers with fairness. 
</P>
<P>
	Amtrak spokesman John Wolf estimated that only one out of every  
1,000 passengers will request a refund voucher. Amtrak is offering 
vouchers, instead of refunds on the current trip, to give itself a 
second chance to woo the customer. 
</P>
<P>
	Amtrak still faces hurdles, such as limited routes and  
schedules, in becoming a true alternative to airlines. But Wolf 
said the guarantees should help the railroad set itself apart from 
other travel modes. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, Amtrak announced a high-speed service to lure  
travelers who now fly the lucrative Washington-New York-Boston 
shuttle route. 
</P>
<P>
	Amtrak also is developing other high-speed rail corridors  
elsewhere, including one linking Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, Michigan, 
Minnesota, Missouri, Nebraska, Ohio, and Wisconsin. 
</P>
<P>
	Amtrak passenger revenues exceeded $1 billion for the first time  
ever last year, with 21 million customers riding by rail. Amtrak 
said it had the best on-time performance in 13 years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 10:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kellogg May Close Part of Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BATTLE CREEK, Mich. (AP) -- The nation's largest cereal maker  
announced today it is considering closing part of its historic 
Battle Creek cereal plant and eliminating up to 64 percent of the 
jobs at the facility. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the proposal, up to 700 of the current 1,100 jobs at the  
Kellogg Co. plant would be eliminated as early as the first quarter 
of 2000, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Streamlining our operations and avoiding future costs would  
help keep our North American cereal business cost-competitive going 
into the 21st century,'' new chief executive Carlos M. Gutierrez 
said in a written statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The news comes seven months after Kellogg cut 525 jobs -- 21  
percent of its salaried workforce -- as part of a reorganization of 
its North American operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's announcement is part of ``an ongoing thing with  
Kellogg,'' said analyst Christopher Jakubik of Warburg Dillon Read 
in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Kellogg has regained some of its sales volume recently but  
continues to find itself in a very tough business environment, 
Jakubik said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You still have too many players,'' he said. ``There's still  
very limited growth in the category.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Kellogg was off 50  
cents a share at $33.50 by early afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	Kellogg will not say what percentage of its overall production  
comes from its Battle Creek plant, which makes Kellogg's Corn 
Flakes. It now is Kellogg's largest plant in North America, but 
would drop to third if the cuts are made. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Battle Creek-based cereal maker decides to close part of  
the plant, the company said some of the operations would be 
relocated to other Kellogg North America cereal plants for an 
estimated annual savings of $35 million to $45 million. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the 700 jobs that would be cut would not be replaced at  
other plants, Joseph Stewart, Kellogg's executive vice president of 
communications, said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Parts of plant date back to 1907, the year after the Kellogg Co.  
made Battle Creek its headquarters, and the company cannot afford 
to keep it running because it's so inefficient, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The plant was at one time a major tourist attraction. An  
estimated 175,000 people visited it each year before the tours 
ended in the mid-1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, a nonprofit group opened Cereal City USA in downtown  
Battle Creek. The company contributed millions to help build the 
attraction, which features exhibits on cereal history, a simulated 
cereal production line and a show featuring the characters used in 
Kellogg's advertising. 
</P>
<P>
	Kellogg will make a final decision about the closure after  
discussions with the union that represents the plant's hourly 
workers. The company met will all employees this morning 30 minutes 
before making its announcement to reporters gathered for a news 
conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Gutierrez said in April that although Battle Creek produces a  
lot of cereal, the plant would have to remain competitive and 
continue to improve its productivity. 
</P>
<P>
	And analysts have previously said Kellogg needs to do more if it  
is to regain its shrinking market share. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, Kellogg reported a 30 percent drop in first-quarter  
earnings, but the cereal maker pointed to an increase in sales as 
an indicator of future growth. 
</P>
<P>
	The results were in line with Wall Street estimates.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
