<DOCNO> APW19990617.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 08:44:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  War Crimes Evidence Is Studied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- U.N. war crimes investigators are studying what  
appears to be a Serb-run torture center in the Kosovo capital of 
Pristina, the Foreign Office said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign Office Minister Geoff Hoon also said NATO now fears Serb  
soldiers and special police may have killed 10,000 of Kosovo's 
Albanian majority in more than 100 massacres as part of their 
campaign to ethnically cleanse the province. 
</P>
<P>
	Briefing reporters, Hoon said British paratroopers have sealed  
off a five-story concrete building that was the headquarters of 
departing Serb military police in Pristina where torture is 
reported to have taken place. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoon said British forces have found knives, rubber and wooden  
batons, baseball bats ``with Serb slogans carved into them,'' a 
wooden crate full of brass knuckles, and ``savage pornography and 
drugs, presumably used to sedate victims.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Journalists taken to the building reported that one room, where  
Kosovar Albanian women were allegedly raped, contained boxes of 
condoms. 
</P>
<P>
	The most chilling aspect, said Hoon, is that the building ``does  
not appear to have been a special holding center for the Serbs' 
victims. It seems to have been just an ordinary police 
headquarters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``In other words, the barbaric acts carried out in this building  
were probably almost a matter of routine. We can expect similar 
discoveries elsewhere.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hoon said that outside the building ``there is a trail of  
charred paper leading to an incinerator,'' apparently indicating 
that the Serbs tried to burn evidence of their alleged crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoon said the further NATO peacekeeping forces penetrate as they  
move into Kosovo following last week's peace deal that ended the 
allies' 78-day air campaign, the higher they put the death toll. 
</P>
<P>
	``According to the reports we had gathered, mostly from the  
refugees, it appeared that around 10,000 people had been killed in 
more than 100 massacres,'' he said. ``The final total may be much 
worse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, Glasgow's Daily Record newspaper said two of its  
journalists and their Albanian interpreter were injured when gunmen 
fired at their car near the southern village of Stimjle. 
</P>
<P>
	The Daily Record said reporter Simon Houston, 30, suffered a  
grazed head and an injured arm and photographer Chris Watt, 29, who 
was driving, was also grazed by a bullet Wednesday night. 
Interpreter Xherdet Shabani was shot in the shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	The men were treated at the British army camp at Stimjle.  
</P>
<P>
	It was not immediately clear who was responsible, but the  
newspaper said a rebel wing of the Kosovo Liberation Army may have 
mistaken the journalists for Serbs fleeing the province ahead of 
NATO troops. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, two journalists from the German newsweekly Stern were  
shot to death as they drove near Dulje. Their interpreter was found 
dead nearby. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 08:44:47 </DATE_TIME>
