<HEADLINE> Said Captures Pole for Grainer 225 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Road racing expert Boris Said, making his  
first start this year in the NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series, won the 
pole position for Friday's Grainger 225 race at Portland 
International Raceway. 
</P>
<P>
	A regular on the tour until his team, co-owned by NASCAR Winston  
Cup Series competitor Ernie Irvan, elected to cut back its 
schedule, Said drove his Ford around the 1.95-mile road course 
Thursday at a speed of 91.144 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	The lap was two-tenths of a second quicker than the 90.824  
posted by Ron Fellows' Chevrolet. 
</P>
<P>
	Fellows, who won a series race at Watkins Glen, N.Y., in 1997,  
also is making his first start of the season. He is making his 
debut in a team co-owned by Winston Cup driver Joe Nemechek. 
</P>
<P>
	Stacy Compton, qualified third in a Dodge at 90.551 mph.  
Starting alongside Compton in the second row will be point leader 
Jack Sprague, whose Chevrolet turned in a lap of 90.548 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifth will be Dennis Setzer, also in a Dodge, at 90.403, with  
Mike Wallace, Greg Biffle, Terry Cook, Ron Hornaday and Mike Bliss 
qualifying sixth through 10th. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty-two drivers qualified for the 73-lap, 142.35-mile race.  
The series' first event at Portland International Raceway, which is 
being run in conjunction with CART's FedEx Championship Series, 
carries posted awards of $393,090. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
