<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Despite Pleas, Texas Kills Canadian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) -- This time, there was no last-minute  
reprieve to keep Joseph Faulder from becoming the first Canadian to 
be executed in the United States in almost a half-century. 
</P>
<P>
	Faulder, 61, avoided the Texas death chamber last December when  
the U.S. Supreme Court issued a reprieve 30 minutes before he was 
to be executed. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday evening, after losing a flurry of legal challenges  
that included support from the Canadian government and Secretary of 
State Madeleine Albright, the former auto mechanic was executed by 
injection for killing a 75-year-old Texas woman. 
</P>
<P>
	``No statements,'' he replied when asked if he had anything to  
say. Six minutes later, he was pronounced dead. 
</P>
<P>
	Faulder didn't deny killing Inez Phillips, but his attorneys  
argued his conviction for the beating and stabbing death was 
tainted because he never was told after his arrest that he could 
seek legal help from Canadian authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	The right is specified under terms of the Vienna Convention on  
Consular Relations, a treaty signed by both the United States and 
Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	``These issues remain important ones for all Canadians who live,  
work and visit outside of Canada,'' said John Morrow, the 
Dallas-based Canadian consul. ``We deeply regret our request for 
executive clemency was not acted on, but the government of Texas 
has its laws and we respect that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the State Department, a spokesman aid officials tried a  
variety of appeals, including personal pleas from the Secretary of 
State. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas authorities said Faulder did nothing to inform them he was  
Canadian. He was carrying a Colorado driver's license and had 
applied for one in Texas. It wasn't until 15 years after his arrest 
that his family, who believed he was dead, and the Canadian 
government discovered he was alive. 
</P>
<P>
	Faulder's case attracted wide attention in Canada, a country  
that outlawed capital punishment in 1976. The last execution of a 
Canadian in the United States was in the early 1950s. 
</P>
<P>
	He was being held in Colorado in 1977 on unrelated charges when  
he was accused of murdering Mrs. Phillips during a burglary at her 
home in Gladewater, about 115 miles east of Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	A maid found Mrs. Phillips' body with a 6 1/2-inch butcher knife  
embedded in her chest. Faulder's girlfriend, who had accompanied 
him to the house, testified against him. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 11:50:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tour de Suisse Boots Four Cyclists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KUESSNACHT AM RIGI, Switzerland (AP) -- Four cyclists were thrown  
out of the Tour de Suisse on Thursday when they flunked a pre-race 
drug test. 
</P>
<P>
	The four showed abnormal levels of red blood cells in tests  
given all 147 riders by the International Cycling Union before the 
race. 
</P>
<P>
	Sergei Gontchar of Ukraine was banned for having a level of red  
blood cells above 50 percent. Also bounced from the race were 
Austrian Harald Morscher, Italian Massimo Gimondi and Timothy Jones 
of Zimbabwe. 
</P>
<P>
	Italian Silvio Martinello won Thursday's third stage of the  
Swiss race. The 36-year-old was only inches ahead of his countryman 
Mario Traversoni and Swiss rider Markus Zberg at the end of the 
137-mile stage from Lausanne. 
</P>
<P>
	Frenchman Laurent Jalabert held on to the overall lead .  
</P>
<P>
	A high level of red blood cells is an indicator that a rider may  
have been using the banned hormone EPO. The drug allows more oxygen 
to get into the bloodstream, increasing athletic endurance. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the levels can also occur naturally and there is no  
accepted test for the drug. The UCI introduced the 15-day enforced 
rest periods in 1997 because of the danger to riders' health from 
high levels of red blood cells. 
</P>
<P>
	Doping has been a major issue in cycling.  
</P>
<P>
	Tour de France champion Marco Pantani was thrown out of the Tour  
of Italy a day before he would have won the race when his red cell 
count was abnormally high. 
</P>
<P>
	Drug use by the competitors plagued last year's Tour de France  
and resulted in several ejections. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 16:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bar Accused of Hiring Discrimination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Preferring an Irish brogue to a heavy ``Bahstahn''  
accent for its Irish theme restaurant, a Hilton hotel has turned 
history upside down by allegedly saying only Irish need apply, 
provoking three waitresses to file a discrimination complaint. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last three decades, Gloria DiMartino, Dorothy Webb, and  
Jo Murray have worked at the Logan Airport Ramada, trying hard to 
calm anxious travelers and being happy to entertain a common 
request from tourists. 
</P>
<P>
	``They all want to hear us say 'Pahk the cah in Hahvahd Yahd and  
chowdah,''' said Murray, a 71-year-old waitress and one of three 
who filed a complaint against Beverly Hills, Calif.-based Hilton 
Hotels Corp., which took over management of the Airport Ramada in 
1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't care if they hire students from Ireland, but we  
should have first preference for those jobs,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	In September the Hilton plans to open a new hotel and Kitty  
O'Shea's, an Irish theme bar. But the veteran waitresses say 
they're being pushed out of their old jobs by management's decision 
to recruit Irish natives to work in the pub -- a historical reversal 
from the start of the century when signs hung in Boston 
entranceways that read ``Irish Need Not Apply.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, the hotel chain said Thursday: ``Hilton has  
acted and will continue to act consistent with its collective 
bargaining agreement ... and applicable law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hilton spokeswoman Kathy Shepard refused to comment further.  
</P>
<P>
	The waitresses said the hotel is violating a collective  
bargaining contract that states employees with seniority have first 
preference for jobs in the new hotel, restaurant and pub. The women 
also said managers made it clear in a May staff meeting that first 
preference for Kitty O'Shea jobs would be given to employees with 
an Irish accent. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're trying to push us out. And why? Because we don't speak  
with an Irish accent,'' said DiMartino, 55. ``It's discrimination, 
pure and simple.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The women have filed a complaint with the Massachusetts  
Commission Against Discrimination and plan to stage protests if the 
hotel doesn't give them first choice of jobs in its planned 
restaurants and bars. 
</P>
<P>
	Managers at another Kitty O'Shea's pub -- unrelated to the  
planned airport pub -- say they hire qualified people, whether they 
have accents or not. 
</P>
<P>
	Denise McCool, a spokeswoman for the Irish Immigration Center in  
Boston, said Irish restaurants would better serve their patrons by 
teaching them about Irish history rather than focus on the staff's 
accents. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not the accent that makes a culture,'' McCool said. ``I  
wonder how many people know who Kitty O'Shea was because if they 
did they would know that she didn't stand for exclusion or 
discrimination.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kitty O'Shea was a married woman whose relationship with Irish  
nationalist leader Charles Stewart Parnell led to a scandal that 
ended Parnell's career and divided Irish public opinion. Parnell 
married O'Shea after her divorce. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 15:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lamar Odom Wants To Return to School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- Deciding he's not ready for the pros  
after all, Lamar Odom wants to return for another season at Rhode 
Island, university officials said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He'd like to return to URI next season to play basketball. But  
we have to iron out some legalities,'' said John Vanner, Rhode 
Island's assistant athletic director. 
</P>
<P>
	Those legalities are thorny ones.  
</P>
<P>
	Odom, who dropped out after his sophomore year, signed with Jeff  
Klein, an agent based in New York City. Under NCAA rules, anyone 
who signs with an agent is barred from returning to college play. 
Klein said he resigned as Odom's agent Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	But that break does not clear Odom, said Bill Saum, the NCAA's  
director of agent and gambling activities. 
</P>
<P>
	``Signing a contract with an agent is significant,'' Saum told  
The Providence Journal. But he kept the door open, saying that if 
``there are mitigating circumstances, they are examined.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The university is helping Odom prepare a long-shot appeal with  
the NCAA in an attempt to revive his collegiate eligibility. 
</P>
<P>
	It is unclear what arguments Rhode Island would use to justify a  
waiver. But Vanner made it clear that he believes Odom needs more 
time to mature, and that the best place to do it is in college. 
</P>
<P>
	``He needs another year to learn the world,'' said Vanner.  
</P>
<P>
	Rhode Island may also need Odom for another year. The 6-foot-10  
forward led Rhode Island in scoring (17.6) and rebounding (9.4) 
last season. He hit a 25-footer at the buzzer to help Rhode Island 
defeat Temple in the Atlantic 10 championship game. 
</P>
<P>
	Odom announced a month ago that he was turning pro, much to  
Rhode Island's disappointment. But his commitment to moving up to 
the pros first came into doubt over the weekend, when he skipped a 
league-wide physical. He later missed a workout with the Charlotte 
Hornets. On Thursday, he did not show up for a workout with the 
Chicago Bulls. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if the NCAA disregards Odom's contract with Klein, his  
academics may be an issue. He disappeared from campus for days at a 
time last semester, even during exams. University officials said 
Odom's grades are a private matter. 
</P>
<P>
	Vanner said he believes Odom was turned off by what he found out  
about the hustle and bustle of professional basketball in recent 
weeks, when he was courted not just by teams but also by companies 
eager for him to endorse products. 
</P>
<P>
	``During his time away, he realized he was just a piece of  
property,'' said Vanner. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 23:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
