<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SLA Fugitive Appears in Minn. Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- Sara Jane Olson waved to her family today  
as she was in court to face accusations she is really Symbionese 
Liberation Army fugitive Kathleen Ann Soliah. 
</P>
<P>
	Her attorney, Howard Bass, did not acknowledge that Olson and  
Ms. Soliah were the same person. But he argued that the crimes Ms. 
Soliah are charged with in California are not punishable by death 
or life in prison, and that bail should be set for his client. 
</P>
<P>
	``And those are only regarding the allegations against Kathleen  
Soliah. I haven't even addressed the issues with Sara Olson,'' Bass 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramsey County District Judge Kathleen Gearin said she could not  
decide on setting bail until she studied the California statutes. 
</P>
<P>
	County Attorney Susan Gaertner said California authorities were  
seeking extradition within 30 days. Olson did not waive her right 
to challenge the extradition request. Her next court appearance was 
set for July 15. 
</P>
<P>
	Dressed in an orange jail jumpsuit, Olson did not speak, but  
smiled and waved to her husband and three daughters. 
</P>
<P>
	Olson, 52, who lived with her doctor husband in an ivy-covered  
home in an upscale neighborhood, was active in community theater 
work, where her acting drew notice from local reviewers. 
</P>
<P>
	One singled her out as the strongest performer in a 1990  
production of ``King Lear.'' Another praised her ``vibrant'' 1993 
performance in ``All's Well That Ends Well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But if the FBI is right, she is really Ms. Soliah, a onetime  
member of the SLA, the band of 1970s radicals who kidnapped 
Patricia Hearst. 
</P>
<P>
	Agents arrested the fugitive Wednesday after receiving tips from  
viewers of ``America's Most Wanted,'' which featured her in a 
recent broadcast. The FBI offered a $20,000 reward for Ms. Soliah 
last month, on the 25th anniversary of a Los Angeles shootout that 
killed six SLA members. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Soliah has been wanted since 1976, when she was indicted in  
Los Angeles on murder conspiracy and explosives charges for 
allegedly placing pipe bombs under two police cars. The bombs did 
not explode. 
</P>
<P>
	In a federal warrant drawn up this year, authorities said that  
in 1984 her husband was aware of her true name and fugitive status. 
It was unclear whether she was married at the time to her current 
husband, Gerald Peterson. They bought their St. Paul house in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Peterson said neither he nor his children had any inkling of his  
wife's double life. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know nothing about that,'' he told the Los Angeles Times.  
``I'll tell you the truth, I'm totally shocked.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No one at the house would comment Wednesday. But Ms. Soliah's  
parents, Martin and Elsie Soliah of Palmdale, Calif., said Peterson 
knew his wife was wanted. 
</P>
<P>
	``She told him about her situation when they got serious,'' Mrs.  
Soliah told the Times. ``He understood.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sometime in the late 1970s, Ms. Soliah arrived in the  
Minneapolis area, where she moved next door to Peterson, then a 
medical intern. Mrs. Soliah said the two lived for a number of 
years in Zimbabwe, where Peterson worked as a physician and her 
daughter taught drama and English. There, her daughter gave birth 
to the second of their three daughters. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Soliah and her husband returned to the United States in the  
mid-1980s, the Soliahs said, settling in Minnesota after a brief 
stay in Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI said she took the last name of Olson, which is common in  
Minnesota because of the large number of people of Scandinavian 
descent. 
</P>
<P>
	Detectives described Ms. Soliah as being surprised by her arrest  
-- and relieved at the same time. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got a pretty good fingerprint identification that she's  
the person we're looking for,'' said James Burrus Jr., the agent in 
charge of the Minneapolis FBI office. 
</P>
<P>
	Her capture closes a chapter in one of the most sensational news  
stories of the 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	The SLA, a band of anti-government radicals with a seven-headed  
snake as their symbol, kidnapped Ms. Hearst from her Berkeley, 
Calif., apartment in February 1974. She was 19. 
</P>
<P>
	The group demanded that the newspaper heiress' parents, Randolph  
and Catherine Hearst, distribute $2 million worth of food to the 
needy before it would discuss freedom for their daughter. The 
demand later climbed to $6 million. 
</P>
<P>
	But then Ms. Hearst changed into Tania, a member of the group  
that took her prisoner. Two months after the kidnapping, she was 
photographed carrying a carbine during an SLA holdup of a San 
Francisco bank -- the robbery for which she eventually was convicted 
and sent to prison. 
</P>
<P>
	In May 1974, as people across the nation watched on live TV, Los  
Angeles police trapped heavily armed SLA members in a house and 
riddled it with bullets. The group's leader, an ex-convict who 
called himself Cinque, and five other SLA members died. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Soliah did not participate in the shootout or the Hearst  
kidnapping. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Hearst went underground and didn't emerge until 1975, when  
she was arrested in San Francisco. Although she claimed she was the 
victim of brainwashing, she was sentenced to seven years for the 
bank robbery. She served two years before President Carter commuted 
her sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, she is a married mother living in Connecticut, and a  
sometime actress and author. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is all so old,'' she told WCBS-AM. ``I don't want to be  
drawn into all of this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At least one other former SLA member is still at large: James  
Kilgore, Ms. Soliah's boyfriend in her SLA days. He was profiled on 
the same ``America's Most Wanted'' show as Ms. Soliah, but FBI 
spokeswoman Coleen Rowley said she wasn't aware of any leads on 
Kilgore. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 18:40:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Logistical Problems in Fugitive Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- With the apparent capture of radical Kathleen  
Ann Soliah, prosecutors face the challenge of trying a 25-year-old 
case in which jurors might ask, ``What was the Symbionese 
Liberation Army anyway?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Soliah, now 52, could be sentenced to life in prison if  
convicted, but legal experts said witnesses' faded memories and the 
easing of any public outrage could lead to a plea bargain. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have successfully prosecuted cases older than this one,''  
said Sandi Gibbons, a spokeswoman for the district attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	But she declined to say what evidence remains against Ms.  
Soliah, who allegedly placed two pipe bombs under two police cars 
in 1975 and then made a new life for herself in Minnesota as Sara 
Jane Olson, an actress, a doctor's wife and mother of three before 
she was captured on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	She was ordered held without bail in Minnesota on Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	``If she has lived an exemplary life, there will be sympathy,''  
said Laurie Levenson, associate dean at Loyola University Law 
School. ``No one is going to applaud her actions, but it is harder 
to prosecute a person who lives like the lady next door.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other legal experts also said Ms. Soliah's chances depend on how  
much physical evidence links her to the two pipe bombs, which did 
not explode. 
</P>
<P>
	A grand jury that indicted Ms. Soliah in 1976 heard from 28  
witnesses, including a police bomb expert who has since died. It is 
unknown how many witnesses remain alive. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it's a physical evidence case it's easier,'' said San  
Francisco lawyer Stuart Hanlon, who has represented other SLA 
members. ``If it's a witness case, it's almost impossible to try it 
25 years later.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Soliah's lawyer, Howard Bass, told reporters on Thursday  
that his client would fight extradition ``because at this time 
there is no evidence that leads us to believe that Sara Olson is 
the person that California wants extradited.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bass also did not say during court proceedings that Soliah and  
Sara Olson are the same person. 
</P>
<P>
	FBI officials say Soliah used ``Sara Olson'' as her alias.  
Spokeswoman Coleen Rowley said a fingerprint analysis concluded the 
Olson and Soliah are the same person. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fingerprints don't lie and the fingerprints do match,''  
Rowley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bass did not return telephone messages left at his office  
Thursday and was not in his office after the arraignment. 
</P>
<P>
	Other 1960s and '70s radicals who spent years as fugitives have  
received light treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	Bernadine Dohrn, an alleged conspirator in bombings by the  
Weather Underground, was allowed to plead guilty to lesser counts 
and drew probation. Silas Trim Bissell, another group member, spent 
17 years in hiding after he was charged with trying to bomb a 
University of Washington ROTC building in 1970. He served 17 months 
in a federal halfway house. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the tougher sentences went to Katherine Ann Power, an  
antiwar radical implicated in a fatal bank robbery in Boston in 
1970. She took an alias and settled in Oregon, where she taught, 
worked as a chef, married and had a son. She surrendered in 1993 
and pleaded guilty to manslaughter. With continued good behavior in 
prison, she could be out in January. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1974, the SLA became front-page news when the radicals  
kidnapped newspaper heiress Patty Hearst. The case took a bizarre 
twist when Ms. Hearst sent word that she had become Tania, a member 
of the group that abducted her. 
</P>
<P>
	Two months after the kidnapping, she was photographed carrying a  
carbine during an SLA holdup of a San Francisco bank -- the robbery 
for which she eventually was convicted and sent to prison. 
</P>
<P>
	A 1974 police shootout in Los Angeles killed six SLA members.  
When pipe bombs were found under two police cars in Los Angeles in 
1975, police traced them to Ms. Soliah and her then-boyfriend, 
James Kilgore, and assumed the attempted bombings were revenge for 
the shootout. 
</P>
<P>
	When Ms. Hearst was arrested in San Francisco in 1975, she was  
living with Ms. Soliah and her brother, Steven. 
</P>
<P>
	At her arraignment Thursday in St. Paul, Minn., Ms. Soliah,  
wearing an orange prison uniform, waved and blew a kiss to her 
family. Two of her three daughters were sobbing. Her husband, 
Gerald Peterson, put his arm around the youngest to comfort her. 
</P>
<P>
	Her lawyer, Howard Bass, argued that she should be granted bail,  
but no ruling was made and another hearing was set for July 15. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
