<DOCNO> APW19990617.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 15:40:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Toyota, Ford Plants Most Productive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Car assembly plants operated by Toyota in  
Cambridge, Ontario, and Ford in Atlanta and Chicago were the most 
productive in North America last year, ousting the Nissan plant in 
Tennessee from the top spot it held for the previous five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Among light truck plants, Ford's Louisville, Ky., factory also  
edged Nissan's Smyrna, Tenn., plant in the annual productivity 
rankings released Thursday by Harbour and Associates Inc. The 
Nissan plant last year produced Altima sedans and Frontier pickup 
trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	Harbour ranks plant productivity by the average number of labor  
hours it takes to build each vehicle. The Cambridge plant, which 
makes the Toyota Corolla sedan, ranked first at 17.66 hours, 
followed by Ford's plants that make the Taurus and Mercury Sable: 
Atlanta at 17.72 hours, and Chicago at 18.09. Nissan's plant ranked 
fourth at 18.97 hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford's Louisville plant, which makes the Ranger pickup and  
Explorer and Mercury Mountaineer sport utility vehicles, ranked 
first among truck plants at 19.29 hours, followed by the Nissan 
plant at 19.77 and the GM-Toyota joint venture plant in Fremont, 
Calif., which makes the Toyota Tacoma pickup, at 19.81. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nissan plant cut production by about 25 percent last year to  
reduce inventories of unsold cars, but did not lay off any workers, 
which lowered its productivity rankings. It also shifted production 
of the Sentra sedan to Mexico. Production is expected to increase 
this year with the recent addition of the Xterra SUV, Nissan 
spokesman Fred Standish said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ron Harbour, president of the consulting firm, said Smyrna was  
``still a very good plant'' in 1998, ``so the performances by 
Toyota and Ford were truly remarkable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When all North American assembly plants for each company were  
considered, the Japanese ``transplant'' automakers still remained 
well ahead of their Detroit competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan was on top at an average of 19.20 hours per vehicle,  
followed by Honda at 21.41, Toyota at 21.63, Ford at 23.87, General 
Motors at 31.58, and DaimlerChrysler at 32.33. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese automakers look better in the corporate average  
rankings partly because they have far fewer North American plants 
that tend to be more modern, while the Detroit automakers have 
dozens of plants, some far more efficient than others. 
</P>
<P>
	Harbour noted that some operations, such as Ford's Taurus-Sable  
plants, have adopted lean manufacturing techniques that make them 
competitive with the best of the newer Japanese plants. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem is the consistency across the company still isn't  
there, so there still is a gap'' between Ford and the Japanese 
plants, Harbour said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford is well ahead of GM and DaimlerChrysler AG, in large part  
because it relies far less on unscheduled overtime to meet demand. 
Unscheduled overtime for such things as plant maintenance and 
repair of vehicles on the line can dramatically lower the 
productivity rankings, Harbour said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to give Ford credit in the discipline that they've  
had to meet their build schedule on straight time. It's really 
giving Ford a significant advantage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	GM and DaimlerChrysler assembly plants require more than 50  
percent more labor hours than Nissan and 30 percent more than Ford, 
Harbour said. 
</P>
<P>
	Harbour estimates that if all of GM's North American plants --  
assembly, stamping and powertrain -- were as efficient as those 
operated by Toyota, it would need 40,041 fewer workers and save 
$4.9 billion a year. DaimlerChrysler would need 21,442 fewer 
workers and could save $2.7 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Productivity does not always equal profitability, however.  
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler was the most profitable major automaker on a  
worldwide basis last year, earning an average of $1,470 for each 
vehicle made, including Mercedes-Benz vehicles. Toyota was next at 
$1,348 a vehicle, followed by Honda at $993, Ford at $854 and GM at 
$317. Struggling Nissan lost $66 a vehicle. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 02:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sabres, Stars Serve Up Cup Thrills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- At last, there's a competitive series in the  
Stanley Cup finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Tied 2-2 going into Game 5 tonight, the Buffalo Sabres and  
Dallas Stars have made it the best championship round in many 
years. The previous four seasons ended with 4-0 sweeps in the 
finals. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is as tight a matchup as you'll find,'' Stars forward  
Brian Skrudland said. ``Both teams deserve a lot of credit for 
where they are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not since the New York Rangers and Vancouver Canucks went seven  
games in 1994 has there been a Stanley Cup final that has lasted 
more than four. The New Jersey Devils, Colorado Avalanche and 
Detroit Red Wings (twice) have all swept the finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the best-of-7 format began in 1939, only 10 finals have  
gone the limit. But no one is betting that this one won't go right 
down to the end. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars and Sabres have each split games in each other's  
arena, and the teams have been tied or had a one-goal difference 
for all but 26 seconds of the first four games. 
</P>
<P>
	Both teams feature a defensive style that has resulted in  
low-scoring games. Their 17 combined goals (Stars 9, Sabres 8) are 
the lowest four-game total in Stanley Cup finals history since the 
Montreal Canadiens outscored the St. Louis Blues 12-3 in 1969. 
</P>
<P>
	The last game of the Stars-Sabres series was typical, the Sabres  
winning 2-1 at Buffalo. The Sabres are 8-1 in one-goal games, and 
the Stars are 7-6 in this year's playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both of these goaltenders are playing so great,'' said Stars  
defenseman Craig Ludwig, referring to Dallas' Ed Belfour and 
Buffalo's Dominik Hasek. ``One break here or there makes a 
difference.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek has the better stats between the two, having allowed only  
eight goals on 127 shots, but Belfour was the more spectacular in 
Tuesday night's victory for Buffalo. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just see this as two really competitive teams trying to  
win,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``(Stars general manager) 
Bob Gainey said to us last night on the airplane this is such a 
great series. You've got two teams with so much passion and 
character going at it. It's so good for the game of hockey.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With their victory on Tuesday night, the Sabres cast an entirely  
new light on this series. A Stars victory in Game 4 would have 
given them a 3-1 lead in the best-of-7 finals, making it a tough 
job for the Sabres to win. 
</P>
<P>
	Only one team since 1939 has come back to win the Cup after  
losing three of the first four games -- the 1942 Toronto Maple 
Leafs. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday night's victory was also important for another reason as  
far as the Sabres were concerned: They admittedly played their 
worst game of the playoffs in losing Game 3 by a 2-1 score on 
Saturday night. The Stars held the Sabres to 12 shots, tying a 
Stanley Cup finals record. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought our team got away from the aggressive forecheck (in  
Game 3) and we wanted to get back to that,'' Sabres coach Lindy 
Ruff said. ``We wanted to get our (defense) involved. That was 
probably the thing that hurt us the most.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres scored first on Tuesday night, but that's not always  
a guarantee of anything in this series. Scoring first in two other 
games, the Sabres lost both. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it would be great if we got the first goal,'' Ruff  
said, ``but I don't think that one goal is the type of lead that 
causes them to start taking chances. Dallas is a very patient 
team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres don't expect Dallas to make the same kind of mistakes  
that helped them win Tuesday night. The Stars defense broke down 
twice, leading to Buffalo goals. 
</P>
<P>
	``Neither team is going to give up many opportunities on  
mistakes now,'' Buffalo's Brian Holzinger said. ``We have to play 
almost a perfect game against them because of how smart 
positionally they are and what a veteran team they have.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
