<HEADLINE> Co-Chairs of Universal Pictures Named </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. (AP) -- Veteran Universal Pictures  
executives Stacey Snider and Brian C. Mulligan on Thursday were 
named co-chairmen of the movie studio that released such recent 
hits as ``The Mummy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The promotions came six months after the resignation of Casey  
Silver, who left in November after overseeing a series of box 
office disappointments that included ``Meet Joe Black'' and ``Babe: 
Pig in the City.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Universal's fortunes have improved in recent weeks through  
moneymakers such as ``The Mummy,'' which has grossed more than $136 
million, and the Eddie Murphy comedy ``Life,'' which earned $61.5 
million, and ``Notting Hill,'' which has taken in $67.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``Brian and Stacey are an outstanding team with a strong  
combination of creative and business instincts,'' said Ron Meyer, 
Universal's president and chief operating officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Snider has been president of film production since November and  
oversaw the development of ``The Mummy,'' ``Life'' and last year's 
``Patch Adams.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She previously was president of production at TriStar Pictures,  
where her projects included ``Sleepless in Seattle'' and ``Jerry 
Maguire.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mulligan was vice president of finance and operations. He helped  
negotiate the $10 billion acquisition by Universal parent Seagram 
Co. of Polygram NV and negotiated a co-production agreement with 
Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer. 

  	   	
</P>
