<DOCNO> APW19990617.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 02:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                         *Anna McCune Harper    	
</P>
<P>
	MORAGA, Calif. (AP) -- Anna McCune Harper, who replaced Helen  
Wills Moody in 1930 as the top-ranked U.S. women's tennis player, 
died Monday. She was 99. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Harper won the mixed doubles at Wimbledon in 1931. She was  
called home in 1932 because of an illness in the family, then 
decided to give up tennis for other tasks including raising three 
children. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Harold Kohn    	
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Harold Kohn, an attorney who filed some of  
the earliest class-action lawsuits accusing corporations of 
price-fixing, died Monday at the age of 85. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1960s, Kohn became nationally known by winning a key case  
against General Electric, Westinghouse and two dozen other 
companies that the federal government had accused of illegal 
price-fixing. 
</P>
<P>
	People who had bought the companies' electrical equipment filed  
hundreds of lawsuits. Kohn's case, brought on behalf of public 
utilities, was the first to go to trial and resulted in a $29 
million verdict. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1981, a jury awarded his clients $2 billion in a class-action  
suit against the timber industry. At the time, it was the largest 
verdict ever in an antitrust case. 
</P>
<P>
	Kohn was also known for public interest cases taken on behalf of  
the American Civil Liberties Union and other groups. During the 
Vietnam War, he helped file a case that argued that the draft was 
unconstitutional because it excluded women. The Supreme Court 
rejected that argument in 1981. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Ryland Milner    	
</P>
<P>
	MARYVILLE, Mo. (AP) -- Ryland Milner, a longtime coach and  
athletic director at Northwest Missouri State University, died 
Wednesday. He was 89. 
</P>
<P>
	He coached the football team from 1937-1957, compiling a  
90-63-13 record and winning six Mid America Intercollegiate 
Athletic Association championships. 
</P>
<P>
	He was 67-60 as basketball coach from 1944-1950.  
</P>
<P>
	Milner also coached track and field, golf and cross country.  
</P>
<P>
	Athletic facilities at Northwest Missouri were renamed the  
Ryland Milner Complex in 1987 and he was inducted into the state 
Sports Hall of Fame in 1988. 

</P>
<P>
                            *J. F. Powers    	
</P>
<P>
	COLLEGEVILLE, Minn. (AP) -- J. F. Powers, a celebrated Catholic  
writer and winner of the 1963 National Book Award for his novel 
``Morte D'Urban,'' died Monday. He was 81. 
</P>
<P>
	Powers was a writer in residence and English professor at St.  
John's University and the College of St. Benedict from 1975 to 
1993. 
</P>
<P>
	He wrote three collections of short fiction and a second novel  
in 1998, ``Wheat That Springeth Green,'' for which he was a 
National Book Award finalist. Both novels follow the careers of a 
Minnesota priest, and much of his writing dealt with the conflict 
between spiritual and secular values in a materialistic society. 
</P>
<P>
	Powers also contributed regularly to The New Yorker and received  
fellowships from the Rockefeller and Guggenheim foundations. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Frank Sordello    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS GATOS, Calif. (AP) -- Frank Sordello, an engineer who held 44  
high-tech patents, including one for a component used in virtually 
all computer disk drives, died June 6 of colon cancer. He was 62. 
</P>
<P>
	Sordello's electronic tachometer proved fundamental to disk  
drives, where most of the information on personal computers is 
stored. 
</P>
<P>
	He began his career at IBM in 1960, leaving to become co-founder  
and chief engineer of Information Storage Systems, a disk-drive 
maker that was acquired by Sperry-Univac. 
</P>
<P>
	From 1973 to 1975, Sordello served on a Commerce Department  
advisory committee on computer peripherals and components. In 1978, 
he helped establish one of the applied-research centers at Memorex 
and was named a corporate vice president and a Memorex fellow the 
following year. 
</P>
<P>
	He received a Distinguished Engineering Alumni Award in 1993  
from Santa Clara. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Lord Sutch    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- David Sutch, who brought a chuckle to British  
politics as leader of the Monster Raving Loony Party with the 
slogan: ``Vote for insanity -- you know it makes sense,'' was found 
hanged Wednesday at his northwest London home. He was 58. 
</P>
<P>
	Known as Screaming Lord Sutch, he was Britain's longest-serving  
party leader. He never won a race, despite running in scores of 
them, but one of his party members was once elected mayor in a town 
in southwest England. 
</P>
<P>
	With his top hat and gold lame suit, Sutch blared his party's  
madcap policies through a rusty loudspeaker from one corner of the 
land to the other. 
</P>
<P>
	Sutch, who legally changed his name to add the ``Lord,'' founded  
the Monster Raving Loony Party in 1963 and first ran for Parliament 
in 1964. He went on to enter some 40 elections over more than 30 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign style of Sutch and his followers irritated more  
traditional candidates but delighted many British voters. And at 
least one of his policies -- all-day pub openings -- later became a 
reality. 
</P>
<P>
	Attempts to price him and other ``nonsense'' candidates out of  
the election scene by increasing the deposit from $240 to $800 
backfired in 1985 -- prompting even more carnival figures, clowns 
and self-described clueless ones to join his ranks. 
</P>
<P>
	During the 1960s, Sutch was a rock singer and until recently  
performed up to 250 concerts a year throughout Europe. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 14:30:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Modell To Sell Share of Ravens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Ravens owner Art Modell, eager to ease the debt  
of his financially strapped NFL team, is seeking an investor to buy 
a minority share of the club. 
</P>
<P>
	Modell plans to hire an investment banker within the next 30  
days to help procure a minority partner. Modell and his wife 
Patricia would maintain controlling interest in the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``Art has been talking privately about adding a minority partner  
ever since he bought out the minority partners in Cleveland,'' 
Ravens spokesman Kevin Byrne said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ravens went heavily into debt when Modell moved the team  
from Cleveland after the 1995 season. Two years ago, the Ravens 
took $185 million in loans and other forms of credit to help reduce 
the deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	Modell told The (Baltimore) Sun the new partner might receive a  
right of first refusal if the team were sold. But he insisted that 
the Ravens are not experiencing cash flow problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's far better than it was three years ago. We have never  
missed a payment,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ravens are trying to restructure part of the team's debt and  
have talked to the commissioner's office about taking out a loan 
from the NFL, Byrne said. 
</P>
<P>
	A portion of the team's debt came from Modell paying more than  
$70 million to buy out his former partners in Cleveland. He also 
had to pay Ohio officials $12 million to settle a lawsuit over 
breaking the lease on Cleveland Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Modell, 73, said a new investor would also benefit the franchise  
in the distant future. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has legal advisors telling him to prepare his estate,''  
Byrne said. 
</P>
<P>
	Modell said he would make sure the new investor would have an  
appreciation of pro football. 
</P>
<P>
	``They should be in it for the love of the sport,'' he said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
