<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Modell Selling Part of Ravens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Baltimore Ravens owner Art Modell will sell  
part of the debt-ridden team to a new investor, The Sun reported 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	Modell said the new partner will not have a controlling share of  
the Ravens, but could receive first refusal rights if the team is 
sold. The controlling share will remain with Modell's wife, 
Patricia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like somebody who's a younger age than me, who can grow  
with the business, grow with my son, David. I want somebody that 
has a very strong interest in professional football,'' said Modell, 
who'll turn 74 in a week. 
</P>
<P>
	He hopes his son, David, 37, the Ravens president, eventually  
will inherit the team. 
</P>
<P>
	Modell said taking on a new investor would help reduce debt,  
which the team incurred beginning in Cleveland. Because it is a 
private company, the team does not report its finances. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, the Ravens completed what was then a record  
restructuring that required league approval. The team took on $185 
million in loans and other forms of credit. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
