<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Engine Builder Dies After Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Engine builder Herb Porter, whose  
turbocharged Offenhausers dominated Indy-car racing in the 1960s 
and 1970s, has died from injuries suffered in a May 20 crash. 
</P>
<P>
	Porter, 84, died Wednesday in Methodist Hospital.  
</P>
<P>
	The crash on Interstate 74 west of Indianapolis which left  
Porter with broken legs and damaged lungs occurred a day before he 
was inducted into the Indianapolis Motor Speedway Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	Porter, who owned Speedway Engine Development, was a fixture in  
the open-wheel engine business for five decades. The company's 
engines power a half-dozen Indy Racing League cars. 
</P>
<P>
	A midget driver and motorcycle racer in the 1930s, Porter  
provided the powerplants that the Goodyear Tire &AMP; Rubber Co. used 
for its testing program in the 1960s. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview last month with The Indianapolis Star, Porter  
said winning the Indianapolis 500 pole in 1971 was one of his 
greatest accomplishments. The other was winning the 1968 500 with 
Bobby Unser. 
</P>
<P>
	Funeral arrangements are incomplete.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
