<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 10:30:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senators Back Steel Industry Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senators sympathetic to the plight of U.S.  
steel, oil and gas producers hurt by low prices urged support today 
for $1.5 billion in federally guaranteed emergency loans. 
</P>
<P>
	The loans would be designed to tide the industries over until  
prices recover. But conservative senators criticized the $270 
million in taxpayer spending needed to back the new loans. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, legislation creating the loan programs appeared to  
have enough votes for passage. The measure cleared a procedural 
hurdle Tuesday, 71-28. A vote on final passage was expected later 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe this is a reasonable response to a terrible crisis  
that threatens more than just companies but whole communities 
across America,'' said Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters said the loans would help domestic steel producers  
injured by low-priced imports and U.S. oil and natural gas 
industries struggling because of sagging prices. Officials say the 
three industries have suffered tens of thousands of layoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., has promised to let the  
House vote on the loan measure. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., chief architect of the loan  
provision, urged colleagues to reject amendments, saying any 
changes would make it harder for Hastert to keep his commitment. 
The measure would help a company in his state, Weirton Steel Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate previously approved the steel-loan program as part of  
an emergency spending bill to pay for Kosovo operations, but 
supporters backed down during negotiations with the House when the 
provision threatened to sink the entire package. 
</P>
<P>
	During those negotiations, Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., insisted  
that a similar program be set up for small oil and gas firms. As 
part of a compromise, the two programs were combined later into a 
separate bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would provide $1 billion in steel loans, with companies  
eligible to borrow $25 million to $250 million at market interest 
rates. U.S. oil and gas producers and service companies would be 
able to borrow up to $10 million each from a $500 million fund. 
</P>
<P>
	The loan measure was only the first of several steel-related  
bills to reach the Senate floor. The full Senate could consider as 
early as next week a bill that would establish comprehensive quotas 
on foreign steel shipments. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, opponents in the Senate Finance Committee tried to  
quash the quota effort by offering to address the U.S. steel 
industry's long-term ability to compete. The committee approved its 
alternative bill, 16-3. 
</P>
<P>
	Steel-state lawmakers denounced the bill as too weak and said it  
offered little short-term relief. 
</P>
<P>
	The Finance Committee bill would initiate an investigation into  
unfair foreign marketing practices, including governments giving 
their producers subsidies and foreign companies flooding the U.S. 
market with products at prices below production costs. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation would also require the development of a  
comprehensive government strategy to eliminate those practices and 
would modify U.S. trade laws to ease U.S. companies' ability to 
prove injury in certain trade complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. William Roth, R-Del., the committee's chairman, said the  
bill was designed to ``address the real problem facing the steel 
industry, the worldwide overcapacity of steel.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0099 </DOCNO>
