<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 15:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ind. To Take Up SBC-Ameritech Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS -- The Indiana Supreme Court on Thursday agreed to  
take up a dispute about whether SBC Communications and Ameritech 
Corp. can merge into one giant telecommunications company. 
</P>
<P>
	In a rare move, the state's high court has granted the two  
companies' request to hear the case before the Indiana Court of 
Appeals does. The Supreme Court gets few such requests, and grants 
just a handful each year. 
</P>
<P>
	A hearing before the court's five justices is scheduled for July  
13. 
</P>
<P>
	SBC and Ameritech sought the Supreme Court's quick entrance into  
the case, arguing in court documents that the Indiana Utility 
Regulatory Commission waited eight months before asserting their 
authority over a proposed merger that affects millions of 
shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for SBC and Ameritech contend the merger is not subject  
to Indiana approval because the transaction merely involves the 
transfer of stock and not Ameritech Indiana's entire system. 
</P>
<P>
	The IURC maintain that a transaction in which more than half of  
a public utility's stock is sold to a different company does fall 
under the state's authority. 
</P>
<P>
	San Antonio-based SBC hopes to buy Chicago-based Ameritech in a  
stock swap that would create a communications company with 57 
million phone lines in 13 states, primarily in the Southwest and 
the Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials hoped to complete the merger, valued at $57  
billion when first announced in May 1998, by late July. 
</P>
<P>
	The two companies are talking with IURC negotiators to reach an  
agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Communications Commission still must approve the  
deal. Ohio regulators and the Justice Department have given their 
blessing. 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana's Office of Utility Consumer Counselor, which represents  
consumers' interests in cases before the IURC, has questioned 
whether the reduced competition caused by the merger would help or 
harm consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents of the merger, which include telecommunications giants  
AT&AMP;T and MCI Worldcom, warn a larger SBC would be so big it would 
deter competition and hurt consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	SBC and Ameritech say the merger will spur local phone  
competition and possibly lower prices, accelerate the roll-out of 
high-speed Internet access and data services and create jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	The states affected by the proposed merger are Arkansas,  
California, Connecticut, Kansas, Missouri, Nevada, Oklahoma, Texas, 
Illinois, Indiana, Michigan, Ohio and Wisconsin. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 14:49:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Leader of British Catholics Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Cardinal Basil Hume, leader of the Roman Catholic  
Church of England and Wales and one of the most admired public 
figures in Britain, died Thursday. He was 76. 
</P>
<P>
	Hume died just hours after his official spokesman announced that  
his cancer had reached its final stages. The cardinal had asked for 
renewed prayers. 
</P>
<P>
	A modest and humorous man, Hume held a position of remarkable  
influence and respect in this country, where Catholics are a 
minority and the established church is Protestant. 
</P>
<P>
	Simple things like his moving prayers at the time of Princess  
Diana's death and his passionate support for the Newcastle United 
soccer team found him a place in many non-Catholic hearts. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was goodness personified, a true holy man with  
extraordinary humility and an unswerving dedication,'' Prime 
Minister Tony Blair said. ``He did much to inspire people of all 
faiths, and none.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hume learned of his cancer in April and informed the archdiocese  
in typically direct manner that he wanted no fuss and would go on 
working as long as he could. He described himself as 
``uncharacteristically, calm and at peace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was admitted to London's Hospital of St. John and St.  
Elizabeth at the end of May, but was able to go to Buckingham 
Palace on June 2 for a private meeting with Queen Elizabeth II. 
</P>
<P>
	She gave him the high honor of the Order of Merit, one of the  
few awards she bestows by her own choice, rather than the 
government's. It is given to people of ``exceptional distinction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The queen is deeply saddened to learn of the death of Cardinal  
Hume, whom she will remember for his outstanding contribution to 
the Christian life of this country,'' Buckingham Palace said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	A funeral mass was scheduled for June 25 at Westminster  
Cathedral, where his body will lie in state Monday through 
Wednesday next week. A memorial mass will likely be held in 
September, church officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Though he shepherded a flock of just 4.6 million, the cardinal's  
ability to cut through complicated moral arguments and get to the 
nub of the matter made his a voice heard beyond his own church. 
</P>
<P>
	The cardinal surprised some more dogmatic Christians in 1993  
when he affirmed the dignity of homosexuals, telling them ``not to 
develop a sense of guilt or think of themselves as unpleasing to 
God. On the contrary, they are precious to God.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He believed in the value of priestly celibacy, but said he often  
regretted not having a wife. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think a successful celibate has to regret he wasn't  
married,'' Hume told the BBC in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	George Haliburton Hume was born March 2, 1923, in Newcastle,  
northern England. He adopted the name Basil after taking his vows 
as a monk in 1945. 
</P>
<P>
	A surprise choice as Roman Catholic primate in 1976, he was  
abbot of Ampleforth Monastery and former head of its prestigious 
school, Ampleforth College. 
</P>
<P>
	After his selection as primate, in the space of just a few  
months, he was ordained a bishop, then Archbishop of Westminster 
and cardinal. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not a position he had sought, and his friends said he had  
hoped one day to retire in the country, where he could pursue his 
love of fishing. 
</P>
<P>
	Some attributed Hume's influence with the largely Protestant  
establishment in part to the fact that he was upper middle class 
and English rather than Irish. 
</P>
<P>
	But there was more to it, wrote veteran journalist Lord Deedes,  
one of the more famous pillars of the establishment. 
</P>
<P>
	``Much of Cardinal Hume's authority is derived from his  
humility,'' Deedes wrote in 1997. ``It is a quality that may stem 
from his years as a Benedictine monk ... it may be part of his 
faith, or it may just spring from goodness. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1990s, with the Church of England in turmoil over  
ordaining female priests, some Anglican clergy and laymen turned to 
the Catholic Church. It was a delicate time for both churches. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one else could have played the careful balance of welcome  
toward those who sought entry into his church, and a sensitivity to 
those members of the Anglican Church left behind,'' said Graham 
Leonard, a retired Anglican bishop who converted to Catholicism. 
</P>
<P>
	The queen, temporal head of the Church of England, took the very  
unusual step of attending a vespers service at Westminster 
Cathedral, Hume's seat, in 1995. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 14:49:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
