	He believed in the value of priestly celibacy, but said he often  
regretted not having a wife. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think a successful celibate has to regret he wasn't  
married,'' Hume told the BBC in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	George Haliburton Hume was born March 2, 1923, in Newcastle,  
northern England. He adopted the name Basil after taking his vows 
as a monk in 1945. 
</P>
<P>
	A surprise choice as Roman Catholic primate in 1976, he was  
abbot of Ampleforth Monastery and former head of its prestigious 
school, Ampleforth College. 
</P>
<P>
	After his selection as primate, in the space of just a few  
months, he was ordained a bishop, then Archbishop of Westminster 
and cardinal. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not a position he had sought, and his friends said he had  
hoped one day to retire in the country, where he could pursue his 
love of fishing. 
</P>
<P>
	Some attributed Hume's influence with the largely Protestant  
establishment in part to the fact that he was upper middle class 
and English rather than Irish. 
</P>
<P>
	But there was more to it, wrote veteran journalist Lord Deedes,  
one of the more famous pillars of the establishment. 
</P>
<P>
	``Much of Cardinal Hume's authority is derived from his  
humility,'' Deedes wrote in 1997. ``It is a quality that may stem 
from his years as a Benedictine monk ... it may be part of his 
faith, or it may just spring from goodness. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1990s, with the Church of England in turmoil over  
ordaining female priests, some Anglican clergy and laymen turned to 
the Catholic Church. It was a delicate time for both churches. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one else could have played the careful balance of welcome  
toward those who sought entry into his church, and a sensitivity to 
those members of the Anglican Church left behind,'' said Graham 
Leonard, a retired Anglican bishop who converted to Catholicism. 
</P>
<P>
	The queen, temporal head of the Church of England, took the very  
unusual step of attending a vespers service at Westminster 
Cathedral, Hume's seat, in 1995. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 09:00:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Summers Says He'll Stay the Course </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lawrence Summers, President Clinton's choice  
to be secretary of the treasury, told lawmakers today that his 
challenge will be to stay the administration's financial course, 
which has helped bring about the nation's current economic boom. 
</P>
<P>
	``At treasury the right course has been set. Our challenge will  
be to carry on,'' Summers told the Senate Finance Committee at a 
hearing today on his nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Under outgoing Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin the nation's  
economy, powered by consumer spending, has grown 4.1 percent in the 
first quarter of this year. Unemployment is at a 29-year low. 
Consumer confidence is up and the stock markets have been rallying. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers, 44, joined Treasury in 1993 as undersecretary for  
international affairs. He has served since 1995 as deputy to Rubin, 
who announced his resignation earlier this month and has said he 
would like to leave the post by July 4. 
</P>
<P>
	The Finance Committee could vote on Summers' nomination next  
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers is expected to win Senate approval. But some steel-state  
lawmakers including committee member Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va., 
wants to talk to Summers about steps they want the Clinton 
administration to take to protect the U.S. steel industry. 
</P>
<P>
	One day before Summers' nomination hearing, the Finance  
Committee approved a bill designed to address the U.S. steel 
industry's long-term ability to compete. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee took up the bill as an alternative to global  
quotas, which many panel members and the White House oppose. The 
steel industry has been battered by a flood of cheap steel imports 
coming into the U.S. from Japan, South Korea, Russia and other 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	When Summers' nomination was announced last month, Senate  
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said he saw no problems with 
the nomination. And, the Finance Committee chairman, Sen. William 
Roth, R-Del., said his panel had had a ``good working 
relationship'' with him. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, Sen. James Inhofe, R-Okla., on Wednesday said he  
would no longer block pending White House nominations, including 
Summers, before the Senate because of an unrelated dispute the 
lawmaker had with the White House over a separate appointment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
