<HEADLINE> Half of Marines' Harriers Grounded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORFOLK, Va. (AP) -- The Marine Corps has grounded about half of  
its AV-8B Harrier jump jets while it investigates two crashes in 
the past two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, 84 planes were grounded. The planes have the same  
Rolls-Royce engine model as the aircraft involved in the crashes, A 
Marine spokeswoman told The Virginian-Pilot. However, the engine 
has not been identified as being at fault in either crash, she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no estimate on how long the planes might be out of  
service. 
</P>
<P>
	The crashes involved Harriers based at Kadena Air Base in Japan  
and the Marine Corps Air Station in Yuma, Ariz. The Kadena crash 
occurred June 4 as the plane was taking off on a training mission. 
The Yuma crash happened during a flight Monday over a training 
range near the base. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilots in both cases ejected safely.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
