<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rockslide Blocks Blue Ridge Parkway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE SWITZERLAND, N.C. (AP) -- A rockslide that sent boulders  
crashing down on the Blue Ridge Parkway is forcing tourists to get 
off the scenic highway and take a 25-mile detour. 
</P>
<P>
	The slide happened Tuesday and included a huge boulder that may  
weigh up to 2,000 tons. No injuries or damage to vehicles were 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	``It might have been lightning or seismic activity, or it could  
have been that during the original construction a crack formed 
which time finally opened up,'' said John Gentry, the parkway's 
division chief for maintenance and engineering. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said they have no idea when they will be able to  
reopen the route, a mostly two-lane road that meanders 470 miles 
runs from the Great Smoky Mountains National Park in western North 
Carolina to Shenandoah National Park in Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the middle of our season, so we're going to move as  
fast as we can to get this section open as soon as possible,'' 
Gentry said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
