<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani May Face GOP Primary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- While political circles are abuzz with talk  
of a possible Senate race between Hillary Rodham Clinton and 
Rudolph Giuliani, the New York City mayor may not have a clear path 
to the Republican nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	A little-known GOP congressman from Long Island, Rick Lazio,  
could be standing in Giuliani's way. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will be making an announcement sometime in the summer and I  
can't imagine right now that announcement is not going to be a 
positive one,'' Lazio, 41, said recently. 
</P>
<P>
	A Republican primary, which would come just two months before  
next year's Senate election, could leave the mayor badly bruised 
and with a lighter bank account or even as a loser, according to 
some veteran New York politicians. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a real problem for Rudy,'' New York GOP consultant Jay  
Severin said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people who vote in Republican primaries don't regard  
(Giuliani) as a conservative and they do regard themselves as 
conservatives,'' Severin explained. ``There is the 
'he's-not-one-of-us' mentality.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The way you beat Rudy Giuliani is you run as the Republican,''  
Lazio said. 
</P>
<P>
	While Giuliani has earned high marks from Republicans and many  
Democrats for a crime-fighting, quality-of-life approach credited 
with making New York City more livable, New York's most powerful 
local GOP chairman, Nassau County's Joseph Mondello, said that 
``with rock-ribbed Republicans, there appears to be a problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Conservatives complain about the mayor's support for abortion  
and gay rights, gun control and his opposition to President 
Clinton's impeachment. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Republicans, especially in traditionally Republican upstate  
New York, have not forgiven Giuliani for crossing party lines in 
1994 to endorse then-Gov. Mario Cuomo over George Pataki in a race 
won by the GOP challenger. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, Lazio is considered a Giuliani threat in large part  
because of a widespread belief that Pataki and his political 
mentor, former Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, are behind the fresh-faced, 
four-term congressman. 
</P>
<P>
	Pataki denies playing favorites, although aides to the governor  
have assisted the congressman in his recent travels across the 
state. Lazio says the governor and D'Amato ``have been very 
generous with their advice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Republican primaries are about organization and the people  
still remember what Giuliani said about Cuomo in 1994, so I can see 
a scenario where this kid could win,'' Lazio supporter Howard 
DeMartini, chairman of the congressman's home Suffolk County GOP, 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He holds Giuliani even in the suburbs, beats him badly  
upstate, and there are not enough Republican votes in the city to 
make a difference,'' DeMartini said. 
</P>
<P>
	While New York City represents about 30 percent of the statewide  
vote in general elections, it contributes only about 15 percent of 
GOP primary voting. About one-third of Republican primary votes 
come from Long Island. 
</P>
<P>
	Also eyeing the Republican nomination is Rep. Peter King,  
another Long Islander. 
</P>
<P>
	``A popular Republican from Long Island is Giuliani's worst  
nightmare,'' said GOP pollster John McLoughlin, who has done work 
for both Lazio and King. 
</P>
<P>
	Lazio has been assiduously courting the state's tiny, but  
politically influential Conservative Party. Over the past 25 years, 
no Republican has won statewide office in New York without 
Conservative Party backing. But in a critical gun control vote 
Thursday night, he supported stronger gun controls over the 
objections of the Conservative Party's leader in the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Given Giuliani's demonstrated ability to pull votes in heavily  
Democratic New York City, a potential boost for the GOP in the 
general election, ``Democrats will not be sorry if Rick Lazio is in 
the primary,'' veteran Democratic consultant Hank Sheinkopf said. 
``They will be very happy people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Lazio thinks a primary victory over Giuliani could give him  
a big boost for a race against Mrs. Clinton. While the first lady's 
camp knows it could wind up facing a ``giant killer'' who comes 
across as more likable than the mayor, it also believes Lazio 
presents a starker conservative contrast for them than Giuliani 
would. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani aides say they're not worried about possible Republican  
opponents. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not worried about Peter King, Rick Lazio,'' Bruce  
Teitelbaum, who heads up the mayor's political operation, said. 
``We're focusing on the things we have to do to get ourselves ready 
should the mayor decide to run.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
