<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Slave Laborers Blast German Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- German companies agreed Thursday to review  
details of a promised fund to compensate Nazi-era slave laborers 
after victims harshly criticized a plan unveiled last week, the 
government said. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement followed talks in Bonn between Chancellor  
Gerhard Schroeder's chief of staff, Bodo Hombach, U.S. 
Undersecretary of State Stuart Eizenstat, and attorneys 
representing former slave laborers in the United States and Germany 
who have filed class-action lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	Schroeder and German industry have pledged to have the fund  
running by September, but negotiations have dragged on for months. 
Last week, 16 German companies that profited from Nazi-era slave 
labor announced details of a promised compensation fund that aims 
to quash lawsuits by survivors of slave labor. 
</P>
<P>
	But victims' groups were enraged by provisions that payments  
would only be offered for six months of slave labor or longer, and 
that they would be based on average pensions and the cost of living 
in claimants' home countries, not back wages. That would mean 
former slave laborers living in poorer countries would be paid less 
compensation. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's statement said there ``appeared to be wide areas of  
agreement'' on numerous issues, including ``need for a prompt and 
fair resolution,'' and ``need for legal closure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, it said, there were still areas of  
disagreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Also at the talks were representatives of the Jewish Claims  
Conference, Poland, Czech Republic, Russia, Belarus, Ukraine and 
Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Thursday, Lothar Evers, head of a German group  
representing former Nazi-era slave laborers, said the victims 
should be at the negotiating table, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Former slave laborers were ``not being accepted as equal  
negotiating partners ... Instead they are being asked to apply as 
supplicants, as charity cases,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Salvatore Bertorelli, who was forced to work for three months  
for a chemical company at a Nazi labor camp in Germany during World 
War II, said the time limit proposed by industry last week was 
arbitrary. 
</P>
<P>
	``This camp was so brutal that no one survived more than three  
months,'' Bertorelli, a British-Italian national, told a news 
conference. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 23:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Robertson Warns GOP of Gore Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Promising a major push to elect Republicans  
next year, Christian Coalition President Pat Robertson is urging 
Senate GOP leaders to stress a religious and pro-family agenda or 
risk ceding issues to Vice President Al Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	Robertson said he also used a series of meetings with top Senate  
Republicans on Thursday to ask for a ``Senate inquiry'' into the 
Internal Revenue Service for its ``selective enforcement'' in 
granting tax-exempt status. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRS recently denied that status to the Christian Coalition.  
Robertson said ``everybody you could name of the liberal persuasion 
seemed to have no problem'' getting tax-exempt status, including 
the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those Robertson met with were Senate Majority Leader Trent  
Lott, R-Miss.; Senate Majority Whip Don Nickles, R-Okla.; and Sen. 
Paul Coverdell, R-Ga. He described the sessions in an interview, 
saying he received no commitments for votes or for an IRS inquiry. 
</P>
<P>
	Robertson said he told the lawmakers the Christian Coalition  
intends to ``gear up very strong'' for next year's voting, which he 
said ``could be the most crucial election of the 20th century.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If the Christian Coalition isn't in the game, the Republicans  
are going to lose'' in 2000, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Robertson made his rounds on Capitol Hill a day after Gore  
formally announced his candidacy for president in remarks stressing 
family, values and faith. 
</P>
<P>
	``Al Gore is in the process of co-opting a number of Republican  
issues,'' Robertson said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he told Lott that with the votes lawmakers have taken so  
far this year, ``The average person doesn't understand what the 
Republican Congress is doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he suggested votes on a proposed constitutional  
amendment that would protect religious Americans from 
discrimination, and on a GOP plan to reduce taxes on married 
couples, many of whom owe more than they would if they were single. 
</P>
<P>
	Christian Coalition spokesman Mike Russell said Robertson also  
said the GOP should express its desire to win a veto-proof 
congressional majority for banning certain late-term abortions that 
opponents have labeled ``partial-birth abortions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked why Robertson had requested the meetings at this time,  
Russell said the Christian Coalition founder was disappointed by 
``the knee-jerk reaction'' of the Senate to the shootings at 
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., this spring. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate approved some restrictions on gun sales. Russell said  
Robertson believes that instead, Congress should address ``the real 
moral problems of this country'' by helping families and 
emphasizing faith. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRS has concluded that some Christian Coalition activities,  
such as its distribution of voter guides at churches across the 
country, were too partisan for it to enjoy tax-exempt status. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he had asked the GOP senators to intervene with the IRS  
on his group's behalf, Robertson said he did not have to because 
the ruling will ``only be a hiccup in our operation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Christian Coalition officials have said the group is  
reorganizing to deal with the ruling. A new Christian Coalition 
International will engage in partisan activity, including candidate 
endorsements and political contributions. The Christian Coalition 
of Texas, a tax-exempt group, will be renamed Christian Coalition 
of America and will limit its activity to nonprofit ``voter 
education.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 16:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Deliberates in Lewis Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Jury deliberations began Thursday in the  
malpractice case stemming from the death of Boston Celtics captain 
Reggie Lewis. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Gilbert Mudge and two consultants, Drs. Mark Creager and  
Peter Friedman, are accused by the player's widow of misdiagnosing 
and mistreating Lewis' fatal heart condition. 
</P>
<P>
	After nearly seven weeks of testimony, the jury received  
instructions from the judge Thursday morning. Jurors then were 
given a five-page questionnaire containing 16 questions about 
whether the doctors were negligent and, if so, whether that 
negligence contributed to Lewis' death. 
</P>
<P>
	If 13 of the 15 jurors answer ``yes'' to those questions, there  
are further entries where they must calculate damage figures. 
</P>
<P>
	Donna Harris-Lewis is asking for the money her husband would  
have earned playing basketball had he lived, estimated at as much 
as $75 million by plaintiff's attorneys. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury deliberated about four hours before going home for the  
day and was scheduled to resume Friday morning. The panel had one 
request Thursday, for a list of witnesses and designations of which 
were considered experts by the court. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
