<DOCNO> APW19990617.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 02:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Charges Filed Vs. Indiana Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) -- Bob Knight, more somber than angry, was  
hardly relieved by a prosecutor's decision not to charge him in a 
restaurant parking lot scuffle. 
</P>
<P>
	``This isn't any relief,'' the Indiana basketball coach said  
Wednesday, an hour after prosecutor Carl Salzmann agreed with 
Knight's contention he was provoked by another diner at the 
restaurant last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Known for his hot temper and seemingly at the center of one  
controversy after another throughout his career, Knight lashed out 
at Salzmann for taking so long to act and at the news media for, 
once again, being too willing to go along with a groundless 
accusation. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're accused of something that you didn't do, and when  
this is battered about pretty carelessly by a lot of different 
institutions ... there's no relief in this,'' Knight said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really don't appreciate being treated differently from  
anybody else in Monroe County. I don't care that my name happens to 
be Knight instead of Jones. I don't think that calls for any 
different treatment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The other man, Chris Foster, said he overheard Knight make what  
he regarded as a racist remark as the coach talked with his wife 
and her two sisters during dinner at an Ellettsville restaurant on 
June 7. When he confronted Knight in the parking lot, the coach 
started screaming at him, grabbed him by the neck and choked him, 
Foster said last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Foster scheduled a news conference in Indianapolis today.  
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Salzmann told reporters that Foster, a 38-year-old  
guitar-maker, initiated the confrontations inside and outside the 
restaurant. Red marks on Foster's neck may have resulted from being 
grabbed by the collar, which Knight admitted, but they certainly 
weren't choke marks, the prosecutor said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Based on the facts I have, including the medical records, my  
decision is not to file charges,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But that didn't satisfy Knight, who repeatedly criticized the  
prosecutor for letting the case drag for nine days. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the Monroe County prosecutor's office investigated Charles  
Manson, it still would be undecided,'' Knight said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Without exception, these (misdemeanor) things are either  
immediately thrown out or resolved in two days. ... I'd like to 
refer to this whole thing as a real Mickey Mouse operation, but 
that would be an insult to Mickey Mouse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Salzmann said it took so long to resolve because Foster hired a  
lawyer and did not make himself available for questioning until 
Wednesday morning. And Foster's dinner companion, who backed his 
friend's story in an earlier interview with the media, refused to 
talk to police altogether, Salzmann said. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't until another restaurant patron and his wife came  
forward on Tuesday -- in support of Knight -- that the prosecutor 
felt he had enough information to make a decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``My job is to make sure justice is done, based on the facts,''  
Salzmann said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Knight said there were at least three other people in the  
restaurant who gave statements that corroborated what he, his wife 
Karen and her sisters told police from the beginning. 
</P>
<P>
	``The information that is available to the prosecutor's office  
at this moment was available to them no later than Wednesday of 
last week,'' Knight said. 
</P>
<P>
	He later hinted he might respond to the incident in another way.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know where it goes from here, but I do know that there  
are avenues open that involve things that are relative to this 
thing that happened,'' Knight told Indianapolis television station 
WTHR. ``I'm going fishing, and if I get some kind of idea while I'm 
fishing, that's where I'm going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Karen Knight said the accusation by Foster and lengthy  
investigation ``totally disrupted our lives. 
</P>
<P>
	``At some point, we have to have rights. We have to have a right  
to go out and have a family dinner and have a conversation with our 
family, a perfectly harmless conversation,'' she said. ``You should 
have some protection so somebody can't come up and continue to 
harass you until you are forced to respond.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her visibly weary husband said, ``Karen has been unbelievably  
good for me ... But the other night, Monday night, after the second 
postponement (of a decision by the prosecutor) she said, `You know, 
if you're ready to quit, I'm ready to go.' I've never heard 
anything like that from her before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Knight gave no indication that he ever considered resigning. He  
left immediately without taking questions. 
</P>
<P>
	Karen Knight's sister, Gina Vieth, also criticized the media.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think Chris Foster has missed his calling. He shouldn't be a  
guitar-maker. He should be in the media, because you guys have a 
real knack for getting things wrong and taking things out of 
context,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	State Police Sgt. J.D. Maxwell also spoke at Knight's news  
conference and said witnesses confirmed no profanity or racial 
slurs came from Knight's table at the restaurant. He said they 
heard Knight talking about the old Negro baseball leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	``The conversation was not racist. He said those players were  
cheated by not going into the same league white players were in. 
The main thing is, without a doubt, there was no profanity, no 
racial slurs. As sure as there's a God in heaven, I know Bob Knight 
is not a racist,'' Maxwell said. 
</P>
<P>
	Salzmann said Foster's actions were ``in the realm of  
provocation,'' but he would not charge Foster because of the 
relatively minor nature of the incident. 
</P>
<P>
	``Responsible men can differ on what is provocation,'' Salzmann  
said. ``But a criminal charge has to be proven beyond a reasonable 
doubt, and I don't feel that there needs to be any more time and 
resources spent in that regard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Foster's attorney Kevin McGoff, said his client was relieved not  
to be charged, although he did not agree with the characterization 
that he provoked Knight in the restaurant. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
