<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 16:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Holbrooke Gains Support for UN Post </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Richard Holbrooke gained significant  
Republican support Thursday for his confirmation as the nation's 
U.N. ambassador after he apologized to senators for 
``carelessness'' that led to questions about his ethics. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke said he violated no laws, but acknowledged that he  
``may not have been careful enough about the appearances'' of his 
contacts with State Department officials abroad just months after 
leaving a top position with the agency in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, he was a private investment banker while also  
serving as an unpaid foreign policy adviser to the State 
Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Foreign Relations Committee Chairman Jesse Helms, R-N.C.,  
remained mum on his position toward the nomination despite 
beginning the first of three hearings with sharp criticism of 
Holbrooke's conduct. 
</P>
<P>
	However, among the 10 Republicans on the 18-member committee,  
influential Sen. Richard Lugar of Indiana said during the hearing 
that he would back the nominee -- and three other GOP members 
indicated they would also support Holbrooke. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had said unless something comes out of the hearing ... that  
I don't know about, that I don't anticipate, then I think he is 
qualified and I'll vote for him,'' said Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore., is ``likely to support the  
nomination,'' his spokeswoman Mary Healy said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe Holbrooke will be confirmed,'' commented Sen. Bill  
Frist, R-Tenn., adding, ``Obviously, that's where I'm leaning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats were effusive in their support, pointing out that  
allegations of wrongdoing by Holbrooke began with an anonymous 
letter to the State Department inspector general, who proceeded 
without showing the nominee a copy. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke, the architect of the Bosnian peace accords, was  
contrite, saying, ``I apologize to the committee and its staff for 
any inconvenience'' his behavior caused. 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke said that in the meetings abroad where State  
Department officials were present, ``I would not discuss 
business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said his employer, Credit Suisse First Boston, ``never gained  
from any of these meetings'' -- a policy he said he stuck to even 
though company officials ``were not happy'' about it. The meetings 
in question were from 1996 to this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Helms produced figures showing that Credit Suisse paid $21,805  
to cover Holbrooke's airfare, hotels and meals on many of the 
trips. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal law imposes a one-year ``cooling-off'' period, designed  
to prevent lobbying of former co-workers. During that year, 
ex-government officials cannot discuss official matters with 
employees of their former agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Even beyond the one-year time frame, Holbrooke acknowledged he  
erred in not making it clear that the discussions were in his 
government role -- and concerned only U.S. foreign policy goals. 
</P>
<P>
	``With regret I must say that carelessness on occasion on my  
part contributed to these misconceptions,'' Holbrooke said. 
</P>
<P>
	Helms said in his opening statement that Holbrooke ignored legal  
advice that could have prevented conflicts of interest while he 
served in both roles. He also criticized the nominee's acceptance 
of $900,000 for speeches and articles about U.S. foreign policy. A 
federal law says even special employees cannot receive compensation 
for speaking and writing on subjects involved in their official 
duties. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Holbrooke could have avoided such conflicts of interest by  
seeking and following the advice'' of either Credit Suisse lawyers 
or State Department attorneys, Helms said. ``But time and again, 
the evidence shows Mr. Holbrooke either chose not to seek ethics 
advice or to ignore it when it was given.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Helms said Holbrooke earned his honoraria by speaking and  
writing ``about the very issues that were a part of his duties'' as 
a State Department official. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton first announced his intention to nominate  
Holbrooke a year ago, and he was formally nominated in February 
after paying a $5,000 Justice Department fine for blurring his 
public and private roles during a trip to South Korea. Holbrooke 
said he settled the case so his nomination could move forward, and 
the State Department cleared him of any wrongdoing on the speaking 
fees. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel's senior Democrat, Sen. Joseph Biden of Delaware,  
defended Holbrooke, saying: ``I believe strongly that none of these 
matters even approach the level where they should be considered 
disqualifying. I do not believe for one minute that Richard 
Holbrooke is an unethical person.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke told the hearing that on visits to foreign countries  
``it was common courtesy to inform ambassadors'' of U.S. foreign 
policy goals. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
