<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Griffey Sr. Manager for a Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Ken Griffey Sr., the Reds' manager for a day,  
was having fun before Thursday night's game with Milwaukee. 
</P>
<P>
	``Is this all Jack does?'' Griffey joked as he sat in Jack  
McKeon's office and talked with reporters, as McKeon does before 
every game. 
</P>
<P>
	``You want a cigar to relax your nerves?'' asked pitching coach  
Don Gullett, referring to McKeon's stogie habit. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey, the Reds' bench coach, was in charge for because McKeon  
had gone home to North Carolina to be with his wife, who had breast 
cancer surgery. McKeon was expected back Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The doctors said they were able to remove all of the cancer,  
and Carol is doing fine,'' McKeon said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey, who wants to manage full-time someday, seemed  
embarrassed by the well wishers who kept calling him ``Skip.'' When 
Greg Vaughn greeted him at the batting cage, Griffey just rolled 
his eyes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody has been congratulating me about being manager.  
That's a strange feeling,'' Griffey said. 
</P>
<P>
	His famous son, Ken Griffey Jr., offered no advice.  
</P>
<P>
	``He just said, `I hope you win,' '' dad said.  
</P>
<P>
	For his major league debut, Griffey gave umpires a lineup card  
filled out by McKeon. Gullett was expected to make the pitching 
decisions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone has their assigned jobs,'' Griffey said. ``We're  
going to work together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey, 49, played 19 years in the big leagues and has spent  
nine years as a coach or instructor. He managed in the Arizona Fall 
League last year, and will manage the Santurce team next winter in 
the Puerto Rican winter league. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
