AMEX Mkt Value Index:          768.69  + 3.77
NASDAQ           2543.45  +25.62
Gold(final) -    $259.30    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.
Silver(final) -   UNCH    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Wed.

</P>
<P>
	Compaq Issues Earnings Warning  
</P>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Compaq Computer Corp. dismayed Wall Street for a  
second time in two months today, disclosing an unexpected quarterly 
financial loss and a restructuring aimed at slashing $2 billion in 
annual costs that will include job cuts. Compaq tied its troubles 
to computer price wars, sluggish sales and a bloated cost 
structure. The company predicts it will report a loss of up to 15 
cents a share in the second quarter, compared to a profit of 20 
cents expected by analysts. The news sent Compaq's stock down as 
much as 10 percent before recovering. Compaq ended up 1/4 at at 22 1/2. 

</P>
<P>
	Belgium Keeps Ban on Coke  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) - Belgian's government extended its ban  
on Coke but agreed today to allow sales of some of the company's 
other beverages to resume for the first time since Monday, when 
they were ordered from shelves after dozens of people became ill 
after drinking Coca-Cola products. And while France partially 
relaxed its ban on sales of Coca-Cola, Switzerland joined a move by 
other nations to block sales of Coca-Cola drinks produced in 
Belgium. In Belgium, the Heath Ministry said it will allow sales of 
Coca-Cola's Nestea, Aquarius, Bonaqua, Kinley, Lift and Minute Maid 
brands. But the ban was extended on Coke, Fanta and Sprite. 

</P>
<P>
	Kellogg May Close Part of Plant  
</P>
<P>
	BATTLE CREEK, Mich. (AP) -- The nation's largest cereal maker  
announced today it is considering closing part of its historic 
Battle Creek cereal plant and eliminating up to 64 percent of the 
jobs at the facility. Under the proposal, up to 700 of the current 
1,100 jobs at the Kellogg Co. plant would be eliminated as early as 
the first quarter of 2000, the company said. Kellogg will not say 
what percentage of its overall production comes from its Battle 
Creek plant, which makes Kellogg's Corn Flakes. 

</P>
<P>
	Trade Deficit Holds at Record High  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- America's trade deficit held steady in April --  
though still at a record high -- amid early signs that U.S. 
companies are selling more products to foreign countries recovering 
from recession. ``While it cannot be said that the world's markets 
for U.S products is booming again, it certainly does look as if the 
bottom has been reached,'' said Joel L. Naroff, chief economist at 
Naroff Economic Advisors in Holland, Pa. April's trade deficit of 
$18.9 billion matched a revised estimate of the deficit in March, 
the Commerce Department said today. 

</P>
<P>
	Lawrence Summers Assures Lawmakers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lawrence Summers, apparently on track for  
swift Senate approval as Treasury secretary, assured lawmakers 
today he will continue policies aimed at fostering economic growth. 
Summers now holds the No. 2 slot at the Treasury Department and is 
seeking to succeed Robert Rubin, who announced plans last month to 
leave the post. The Senate Finance Committee's chairman, William 
Roth, R-Del., said his panel expects to vote on and approve 
Summers' nomination on Tuesday. ``I think it would be 
overwhelming'' Roth said of the committee's support. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Authority Over Assets Limited  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal judges generally cannot protect  
plaintiffs in lawsuits by barring defendants from spending or 
giving away their assets, the Supreme Court ruled today. In a 5-4 
decision, the justices said a New York federal judge could not bar 
a group of Mexican companies from transferring assets while they 
were being sued by U.S. investors. Traditionally, creditors must 
first win judgment in a case, Justice Antonin Scalia wrote for the 
court. Writing for the four, Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg said now 
that assets can be transferred almost instantly, courts should be 
allowed to keep defendants from ``making themselves 
judgment-proof'' by transferring assets. 

</P>
<P>
	Airlines Announce Service Measures  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Prodded by Congress, the airlines today  
announced a package of voluntary measures to address growing 
complaints from consumers about poor service. Also today, Amtrak 
revealed a plan to win back disgruntled rail passengers, including 
enhanced food-service options and guaranteed refund vouchers to any 
dissatisfied passenger. The airlines' measures include ensuring 
that each airline will tell customers the lowest fare available, 
notifying customers of delays, supporting an increase in the 
baggage liability limit, allowing reservations to be held without 
payment for 24 hours and providing prompt refunds. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Rejects Bill To Get IMF Loan  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia's Communist-dominated parliament frustrated  
the country's chances of winning crucial foreign loans by defeating 
a government-supported economic reform bill today. The bill, which 
would have imposed a new tax on gas stations, is part of a package 
of reforms designed to meet conditions for a $4.5 billion loan from 
the International Monetary Fund. Moscow wants the money to pay off 
old debts to the IMF. The lower house of parliament, the State 
Duma, voted 219-101 to reject the bill. 

</P>
<P>
	Britain May Ban Some Tobacco Ads  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Tobacco advertisements would be banned from  
billboards, newspapers and stores by the end of the year under a 
draft proposal announced today by the British government. The 
initiative also calls for ending tobacco sponsorship of major 
cultural and sporting events by July 2003. Formula One car racing 
and other events such as snooker, which are highly dependent on 
tobacco sponsorship, would be given an additional three years to 
find alternative sponsors. Tobacco advertising already is banned in 
Finland, France, Italy, Portugal, Sweden and Belgium. 

</P>
<P>
	News Corp. Buys Hearst Publishers  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. is buying the book  
publishing operations of Hearst Corp., consisting of William Morrow 
&AMP; Co. and Avon Books, for an undisclosed amount. The sale announced 
today, which had been rumored for some time, further solidifies the 
position of News Corp.'s HarperCollins, which has spent the last 
two years overcoming a severe profit plunge. Together, Avon and 
Morrow publish some 1,000 books each year and have a combined back 
catalog of nearly 6,000 titles. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic numbers:  
</P>
<P>
	Trade deficit: unchanged at $18.9 billion  
</P>
<P>
	Jobless claims: down 28,000 to 297,000  


  	   	
</P>
