<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate GOP Again Pushing Comp Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate Republicans on Thursday renewed a drive  
to let workers choose time off instead of overtime pay, saying 
their comp-time legislation should be part of the coming debate 
over raising the minimum wage. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure would make it easier for employees to pick  
compensatory time off -- 1 1/2 hours for every hour of overtime work -- 
rather than the decades-long time-and-a-half overtime pay standard. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton vetoed the bill in 1996 because of concerns  
that employers could discriminate against workers who choose 
overtime pay instead of time off. Senate Democrats filibustered the 
measure in the last Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Working parents, especially mothers, need the flexible working  
hours to help balance the demands of their jobs with the needs of 
their families, said Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo. ``No matter where 
you are, unless you're in the government, which already has some of 
these programs, you find people suffering from this trauma,'' said 
Ashcroft, the bill's chief sponsor. 
</P>
<P>
	``Flexible job schedules could allow a working mother to leave  
work early on Friday for a child's doctor's appointment, and then 
make up the missed time the next week without suffering a loss of 
pay,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashcroft said he has made changes to make the measure more  
palatable to Democrats. The bill sets up an 80-hour, two-week 
schedule, but unlike past proposals, it sets a 50-hour limit for 
any given workweek. Unused time off would be converted to cash at 
the end of each year. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashcroft and Sen. Christopher Bond, R-Mo., one of more than 30  
co-sponsors, said the approaching debate over boosting the minimum 
wage is an ideal setting for another attempt to pass comp-time 
legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats, including Missouri Rep. William Clay and Sen. Edward  
Kennedy of Massachusetts, are pushing to phase in over two years a 
$1 increase in the minimum wage to $6.15 an hour. 
</P>
<P>
	``Frankly, I suspect that if there is a minimum wage proposal  
that is made, it would be appropriate to think about things like 
this in conjunction with it,'' said Ashcroft. 
</P>
<P>
	The last wage increase, 90 cents an hour, was implemented in two  
stages, in 1996 and 1997. Republicans are facing potentially 
unstoppable demands for another increase this year; House Majority 
Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, conceded in April that Congress may act 
this year to raise the minimum wage. 
</P>
<P>
	The Missouri senators have opposed previous wage increases, but  
on Thursday, neither ruled out the possibility of supporting a wage 
increase should it include a comp time provision. 
</P>
<P>
	But Kennedy's spokesman, Jim Manley, ruled out a compromise on  
the GOP measure, which he labeled ``an anti-labor poison pill.'' 
Even with the concessions, Manley said, employers could misuse it 
to undermine the traditional 40-hour workweek. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no choice in flex time,'' Manley said.  
</P>
<P>
	Ashcroft, who was joined at a Capitol Hill news conference by  
Bond and Sens. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas and Michael Enzi, 
R-Wyo., said the option would be voluntary and optional for 
employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashcroft said a Rutgers University survey released in March  
bolsters the cause by reporting that 87 percent of 1,000 adult 
workers rated flexible work hours or days as important. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
