<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kentucky Court Voids Gambling Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) -- A man who ran up close to $400,000 in  
gambling debts at an off-track betting parlor does not have to pay 
up because of a nearly century-old law, the Kentucky Supreme Court 
ruled today. 
</P>
<P>
	Because gambling was illegal then, the statute deemed all  
gambling debts void. In light of that, Justice Donald Wintersheimer 
said that when Kentucky Off-Track Betting took checks from James 
McBurney, the betting parlor was in effect loaning him money to 
gamble. 
</P>
<P>
	``The real issue presented here is whether one may collect money  
loaned or advanced to a person to bet while that person is actually 
engaged in betting,'' Wintersheimer said. 
</P>
<P>
	In late 1994 and early 1995, McBurney was a regular customer at  
the KOTB parlor in Corbin. At one point, his debt neared $400,000. 
</P>
<P>
	McBurney, who wrote numerous checks to cover his losses, said he  
told KOTB there was not enough money in his account to cover the 
checks. KOTB, however, said they learned only later about the lack 
of funds. 
</P>
<P>
	In March 1995, McBurney signed a promissory note and agreed to a  
repayment schedule. He made several payments, then stopped with the 
tab still at $342,565. 
</P>
<P>
	The KOTB company, which was authorized by the General Assembly  
in 1992 and is owned by the thoroughbred race tracks in Kentucky, 
sued to force payment. 
</P>
<P>
	In its 5-2 decision today, the court said KOTB was out of luck.  
</P>
<P>
	``By accepting checks that it knew to be worthless in exchange  
for bets while McBurney was actually engaged in betting and by 
continuing to allow him to place more bets thereafter, KOTB clearly 
entered into a gambling transaction declared void by the plain 
language of (the law),'' Wintersheimer said. 
</P>
<P>
	KOTB had argued that the turn-of-the-century law has been  
superseded by more recent legislation that actually promotes 
gambling, including that to create KOTB parlors. 
</P>
<P>
	But ``betting is legal, the lending of money by a betting  
facility in order to bet is not,'' Wintersheimer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Martin Johnstone, who wrote the dissenting opinion, said  
the ruling made no sense. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is preposterous that while it is legal to place a  
pari-mutuel wager on a horse race at an authorized facility, and it 
is legal to loan money, it is illegal to loan money to someone to 
place a legal wager on a horse race in this commonwealth,'' he 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
