<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Christian Bikers Battle Over Logo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAYTON, Ohio (AP) -- A court battle between bikers may require  
divine intervention. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sons of God Motorcycle Club Ministry Inc. is suing the  
Chosen Sons of God Motorcycle Club Ministries for allegedly trying 
to take over its corporate identity through use of the name, and a 
logo showing Christ's head with a crown of thorns and the words 
``New Jerusalem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It symbolizes our identity and who we are,'' Sons of God  
President Thomas Douthat testified Thursday before U.S. Magistrate 
Michael Merz. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've chosen New Jerusalem as our territory, which is a future  
place,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bikers in leather jackets, ponytails and tattoos filled the  
courtroom for the trial. Included on the witness list are Happy 
Jack, Ring-a-ding, Stealth and Bear. 
</P>
<P>
	Douthat's group seeks $500,000 in damages and asks that the  
Chosen Sons of God be barred from using the name. 
</P>
<P>
	Sons of God is a non-profit corporation that serves as a  
Christian ministry. It has about 200 members in 17 chapters in 
about 10 states, including Pennsylvania, New York, North and South 
Carolina, Florida, Tennessee, Ohio and Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of its members are ministers and pastors, and some are  
former members of outlaw motorcycle clubs who have abandoned their 
rough-and-tumble ways for a more spiritual life. 
</P>
<P>
	``The organization gave them a place to belong,'' said Douthat,  
who is known as Virginia Tom and is a minister. 
</P>
<P>
	Douthat said the dispute arose after ``Mountain Bill'' Hodge of  
Dayton was expelled from Sons of God for creating ``division and 
dissension'' after he lost a presidential election in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Hodge says the Chosen Sons are the true owners of the name and  
the Christ-head symbol. 
</P>
<P>
	The non-jury trial was to continue Friday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
