<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Chips Away At Wooden Image </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- On his second day as a full-fledged presidential  
candidate, Vice President Al Gore sounded as though he had been 
studying how to chip away at his oh-so-wooden image. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stump in Manhattan, he promised true equality for women  
and minorities, after-school programs for teens and pre-school for 
younger children. But perhaps just as importantly, he punctuated 
those pledges with sweeping gestures. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you look at our economic circumstances today compared to  
what they were seven years ago, the contrast is truly 
astonishing,'' Gore said while warming to about 800 supporters at 
the midtown campaign reception at The Pierre Hotel. 
</P>
<P>
	He rattled off the statistics: budget surpluses instead of  
deficits, a rising stock market. And as the applause grew, so did 
his decibel level. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have higher wages, higher living standards, a better  
country!'' Gore shouted in a voice growing guttural with the 
effort. 
</P>
<P>
	He recalled his mother, who was among the first women graduates  
of Vanderbilt University's law school, and his father, who spoke 
against poll taxes in the 1940s. He dedicated the coming 17-month 
campaign to their ideals. 
</P>
<P>
	``I begin this campaign with a pledge that the progress we've  
made in this century is only the beginning of what we're going to 
do in the 21st century for the equality of women,'' Gore said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	He credited his father -- former U.S. Sen. Al Gore Sr. -- with  
teaching him ``the meaning of political courage'' and again shouted 
louder than the crowd's cheers when vowing that ``the progress that 
we've made toward civil rights in America is only the beginning!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aides said Gore was beginning to stake out his own record in the  
delicate job facing every vice president seeking the top spot: 
distancing himself from the White House while not seeming disloyal. 
</P>
<P>
	``To begin unshackling from the vice presidency is the key,''  
said campaign chairman Tony Coelho. ``We need to break free of the 
vice presidency.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The trip through New York was part of a four-day, six-state  
campaign swing. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the nod he gave traditionally Democratic  
priorities like women's and minority rights, Gore has promised tax 
cuts targeted for small businesses and a doubling of the nation's 
investment in information technology. 
</P>
<P>
	He also weighed in for first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton's  
potential U.S. Senate run in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore said a bid by Mrs. Clinton would be ``a positive force''  
and generate Democratic enthusiasm throughout the country. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm all for it,'' the vice president told reporters on Air  
Force Two as it flew to New York. ``It will generate enthusiasm 
here and around the country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aides were even more direct, saying likely Republican assaults  
on Mrs. Clinton would galvanize women voters. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans are already honing charges that she's a  
carpetbagger, and are likely to revisit sex scandals at the White 
House and financial investigations in Arkansas. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
