<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 06:20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S., Russia Still Differ on Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	HELSINKI, Finland (AP) -- U.S. and Russian negotiators opened a  
second day of negotiations today on a Russian role in Kosovo 
peacekeeping that would leave NATO in charge. In Paris, President 
Clinton predicted a ``successful conclusion'' to the talks. ``The 
atmosphere is pretty positive and pretty hopeful,'' Clinton told 
reporters on the lawn of Elysee Palace after a meeting with French 
President Jacques Chirac. Nonetheless, Clinton said the NATO allies 
would not abandon their insistence that peacekeeping forces in 
Kosovo operate under a unified command. The Russians have insisted 
that their troops not come under a NATO commander. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Villagers Describe Massacre  
</P>
<P>
	POKLEK, Yugoslavia (AP) -- In a massacre that left blood dripping  
through the floorboards, Serb police slaughtered 62 ethnic 
Albanians two months ago by herding them into a room, tossing in a 
grenade and spraying survivors with machine-gun fire, villagers 
said today. The grisly events in Poklek, 20 miles west of Pristina, 
came to light as the first NATO troops moved into the area. 
Accounts of mass killings have been surfacing since Serb forces 
began withdrawing from Kosovo to comply with last week's peace 
deal. According to the villagers, the killings occurred April 17 
when Serb police and paramilitary men blocked a group -- mainly 
members of a single extended family -- from going to the adjacent 
town of Glogovac and sent them back to their family compound. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton To Wait and See on Milosevic  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- President Clinton today advocated a  
``wait-and-see'' approach on seizing Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic to stand trial for atrocities in Kosovo, saying NATO's 
first priority is to get the refugees home. The president spoke to 
reporters outside the Elysee Palace, where he and French President 
Jacques Chirac met today and agreed anew that Milosevic must be 
unseated before any international development aid goes to 
rebuilding Serbia from 78 days of NATO airstrikes. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Seeks Mideast Peace Process  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- President Clinton gave a vote of confidence today  
to Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak, saying the United 
States counted on his new government to revive a ``vigorous 
pursuit'' of the Middle East peace process. ``I don't believe that 
I will have to take any steps to revive the peace process,'' 
Clinton said in response to a reporter's question about the stalled 
peace process. The president spoke to journalists at the Elysee 
Palace. 

</P>
<P>
	Pope Returns to His Birthplace  
</P>
<P>
	KRAKOW, Poland (AP) -- Pope John Paul II extended his pilgrimage  
to Poland by a few hours today to visit the country's holiest 
shrine, making up the stop he missed while he was ill earlier this 
week. The 79-year-old pontiff appeared revitalized today after an 
emotional return to his birthplace of Wadowice last night. Back on 
his feet after a bout of flu, John Paul said a private Mass for 
friends and seminarians today at Krakow's 14th century Wawel 
Cathedral, where he celebrated his first Mass upon becoming a 
priest in 1946. 

</P>
<P>
	Indian Navy Said To Be on Alert  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- A Pakistani military buildup in the  
Arabian Sea has prompted India to put its navy on alert there, The 
Times of India reported today. The move also aroused fear that 
fighting in Kashmir between the two nuclear neighbors could spread 
to the seas. Indian soldiers are trying to cut off ammunition and 
food supplies to Islamic guerrillas entrenched on the snowy 
mountaintops on the Indian-held side of the disputed territory. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stock Prices Close Higher  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Overnight gains on Wall Street helped push the  
major barometer for Japanese stocks to a 20-month high today. The 
Nikkei gained 260.27 points to close at 17,470.45. 

</P>
<P>
	Spurs 89, Knicks 77  
</P>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- The San Antonio Spurs beat the New York  
Knicks 89-77 last night in Game 1 of the NBA Finals, lead by Tim 
Duncan's 33 points. Duncan was virtually unstoppable all game, 
shooting 13-for-21 and grabbing 16 rebounds. Jaren Jackson had five 
3-pointers and scored 17 for the Spurs. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by PRUDENCE HELLER  
  	   	
</P>
