<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 00:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Quayle Touts 'Real Compassion' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) -- One day after Texas Gov. George W. Bush  
and his ``compassionate conservatism'' left New Hampshire, former 
Vice President Dan Quayle came for a look at what he called ``real 
compassion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle visited a privately funded home for mothers battling drug  
addiction. He said the work done there is a good example of the 
compassion conservatives have shown for years. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a shot at Bush, who has made ``compassionate  
conservatism'' the theme of his campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``Conservatives are compassionate,'' Quayle told reporters in  
Concord. ``We care deeply about our friends and neighbors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aides said Quayle did not change his game plan in light of  
Bush's first visit to the state with the earliest presidential 
primaries. However, the timing did help Quayle highlight 
differences he sees between himself and the Texas governor -- namely 
that he considers himself a conservative alternative to Bush, the 
darling of the moderate Republican ``establishment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Addressing about 50 state legislators at a luncheon, Quayle said  
he would ``shape up those Republicans in Congress,'' encouraging 
them to cut taxes and ``take on the education bureaucracy.'' It was 
a subtle jab at Bush, who has garnered endorsements from more than 
half of the 222 Republicans in the House. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, Quayle listened as women who had overcome cocaine and  
alcohol addiction recounted their stories to a chorus of ``Amens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle said private, faith-based programs such as the New Life  
Home for Women and Children have long been doing a better, more 
compassionate job than government programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Carole Cadieux, 35, who used cocaine intravenously for six years  
before joining New Life, said Quayle's message was right on target. 
</P>
<P>
	``Without God, you can't change,'' Cadieux said. ``I never could  
have done it on my own.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Echoing a theme Bush struck in his recent visits to Iowa and New  
Hampshire, Quayle said that while such groups have done fine on 
their own, they should have the option of getting federal money. 
Federal grants would not violate the First Amendment separation of 
church and state, any more than federal loans to students at 
religious colleges, a top aide said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Concord, Quayle picked up an endorsement from state Rep. Fran  
Wendelboe of New Hampton, who resigned from Elizabeth Dole's 
campaign after Dole said she supported some types of gun control. 
Wendelboe said Bush and others recruited her after she split with 
Dole, but she and Quayle saw eye to eye on every issue. 
</P>
<P>
	The endorsement could sway many state representatives to  
Quayle's side, Rep. Phyllis Woods of Dover said. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's well-respected,'' Woods said. ``And Quayle has got the  
experience and the right message.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle won applause from legislators at several points,  
especially when he criticized President Clinton's foreign policy. 
He said Clinton has gotten bogged down in Yugoslavia when the real 
foreign policy challenge -- China -- has received little attention. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can ill afford another president who needs on-the-job  
training when it comes to foreign policy,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
