<HEADLINE> Siemens, Fujitsu in Computer Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- German industrial group Siemens AG and  
Japan's Fujitsu Ltd. plan to combine most of their European 
computer businesses in a move that would create one of Europe's 
largest personal computer vendors. 
</P>
<P>
	The two companies, which have cooperated for six years, signed a  
memorandum of understanding Thursday on the combination and plan to 
develop, manufacture and market a full range of information 
products. 
</P>
<P>
	Siemens said it expects the new venture to generate sales of  
more than $7.4 billion in fiscal 2000. Independent market 
researchers said the new venture would be second only to Compaq 
Computer Corp. in the European market for personal computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement, Siemens and Fujitsu will cooperate in PCs,  
server and mainframe computer systems with ambitions of becoming 
one of the world's three leading computer manufacturers. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the latest step in an overhaul by Siemens aimed at  
improving earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	A new company called Fujitsu Siemens Computers will start  
operation Oct. 1, pending regulatory approval. Siemens said the 
headquarters may be located in the Netherlands. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
