<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stock Prices Close Higher / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Overnight gains on Wall Street helped push the  
major barometer for Japanese stocks to a 20-month high today. The 
dollar was slightly lower against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed at 17,470.45  
points, up 260.27, or 1.51 percent from Wednesday -- its highest 
since Oct. 22, 1997, when the Nikkei closed at 17,687.61. On 
Wednesday, the Nikkei had dropped 71.82 points, or 0.42 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``The mood has brightened,'' said Hiroichi Nishi, a deputy  
general manager at Nikko Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Rising share prices boosted sentiments for the yen and sent the  
dollar lower. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 120.04 yen by late afternoon, down 0.20 yen  
from late Wednesday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level 
of 120.43 yen overnight. During the day, it ranged from 119.75 yen 
to 120.50 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, Tokyo share prices were sharply higher  
following the overnight rally in U.S. stocks on consumer price data 
indicating that inflation was under control, traders said. That 
means the U.S. Federal Reserve is unlikely to raise interest rates 
anytime soon. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York on Wednesday, the Dow Jones industrial average  
gained 189.96 points, or 1.8 percent, closing at 10,784.95. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many investors are very optimistic, both for the U.S. economy  
and the domestic economy in Japan,'' said Tsuyoshi Nomaguchi, a 
strategist at Daiwa Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange finished up 16.00 points, 
or 1.16 percent, to 1,399.17. The TOPIX ended down 1.90 points, or 
0.14 percent, the previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the first section was estimated at 703.85 million  
shares, up from 691.9 million shares Wednesday. Advancing issues 
outnumbered retreaters 733 to 452, while 120 issues were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	On the foreign exchange market, the U.S. currency was moving  
narrowly on fears of more dollar-buying intervention by the Bank of 
Japan to keep the greenback from falling further against the yen, 
traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, the Bank of Japan sold yen and bought dollars to halt  
a sharp rise in the Japanese currency which was feared could 
threaten emerging signs of economic recovery here. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was traded at 123.90 yen, down from 125.18 yen late  
Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 213 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.700 percent from 1.630 percent late Wednesday, 
driving its price down to 97.43 yen from 98.02. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
