<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> HaperCollins Buys Hearst Publishers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. is buying the book  
publishing operations of Hearst Corp., consisting of William Morrow 
&AMP; Co. and Avon Books, for an undisclosed amount. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale announced today, which had been rumored for some time,  
further solidifies the position of News Corp.'s HarperCollins, 
which has spent the last two years overcoming a severe profit 
plunge. 
</P>
<P>
	HarperCollins president and CEO Jane Friedman, who has received  
kudos for the turnaround, said the acquisition of Morrow and Avon 
will create ``a powerhouse in the industry with a diverse and 
impressive publishing program.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Avon and Morrow had operated together as the book publishing  
division of Hearst Corp., a major privately held media company with 
interests in television, newspapers, radio and the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Together, Avon and Morrow publish some 1,000 books each year and  
have a combined back catalog of nearly 6,000 titles. Morrow's 
authors include Sidney Sheldon, Beverly Cleary and Cokie Roberts, 
while Avon publishes Faye Kellerman, Johanna Lindsey and Elizabeth 
Lowell. 
</P>
<P>
	Several big publishers have merged in recent years, as companies  
seek to cut costs and gain market share. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year the German media conglomerate Bertelsmann AG bought  
the biggest U.S. book publisher, Random House, from Advance 
Publications, for a price estimated by analysts at between $1.1 
billion and $1.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Bertelsmann also bought Bantam Books in 1977 and owns Doubleday,  
Dell-Delacorte and Broadway Books. Also last year, Viacom Inc. sold 
the educational, professional and reference divisions of Simon &AMP; 
Schuster to the British media group Pearson for $4.6 billion. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
