<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 7 Schools Join ECAC Lacrosse League </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- With the NCAA ready to give conference  
champions automatic invitations to its national lacrosse 
tournament, seven East Coast schools have formed a Division I men's 
league that will begin play next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgetown, Maryland-Baltimore County, Massachusetts, Navy, Penn  
State, Stony Brook and Rutgers will play in ECAC Lacrosse. 
</P>
<P>
	The teams will play each other once in the regular season to  
determine a champion. A postseason tournament will not be held. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you are going to form a conference you might as well go for  
the top,'' Rutgers coach Tom Hayes said in a telephone interview. 
``This is going to be a good one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The schools, which belong to other conferences in other sports,  
have occasionally played each other. 
</P>
<P>
	``Stony Brook has to be considered the new kid on the block, but  
it's going to be a very competitive league,'' Hayes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgetown, Navy and Maryland-Baltimore County were in the NCAA  
tournament this season, with Georgetown advancing to the 
semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	Playing in a new league will force Rutgers to change some  
opponents on its schedule, Hayes said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're still going to play Syracuse, Army, Princeton and Yale,  
teams we've been playing the last 60 or 70 years,'' Hayes said. 
</P>
<P>
	The result will be a more difficult schedule for a team that was  
4-10 this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're used to a tough schedule,'' Hayes said. ``We think this  
will be great for our program and great for our fans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The catalyst for the formation of the league was the decision by  
the NCAA men's lacrosse committee to implement automatic 
qualification for conference champions effective with the 
championship in 2000, the ECAC said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	It took about a year to form ECAC Lacrosse, Hayes said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
