<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Dole: I Want To Win Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Republican White House hopeful Elizabeth  
Dole insists she is running for president, not vice president. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am in it to win,'' she says.  
</P>
<P>
	She has formed a presidential exploratory committee but has not  
formally announced her intention to seek the White House, as the 
GOP front-runner, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, did last weekend and 
Vice President Al Gore did Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let me set the record straight: you do not go through this  
process, which is a rigorous one, to be vice president,'' she told 
reporters before a speech here Wednesday, trying to kill 
speculation that she really is seeking the second spot on the GOP 
ticket. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you enter the process, which I have, you do it to win.''  
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole never stopped smiling as she described the trials of  
the campaign trail for an audience of about 300 Rotary Club 
members. At the same time, she offered a rationale for running. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am on the road right now for nine days, if you can imagine --  
one little suitcase and one little ... bag,'' she said. ``You can't 
check your luggage because you'd never get there on time for your 
appointments. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a rigorous process, but I love it, because it gives me a  
chance to share views and share my passion on a lot of things and 
hear from you,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	A Los Angeles Times Poll released Wednesday showed Mrs. Dole  
trailing Bush 50 percent to 13 percent among California voters, but 
she dismissed all such surveys as meaningless. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't be distracted by polls. It is early. Only five percent  
of people are even thinking about the year 2000 right now,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Dole offered a litany of promises relating to the high-tech  
industry. She said she would press for a permanent federal research 
and development tax credit, something the Silicon Valley industry 
has long sought. 
</P>
<P>
	She backed legislation passed by the U.S. Senate on Tuesday that  
would curb Y2K-related lawsuits, and warned that the ``Clinton-Gore 
administration'' has threatened a veto. 
</P>
<P>
	And she called for increasing the cap on the number of highly  
skilled workers allowed into the country under so-called H-1B 
visas, something companies here have asked the federal government 
for. 
</P>
<P>
	Her pitch was tailored to computer industry employees, and she  
was the latest in a growing list of presidential candidates making 
pilgrimages to Silicon Valley. Republican Sen. John McCain, her 
rival for the nomination, will tour a nearby computer company on 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	There were few high-tech workers in Mrs. Dole's audience,  
however, because the Rotary Club limits how many members from one 
industry can join, said Dan Orloff, a club spokesman. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
