<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC's 2006 Vote To Be Saturday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- A Santa Claus roams the hotel  
corridors lobbying for votes, a fitting symbol of virtue for an 
Olympic movement trying to recover its ideals. 
</P>
<P>
	As the International Olympic Committee prepares to choose the  
host city for the 2006 Winter Games, the process has become as 
important as the result. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's vote is the first site-selection since the Salt Lake  
City vote-buying scandal broke six months ago, plunging the IOC 
into the worst crisis of its 105-year history. 
</P>
<P>
	The last time the IOC voted on a Winter Olympic site, in 1995,  
Salt Lake City won the 2002 games in a landslide. As it turned out, 
the victory was aided by more than $1 million in inducements to IOC 
members, 10 of whom have resigned or been expelled. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, six European cities are vying to be the winter stage  
in 2006: Helsinki, Finland; Klagenfurt, Austria; Poprad-Tatry, 
Slovakia; Turin, Italy; Sion, Switzerland; and Zakopane, Poland. 
</P>
<P>
	Their bids, however, have been overshadowed by the scandal, with  
only a slight buzz of suspense building the last few days. 
</P>
<P>
	Sion has been the front-runner from the start and remains the  
favorite, ahead of Turin, Helsinki (and its Santa Claus mascot) and 
Klagenfurt. Slovakia and Poland aren't given much of a chance. 
</P>
<P>
	Bidding rules were changed halfway through the race to eliminate  
any hint of corruption. The most significant: IOC members were 
banned from visiting the cities. Virtually all contact was 
forbidden, cutting out the wining and dining and gift-giving that 
tainted the process in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	The selection procedure has been slightly modified. On Saturday  
morning, a 15-member panel will whittle the field to two finalists. 
Then the full general assembly -- 89 members in this case -- will 
choose the winner by secret ballot. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must not have any question marks at all about the 2006  
selection,'' British IOC member Craig Reedie said. ``It's always 
been very important that the process is seen to be as fireproof as 
you can possibly get it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not everybody is happy with the process.  
</P>
<P>
	Bidders say they were penalized by not being able to show off  
their cities to the IOC delegates. They resorted, instead, to 
mailing brochures and video cassettes. 
</P>
<P>
	``The IOC told us in January, `You are victims and have to make  
the sacrifice,' '' said Turin bid leader Evelina Cristillin. ``It's 
been very frustrating, but you do the best you can in the 
circumstances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Italians have complained that the ban on site visits gives  
an unfair advantage to Sion, which hosted more than 60 IOC members 
during an unsuccessful attempt to land the 2002 games. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Swiss say they, too, were hurt by the new rules because  
they couldn't show members the vast improvements made since the 
previous bid. 
</P>
<P>
	The closest view many members will get will come Friday when the  
bidders make one-hour presentations to the IOC assembly. 
</P>
<P>
	But Saturday's vote could be more heavily influenced by a  
written report issued in January by a special IOC inspection panel 
that evaluated the merits of each bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Many IOC members believe the system is flawed.  
</P>
<P>
	``Now we have to rely on a book,'' Russia's Vitaly Smirnov said.  
``You have to see and feel the spirit of the city. Can you fall in 
love with a woman just reading about her? No, it's not possible. 
It's the same without seeing the bid cities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marc Hodler, the Swiss member who blew the whistle on Olympic  
corruption in December, disagrees. 
</P>
<P>
	``What is it worth to see a ski course somewhere from a  
helicopter?'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hodler himself could be a factor in the result.  
</P>
<P>
	There has been widespread speculation that some IOC members  
might vote against Sion, and presumably for Turin, to punish Hodler 
for escalating the scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is possible,'' Hodler said. ``But I have many (members)  
testifying that they appreciate what I have done. They have sent me 
many letters. They don't like to be in a club that has a bad 
reputation. I hope this vote can restore some dignity to the IOC.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many believe the race will come down to a contest between a  
small Alpine town (Sion, 26,000) and a large industrial city 
(Turin, 2.2 million). 
</P>
<P>
	The Swiss have looked confident all week, but the Italians have  
been working the lobby hardest. Then there's Helsinki, which could 
also be a finalist. 
</P>
<P>
	That would suit Sion, which would rather face Helsinki than  
Turin in the final, considering Italy's strong influence in the 
IOC. 
</P>
<P>
	But nothing is ever certain in IOC voting.  
</P>
<P>
	Look back to 1988. In the same hotel in Seoul where the IOC is  
meeting this week, a little-known Norwegian village -- Lillehammer -- 
came out of nowhere to win the right to stage the 1994 Winter 
Games. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
