<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Video Health Care Aids Rural Clinics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOBILE, Ala. (AP) -- Suppose sickness strikes, and it's too far  
to reach the hospital. Now there's video medical care for such 
crises. 
</P>
<P>
	New high-tech equipment at University of South Alabama hospitals  
will allow a live image of a patient at a rural clinic to be 
projected into the hospital 100 miles away or more. 
</P>
<P>
	The university's ``Telemedicine'' program, unveiled Tuesday,  
will begin operating July 1. It will be the first of its kind in 
the state, said USA President Gordon Moulton. 
</P>
<P>
	USA-based specialists will be able to offer medical testing,  
diagnoses and drug prescriptions to rural patients using high-speed 
telecommunications lines, video-conferencing and the latest medical 
equipment, such as a tiny ear scope that can send a live image of 
an eardrum for a specialist to view. 
</P>
<P>
	Often, residents living in rural areas do without much-needed  
specialty care because of transportation problems, Moulton said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The best medical treatment in the world is useless if the  
people who need it can't get to it,'' he said. ``This combination 
... is a real boost for area health care.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also suggested its use in state prisons. Moulton said  
university officials will be talking with the state about the 
possibility of saving money by using the video system to treat 
inmates at correctional centers. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new service, four ``health stations'' will be set up  
so specialists can reach patients in outlying areas: Mostellar 
Medical Centers in McIntosh and Bayou La Batre; and the Mobile 
County Health Department clinics. 
</P>
<P>
	Future remote sites also are being proposed for Baldwin, Clarke,  
Conecuh, Monroe, Montgomery and Wilcox counties. 
</P>
<P>
	The stations will link up with USA Medical Center, USA  
Children's and Women's Hospital, USA Knollwood Park Hospital, the 
pediatric and adult clinics on Springhill Avenue and the USA Health 
Services building. 
</P>
<P>
	Units at each of the four health stations will include two  
cameras and examination equipment to give the consulting physician 
the opportunity to conduct a thorough examination. 
</P>
<P>
	Each of the four stations will have access to all services  
offered by the USA Health Network, including dermatology, 
cardiology, gastroenterology, neurology, OB/GYN, pediatrics, 
surgery and trauma services. 
</P>
<P>
	Helping finance the program is a $2.7 million federal grant from  
the U.S. Department of Health's Office for the Advancement of 
Telehealth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
