<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Prices Soar / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices soared Thursday, pushing the yield  
on the 30-year Treasury bond back below 6 percent, as comments by 
Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan were interpreted to mean 
the central bank would only slightly increase interest rates at its 
meeting later this month. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 1 9/32  
point, or $12.81 1/4 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves 
in the opposite direction, fell to 5.96 percent from 6.06 percent 
late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In testimony before the Joint Economic Committee of Congress,  
Greenspan said that when possible, Fed policy-makers should be 
``pre-emptive'' in fighting inflation. With the market 
well-prepared for a tightening, many felt Greenspan's comments 
indicated that the Fed can and will raise rates at the upcoming 
meeting beginning June 29. 
</P>
<P>
	But at the same time, Greenspan hinted that rate hikes could be  
limited, easing market concerns that policy-makers would initiate a 
series of rate increases, reversing all three rate cuts made last 
year. ``Modest pre-emptive actions can obviate the need of more 
drastic actions at a later date,'' Greenspan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan's comments came a day after the Labor Department  
reported that May consumer prices, excluding the volatile energy 
and food categories, rose a modest 0.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The markets had been anxiously awaiting the report as a  
barometer of inflation after a surge in April helped prompt the 
Federal Reserve to warn last month that it might boost interest 
rates to slow the economy's growth. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader bond market, prices of short-term Treasury  
securities were up 1/8 point, and intermediate maturities were up 
between 3/16 point and 11/16 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a 
financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.63 percent as the  
discount fell 0.02 percentage point to 4.51 percent. Six-month 
yields were 4.94 percent, as the discount fell 0.06 percentage 
point to 4.75 percent. One-year yields were 4.92 percent as the 
discount fell by 0.04 percentage point from late Wednesday to 4.69 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 4.75 percent from 4.69 percent late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds rose to 120 5/32 from 119 5/16. The average 
yield to maturity fell to 5.46 percent from 5.50 percent late 
Wednesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
