<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	US, France Agree on Serb Aid Terms  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- President Clinton today advocated a  
``wait-and-see'' approach on seizing Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic to stand trial for atrocities in Kosovo, saying NATO's 
first priority is to get the refugees home. The president spoke to 
reporters outside the Elysee Palace, where he and French President 
Jacques Chirac met today and agreed anew that Milosevic must be 
unseated before any international development aid goes to 
rebuilding Serbia from 78 days of NATO airstrikes. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S., Russia Open 2nd Day of Talks  
</P>
<P>
	HELSINKI, Finland (AP) -- Agreemeent on a Russian role in the  
NATO-led Kosovo peacekeeping operation appeared within reach today. 
U.S. and Russian officials were back at the negotiating table to 
discuss whether Russian peacekeepers would patrol a separate sector 
of Kosovo. The United States and NATO oppose the idea, fearing that 
it would lead to a partitioning of Kosovo and undermine efforts to 
stabilize the province. Asked whether he foresaw a final deal 
today, Defense Secretary William Cohen replied, ``We hope so, but 
there are issues that remain to be resolved.'' In Paris, President 
Clinton predicted a ``successful conclusion'' to the talks. 

</P>
<P>
	17 Die in Papua New Guinea Crash  
</P>
<P>
	PORT MORESBY, Papua New Guinea (AP) -- A plane crashed today in  
mountainous terrain in Papua New Guinea's highlands, killing all 17 
people on board, officials said. A twin-engine turboprop 
Bandierante aircraft operated by Papua New Guinea carrier Airlink 
crashed 12 miles southeast of Goroka, in Eastern Highlands 
province, the Office of Air Safety Investigation said. The aircraft 
was en route from Nadzab, 185 miles north of the capital, Port 
Moresby, to Goroka, 87 miles further west, an air safety 
investigator said. 

</P>
<P>
	Pope Returns to His Birthplace  
</P>
<P>
	KRAKOW, Poland (AP) -- Pope John Paul II extended his pilgrimage  
to Poland by a few hours today to visit the country's holiest 
shrine, making up the stop he missed while he was ill earlier this 
week. The 79-year-old pontiff appeared revitalized today after an 
emotional return to his birthplace of Wadowice last night. Back on 
his feet after a bout of flu, John Paul said a private Mass for 
friends and seminarians today at Krakow's 14th century Wawel 
Cathedral, where he celebrated his first Mass upon becoming a 
priest in 1946. 

</P>
<P>
	Indian Navy Said To Be on Alert  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- A Pakistani military buildup in the  
Arabian Sea has prompted India to put its navy on alert there, The 
Times of India reported today. The move also aroused fear that 
fighting in Kashmir between the two nuclear neighbors could spread 
to the seas. Indian soldiers are trying to cut off ammunition and 
food supplies to Islamic guerrillas entrenched on the snowy 
mountaintops on the Indian-held side of the disputed territory. 

</P>
<P>
	Turkish Troops Kill 19 Kurdish Rebels  
</P>
<P>
	ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Turkish troops killed 19 Kurdish  
guerrillas in separate clashes in the country's southeast, a news 
agency reported today. Four soldiers were also killed. Fighting 
between Turkish troops and autonomy seeking rebels has escalated 
since Kurdish guerrilla leader Abdullah Ocalan was put on trial on 
charges of treason and separatism. Ocalan's Kurdistan Workers Party 
took up arms for autonomy in the southeast in 1984. Some 37,000 
people have been killed in clashes since then. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stock Prices Close Higher  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Overnight gains on Wall Street helped push the  
major barometer for Japanese stocks to a 20-month high today. The 
Nikkei gained 260.27 points to close at 17,470.45. 

</P>
<P>
	Phillies 4, Padres 2  
</P>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Randy Wolf followed his successful major league  
debut with an even stronger effort, holding San Diego to five hits 
in eight innings and getting his first hit as the Philadelphia 
Phillies beat the Padres 4-2 last night. Wolf won his debut on 
Friday, allowing one earned run and six hits in 5 2-3 innings in 
beating the Toronto Blue Jays 8-4 at Philadelphia. Wolf, who's from 
the Los Angeles area, allowed one earned run against the Padres, 
struck out seven and walked two. 

</P>
<P>
	Cardinals 5, Expos 4  
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Kent Bottenfield became the NL's second 10-game  
winner and Fernando Tatis homered as the St. Louis Cardinals beat 
the Montreal Expos 5-4 last night. Bottenfield lasted five innings 
and allowed two earned run. He's one victory behind league leader 
Jose Lima of Houston after entering the year with a career record 
of 18-27. Bottenfield had never won more than five games in a 
season before this year. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
</P>
