<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Greene Sets 100M Record of 9.79 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- Maurice Greene made a quick decision to  
enter the 100-meter invitational race. He then ran the fastest time 
in history. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene shattered the 3-year-old world record Wednesday, running  
away from an elite field for a clocking of 9.79 seconds. He has 
ambitions to run even faster. 
</P>
<P>
	Greene came to Athens planning only to run the 200 meters. When  
he saw the caliber of competition in the 100 -- including training 
partner Ato Boldon of Trinidad &AMP; Tobago -- he asked for a place in 
the field. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said, `They can't have a party without me,''' Greene said.  
``I knew something was going to happen with this race. I wanted to 
be part of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Greene calls Athens' Olympic Stadium a ``special place.'' In  
1997, he won the 100-meter world championship gold medal in the 
venue that will be the site of the 2004 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, on a sultry and near windless evening just before  
sundown, he again blasted away from the pack and smashed the 
previous record of 9.84 set by Donovan Bailey of Canada at the 1996 
Atlanta Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``I expected it,'' Greene said. ``I wanted to win it here ...  
This is only the beginning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd gave the 24-year-old Greene a standing ovation as he  
hugged some other athletes and waved the banner of his track club 
HSI, which stands for Handling Speed Intelligently. He looked for 
an American flag, but there were none handy. 
</P>
<P>
	He wanted to tell his mother the news by phone, but she wasn't  
home. He simply left a message: ``I did it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even as he basked in the record, he was looking ahead. ``I can  
do better,'' he said, setting his next goal at 9.76. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a start, but not a finish,'' Greene, the world's  
top-ranked sprinter last year, said. ``It was a good race, but not 
a great race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The .05-second difference between Bailey's mark and Greene's is  
the biggest drop the record has taken since the first officially 
accepted electronic record of 9.95 by Jim Hines at the 1968 
Olympics in Mexico City. 
</P>
<P>
	The last American to own the record was Leroy Burrell, who ran  
9.85 in 1994 at Lausanne, Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	Boldon, who trains with Greene under coach John Smith, was awed  
by his friend's performance. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's very significant we came to the birthplace of  
track and field to break this record,'' said Boldon, who placed 
second in the special race at 9.86. Bruny Surin of Canada was third 
at 9.97. 
</P>
<P>
	Boldon won the regular 100-meter race at 9.97.  
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month in Milan, Italy, Greene won the 100 at 10.16  
and insisted he was only concerned about the competition and not 
the clock. ``I am not obsessed with the world record,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Less than 90 minutes after setting the record, Greene finished  
second in the 200 at 20.03, behind Boldon's winning time of 19.86. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1,500 meters, Noah Ngeny led a Kenyan sweep of the first  
three places in 3 minutes, 31.32 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	Morocco's Nezha Bidouane won the women's 400 hurdles at 53.54,  
more than a second ahead of world record-holder Kim Batten, who 
finished at 54.73. Batten set the world mark of 52.61 in 1995. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
