<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Belo Acquires Denton Publishing Co. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- A.H. Belo Corp. announced Thursday it has acquired  
Denton Publishing Co., which publishes the Denton Record-Chronicle 
and two free-distribution newspapers just northwest of Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the transaction were not disclosed.  
</P>
<P>
	Belo publishes The Dallas Morning News and six other newspapers,  
including The Providence (R.I.) Journal, and also has extensive 
television holdings. 
</P>
<P>
	The Record-Chronicle, an afternoon newspaper with a circulation  
of 16,000 daily and 19,000 on Sundays, had been under family 
ownership since 1945. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Patterson, executive vice president and general manager of  
the Denton Publishing Co., will serve as publisher of the 
Record-Chronicle under Belo's ownership. 
</P>
<P>
	Belo also acquired The Lewisville News, which is published three  
times a week, and the Grapevine Sun, published twice a week. Each 
newspaper has a circulation of about 20,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Belo's other newspapers are The Eagle in Bryan-College Station;  
the Arlington Morning News in Arlington; The Press-Enterprise in 
Riverside, Calif.; the Messenger-Inquirer in Owensboro, Ky., and 
The Gleaner in Henderson, Ky. 
</P>
<P>
	Its television group includes WFAA in Dallas-Fort Worth, KHOU in  
Houston, KING-TV in Seattle-Tacoma and 17 other stations. Belo also 
manages four television stations through local marketing agreements 
and owns four local or regional cable news channels. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
