<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sabres Go Home Facing Elimination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- If the Buffalo Sabres are going to win the Stanley  
Cup, they're going to have to do it the hard way. 
</P>
<P>
	A 2-0 loss to the Dallas Stars Thursday night put the Sabres on  
the brink of elimination for the first time this postseason. 
Buffalo trails 3-2 in the best-of-7 series. 
</P>
<P>
	Only three of 15 teams which have lost Game 5 of a tied finals  
have rebounded to win the championship, none since the 1971 
Montreal Canadiens. 
</P>
<P>
	For the Sabres to do it, the seventh-seeded team from the East  
must win two straight, beginning with Game 6 Saturday night in 
Buffalo. The Sabres are 8-1 at Marine Midland Arena in the 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo had chances early as Dallas committed many of the same  
mistakes it made in the Sabres' 2-1 victory in Game 4. But the 
Sabres rarely challenged Stars goaltender Ed Belfour -- and when 
they did, he was sharp. 
</P>
<P>
	Jay McKee and Geoff Sanderson each got good looks as they were  
flying across open ice, but Belfour saw the shots all the way and 
caught both. 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo create traffic in front of Belfour with about six  
minutes left, but didn't have a player in the right place at the 
right time. 
</P>
<P>
	One shot deflected just wide of the post, and Belfour went  
behind the net to make a save when the puck came off the boards. 
Shortly thereafter, he let a rebound squirt into the zone but he 
dove on it before any Sabres arrived. 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo goalie Dominik Hasek kept his team within a goal for  
more than 55 minutes until getting faked out of position on a 
2-on-1 and allowing a goal by Pat Verbeek. It gave Dallas a 
two-goal lead for only the second time this series, the only other 
being the final 26 seconds of Game 3. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres trailed 1-0 early in the second period on a  
power-play goal by the Stars. Buffalo had overcome a similar 
deficit in Game 1 when Dallas tried playing keep-away to protect 
its lead. The Stars didn't make that mistake this time and the 
Sabres weren't able to slow their aggressiveness. 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo had just two power plays in the game, one in each of the  
first two periods. The Sabres didn't get off a shot on the second. 
</P>
<P>
	This is only the third time Buffalo has trailed a series in the  
playoffs. The Sabres were down 1-0 to Boston in the second round 
and were in a 2-1 hole against the Stars. 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo had not been shut out this postseason. The Sabres are  
8-2 in one-goal games, with the losses coming to the Stars in Games 
3 and 5. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
