<DOCNO> APW19990617.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 11:50:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Authority Over Assets Limited </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal judges generally cannot protect  
plaintiffs in lawsuits by barring defendants from spending or 
giving away their assets, the Supreme Court ruled Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In a 5-4 decision, the justices said a New York federal judge  
could not bar a consortium of Mexican companies from transferring 
assets while they were being sued by U.S. investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Traditionally, creditors must first win judgment in a case,  
Justice Antonin Scalia wrote for the court. 
</P>
<P>
	Allowing them to get a court order beforehand ``could radically  
alter the balance between debtor's and creditor's rights,'' Scalia 
said, and ``might induce creditors to engage in a race to the 
courthouse ... which might prove financially fatal to the 
struggling debtor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Any such change in judges' authority should be made by Congress,  
not the courts, Scalia said. His opinion was joined by Chief 
Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, 
Anthony M. Kennedy and Clarence Thomas. 
</P>
<P>
	Justices Ruth Bader Ginsburg, John Paul Stevens, David H. Souter  
and Stephen G. Breyer dissented. 
</P>
<P>
	Writing for the four, Ginsburg said such orders may not have  
been needed in a long-ago ``age of slow-moving capital and 
comparatively immobile wealth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But now that assets can be transferred almost instantly, courts  
should be allowed to keep defendants from ``making themselves 
judgment-proof'' by transferring assets during a lawsuit, she 
wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal appeals court had upheld the New York federal judge's  
order issued against Grupo Mexicano de Desarrollo. 
</P>
<P>
	The consortium participated from 1990 to 1994 in the Mexican  
government's program to develop an intercity highway network. When 
road toll revenue fell below expected levels, Grupo Mexicano sought 
to raise money by selling notes, including $75 million to 11 U.S. 
investment funds. 
</P>
<P>
	The consortium defaulted on an interest payment on the notes in  
1997, and the Mexican government promised to provide about $309 
million in notes. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. investors sued in federal court in New York. The  
investors told the judge the consortium already had assigned some 
of the $309 million to other creditors in Mexico and that if it 
continued to do so, the U.S. investors might not be able to collect 
any judgment they won. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge issued a preliminary order barring Grupo Mexicano from  
transferring or assigning its right to the Mexican government 
notes, and the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld that order. 
The judge later awarded $82.4 million to the U.S. investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The Supreme Court on Thursday, acting on the Mexican  
consortium's appeal on the asset transfer ban, reversed the appeals 
court's ruling. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 02:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Director Loyal to Samaranch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The IOC general assembly opened today  
with a senior administrator denying rumors of an in-house plot 
against President Juan Antonio Samaranch and pledging loyalty to 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	Francois Carrard, director general of the International Olympic  
Committee, addressed speculation that he and other staff at IOC 
headquarters in Lausanne, Switzerland, were working to oust 
Samaranch. 
</P>
<P>
	``There have been some rumors floating around,'' Carrard told  
the delegates. ``The entire administration and secretariat are 
fully dedicated to serving the institution, and we all totally 
support our president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carrard's statement came at the start of the 109th IOC session,  
whose deliberations were opened to the media for the first time in 
history. The proceedings were beamed to journalists via 
closed-circuit television feed. 
</P>
<P>
	The first order of business was the swearing-in of new members,  
including Crown Prince Willem-Alexander, heir to the Dutch throne. 
The prince's IOC membership was questioned by Dutch 
parliamentarians following the Olympic corruption scandal, but the 
government gave its go-ahead when the IOC took steps toward reform. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Samaranch dismissed as ``rumors'' the recent  
published reports that IOC staff have plotted against him, and 
expressed support for Carrard. 
</P>
<P>
	``Always we have rumors,'' he told reporters. ``I am not  
worried. Nothing has happened. ... In an organization like ours, we 
have to be used to rumors. But rumors are rumors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch also reiterated he intends to complete the final two  
years of his term and declared the IOC won't rush into reforms to 
appease critics. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech at the opening ceremony of the assembly, Samaranch  
said the committee already had taken important steps toward reform 
following the Salt Lake City bribery scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	But he stressed the IOC would move at its own pace and on its  
own terms. 
</P>
<P>
	``We say `yes' to reforms necessary to consolidate the Olympic  
movement, without renouncing our convictions,'' he said. ``We say 
`no' to hasty reforms to please our critics. 
</P>
<P>
	``No to reforms which defend the interests of some at the  
expense of others. No to reforms based on personal and conflicting 
interests.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the speech, Samaranch sought to erase any further speculation  
that he might retire early. 
</P>
<P>
	``My concern is to leave to my successor, at the end of my term  
in 2001, an institution which is over 100 years old, solid and 
beyond reproach,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, in a breakfast meeting with a small group of reporters,  
Samaranch was eager to put across the same point. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am not leaving,'' he said. ``I have decided to go until the  
end of my mandate. The only thing that can stop me is if I don't 
have the confidence of IOC members or if I am ill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also refuted suggestions of a rift with IOC vice president  
Dick Pound, who has publicly speculated that Samaranch might retire 
after reforms are made at the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch, who has been president since 1980 and turns 79 next  
month, released a letter signed by the 10 members of the executive 
board -- including Pound -- endorsing his continued leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	``In these difficult times of crisis wrought with danger, a  
strong, wise, trusted leadership is essential,'' the letter said. 
``We unanimously support you ... and ask you to continue to devote 
your time to the Olympic movement as president of the IOC, until 
the end of your present mandate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The four-day IOC session will include progress reports from  
organizers of the 2000 Sydney Olympics and 2002 Winter Games in 
Salt Lake City. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, the IOC will elect the host city of the 2006 Winter  
Games. The six cities in the all-European race are Helsinki, 
Finland; Klagenfurt, Austria; Poprad-Tatry, Slovakia; Sion, 
Switzerland; Turin, Italy; and Zakopane, Poland. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
