<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Deficit Holds at Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- America's trade deficit held steady at a  
record high in April, with some signs that U.S. companies may be 
seeing relief from a global financial crisis that has depressed 
overseas markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department said today that the April trade deficit  
was $18.9 billion -- matching a revised estimate of the deficit in 
March. The government's original estimate had pegged the March 
deficit at $19.7 billion. The new, lower March estimate, however, 
was still a record that was tied in April. 
</P>
<P>
	Global economic troubles that started nearly two years ago in  
Asia have continued to hamper America's trade performance. The U.S. 
trade deficit is running at an annual rate of $218.1 billion, 
compared to the all-time high of $169.3 billion set last year. 
</P>
<P>
	During the international financial crisis, overseas markets for  
American products have dwindled and a flood of imports from 
troubled countries trying to unload their own goods here at 
discount prices has given American manufacturers stiff competition. 
</P>
<P>
	However, since other countries began a tentative recovery from  
recession this spring, American exports have started to pick up 
again. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. exports, which had fallen for five previous months staged a  
small comeback in April. Exports rose 1.2 percent to $78 billion, 
including all categories from food to toys to cars. 
</P>
<P>
	Imports, however, have also continued to rise, climbing 1  
percent to $97 billion in April, a record high. Imports of foods, 
feeds and beverages reached a record $3.5 billion and imports of 
consumer and industrial goods were also up. 
</P>
<P>
	Among several bright spots, imports of motor vehicles and parts  
declined in April by 5.9 percent. Also, imports from Japan 
declined, pulling the sensitive deficit with Japan down 13.1 
percent to $5.6 billion, the first drop since November. 
</P>
<P>
	The trade deficit with Mexico, a partner in the North American  
Free Trade Agreement, also declined in April by 32.5 percent to 
$1.7 billion due to a sharp drop in imports. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the April deficit with countries belonging to the  
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries -- which agreed this 
spring to limit production in the face of falling world demand for 
oil -- more than doubled in April to $1.8 billion, the most since 
October 1997. That was largely due to a sharp spike in oil and gas 
prices because of the production limits. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, imports from China rose to $5.8 billion, the highest since  
November. That helped push the U.S. trade deficit with China -- the 
second- biggest with any country behind Japan -- up by 15.7 percent 
to $4.8 billion in April. 
</P>
<P>
	America's deficit with the 15-nation European Union, meanwhile,  
increased by 9.7 percent to $2.9 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration argues that the overall trade deficit  
has a positive side: As the only major economy doing well, the 
United States is playing a valuable role providing markets for 
other countries struggling to get back on their feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists also note that cheap imports have helped keep  
inflation low here during a period of unusually high employment and 
heavy spending by Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department issued a separate report today showing that  
low U.S. unemployment is continuing. The number of Americans filing 
new claims for unemployment benefits fell by 28,000 last week to 
297,000. A more closely watched four-week moving average of 
first-time jobless claims also dropped, by 750 to 308,250 in the 
previous week. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration is worried that too big a trade deficit could  
cause American industries to pressure Congress for protectionist 
measures. 
</P>
<P>
	Already, the steel industry has won a vote in the House to  
impose global quotas on imports despite a presidential veto threat. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate report today, the Commerce Department said steel  
imports fell by 8.6 percent in April, less than the 14 percent the 
government had first estimated. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration says the United States cannot sustain such  
high trade deficits and that other economic powers, such as Japan 
and Europe, must do their part by boosting growth at home. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
