<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Upholds Va. Death Sentence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court upheld a Virginia murderer's  
death sentence today, ruling that state prosecutors did not violate 
Tommy David Strickler's rights by withholding evidence he said 
would have helped his case. 
</P>
<P>
	The 7-2 decision means Virginia authorities are free to schedule  
an execution date for Strickler. 
</P>
<P>
	Strickler ``has not shown that there is a reasonable probability  
that his conviction or sentence would have been different had these 
materials been disclosed,'' Justice John Paul Stevens wrote for the 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	Strickler, from New Market, and Ronald Lee Henderson of Frost,  
W.Va., were convicted in the 1990 murder of 19-year-old Leanne 
Whitlock, a sophomore at James Madison University in Harrisonburg, 
Va. 
</P>
<P>
	Strickler's Supreme Court appeal focused on certain helpful  
evidence -- statements to police by an eyewitness to Whitlock's 
abduction from a Harrisonburg shopping mall parking lot. 
</P>
<P>
	Police and prosecutors had not disclosed before trial the  
testimony to be offered by eyewitness Anne Stoltzfus. 
</P>
<P>
	In a series of decisions dating back to 1965, the Supreme Court  
has ruled that the Constitution requires prosecutors to disclose 
all material evidence favorable to criminal defendants. 
</P>
<P>
	Material evidence is defined as that which probably would have  
changed a case's outcome if it had been disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's decision was based on the facts of Strickler's case, and  
did not appear to alter the previous Supreme Court rulings. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitlock was last seen alive Jan. 5, 1990. Her body was found  
eight days later in a wooded area of Augusta County. Police said 
her head had been struck four times with a 69-pound boulder. 
</P>
<P>
	Anne Stoltzfus testified at Strickler's trial that she saw him  
and others abduct Whitlock from the mall parking lot. 
</P>
<P>
	Strickler's lawyer later learned that reports held by local  
police indicated that Stoltzfus initially had been unable to 
identify Strickler, and that she gave police the license tag number 
on Whitlock's car only after seeing it in an impoundment lot. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time that information was learned, Strickler's conviction  
and death sentence had been upheld on direct appeals to the 
Virginia Supreme Court and the nation's highest court. 
</P>
<P>
	He sought help from a federal trial judge, who overturned his  
conviction and death sentence. But the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of 
Appeals last year reinstated both, ruling that Strickler had given 
up his right to raise the undisclosed-evidence issue in federal 
court by failing to raise it in his state court appeals. 
</P>
<P>
	The Supreme Court disagreed with that point but said Strickler  
must lose anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	``Notwithstanding the obvious significance of Stoltzfus'  
testimony, (Strickler) has not convinced us that there is a 
reasonable probability that the jury would have returned a 
different verdict if her testimony had been either severely 
impeached or excluded entirely,'' Stevens said. 
</P>
<P>
	Justices David H. Souter and Anthony M. Kennedy dissented.  
Writing for the two, Souter said, ``I believe there is a reasonable 
probability ... that disclosure of Stoltzfus' materials would have 
led the jury to recommend life, not death.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Strickler vs. Greene, 98-5864.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
