<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian Women Bring Same Style </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- They're good, they're flashy, they're popular.  
And they can samba as well as any of their male counterparts. 
</P>
<P>
	There will be plenty of dance moves in the stands and lots of  
flamboyant maneuvers on the field whenever the Brazilian women play 
in the World Cup that begins Saturday. This team doesn't carry 
anywhere near the credentials of their countrymen, who have won 
four world titles, but they might be just as entertaining. 
</P>
<P>
	And without the pressure that always accompanies Brazil's men,  
who are favorites in nearly every event they enter, these women 
just might go far in the tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will be one of the surprises of the World Cup,'' coach  
Wilson de Oliveira promised as his team prepared to play Mexico in 
the second game of a Saturday doubleheader at Giants Stadium. The 
United States faces Denmark in the opener, with perhaps 75,000 fans 
on hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are preparing ourselves for our goal of Olympic qualifying  
by being one of the last eight teams in the World Cup. But we 
really believe we can aim for the top four and then see.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Brazil has an illustrious history in the men's game, it is  
a relative newcomer to the top level of women's soccer. Indeed, the 
men had won their first three World Cups and were headed for their 
unprecedented fourth before a national women's squad was in place. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1981, coach Eurico Lira started the Radar team and, in  
general, gave birth to women's soccer in Brazil. Lira is as much a 
hero to the Brazilian women as Pele is to all Brazilians. 
</P>
<P>
	``He fought for the girls,'' said defender Elane, who played for  
Radar for five years. ``He fought for the local games and local 
teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``In 1988, he got us all the equipment and uniforms and he went  
to the Brazil confederation to let them know of the women playing 
soccer. He asked for their support to go to China for a pre-World 
Cup tournament.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lira got the federation's approval, if not its financial  
backing. He paid the team's expenses, and with 16 of the 18 players 
from his Radar club, Brazil wound up third in the event. 
</P>
<P>
	``He passed away, sadly, several years ago,'' Wilson said. ``But  
his memory lives on, because he founded women's soccer in Brazil 
and the team is progressing in his memory.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil didn't fare well in the inaugural Women's World Cup in  
1991, finishing ninth. It didn't do any better at the 1995 
tournament, again finishing ninth. 
</P>
<P>
	But with clubs sprouting throughout the nation, under the  
confederation's leadership and financial support, the women's game 
began to flourish in the South American soccer powerhouse. Although 
the Brazilians did not qualify for the Atlanta Olympics, they were 
invited when England dropped out. They took advantage, tying world 
champion Norway and Germany to make the semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	They wound up fourth.  
</P>
<P>
	``Brazil might be the most improved team in the world,'' U.S.  
coach Tony DiCicco said. 
</P>
<P>
	Pretinha, the team's most dangerous scorer and one of the best  
players in the world, agrees. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our success is very important for women in Brazil to able to  
get a job and get paid as a player,'' she said. ``So we strive to 
get much better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As they improve, the Brazilians also become more popular. When  
Pretinha walks down the street back home, people notice her and 
call her name. They ask for autographs. They take pictures. 
</P>
<P>
	``After the Olympics, I couldn't walk anywhere, because it would  
create a mob,'' she said. ``I love it. It's an acknowledgment of 
me, and of our team, and of women's soccer.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
