<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 13:10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mayfield Chases Second Victory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONG POND, Pa. (AP) -- Jeremy Mayfield hadn't finished  
celebrating the first win of his career when the rain fell in 
torrents. 
</P>
<P>
	Was this an omen?  
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps not.  
</P>
<P>
	But a year after the abbreviated ceremony in the winner's circle  
at Pocono International Raceway, he is still looking for victory 
No. 2. 
</P>
<P>
	``You never forget your first win, but we were hoping it would  
be one of a blur of Victory Lane memories by now,'' Mayfield said. 
``It's time to win again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He'll try to do that Sunday, when he defends his title in the  
Pocono 500. If anything, he is more anxious now than he was as a 
winless driver on the Winston Cup circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had a lot of people tell me the first win was the hardest,  
but I wonder about that,'' Mayfield said on the eve of qualifying 
for the race. ``Right now, the second win is the hardest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mayfield is confident, not only because he's back at the scene  
of his only triumph in six years on the circuit. He figures he's 
ready to break out, and finds this portion of the schedule to his 
liking. 
</P>
<P>
	After some difficult times -- which resulted in the departure of  
crew chief Paul Andrews and his replacement by Peter Sospenzo -- the 
Penske-Kranefuss Ford team is showing signs of renewed vigor. 
</P>
<P>
	After winning a year ago, Mayfield was leading in the points  
race before fading to finish eighth. This season, after climbing 
two positions in three races under Sospenzo, he is 11th. 
</P>
<P>
	``The top-10s are starting to come consistently again,'' said  
Mayfield, who finished among the elite in a non-points race, The 
Winston, then followed with similar efforts in the Coca-Cola 600 
and the MBNA 400 before a late pit stop cost him a top-10 spot last 
Sunday in the Kmart 400. ``We're on some good tracks for me and for 
this team like Pocono, Dover, Michigan and Daytona.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 2 1/2-mile Pocono triangle suited Mayfield well last year, when  
he led this race for 122 of 200 laps. 
</P>
<P>
	So, Mayfield is hungry for victory. But Mark Martin and Jeff  
Gordon -- who combined to win 20 of 33 races last season -- also are 
anxious. 
</P>
<P>
	``We should be strong at Pocono,'' said Martin's crew chief,  
Jimmy Fennig. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Pocono is one of only four tracks on which Martin has  
not won, he has 16 top-10 finishes in 24 starts. After seven 
victories last year, Martin has only one in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	``We may be fourth in the points now, but hope to move up before  
long,'' Fennig said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon has farther to go than Martin if he wants to reach the  
top of the standings. Despite three victories, Gordon is sixth -- 
349 points behind leader Dale Jarrett -- because of accidents and 
mechanical failures. 
</P>
<P>
	But Pocono has been good to Gordon, a two-time winner of the  
event who also took the second of the two annual races on the 
mountaintop last year. He led 164 laps in the Pennsylvania 500. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to worry about running good and winning races,''  
said Gordon, who figures that's the only way to transform what now 
seems like an insurmountable deficit into a legitimate run at a 
record-tying third straight championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Jarrett, a two-time Pocono winner, has earned his spot at the  
top with 11 top-five finishes in 14 races. Although he's coming off 
a rout of the field last Sunday in Brooklyn, Mich. -- Jarrett's 
second victory this season -- his plan for a championship run is 
based on consistency. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're happy,'' he said. ``We just have to stay away from those  
bad days. Whenever problems occur, we just have to stay away from 
the 15th- and 20th-place finishes.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
