<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pope Extends Trip to Poland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KRAKOW, Poland (AP) -- Seemingly revitalized after sharing  
boyhood memories with thousands in his hometown, Pope John Paul II 
extended his pilgrimage to Poland by a few hours today -- and hinted 
he'd be back. 
</P>
<P>
	Many have speculated that the trip may be the frail, 79-year-old  
pontiff's last to his native land, a fear compounded by health 
troubles during his stay. 
</P>
<P>
	And as the crowd in Gliwice, a southern town in the industrial  
and mining region of Silesia, implored him to stay longer, he 
responded playfully: ``The next time, we'll see.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With only a short notice, workers hurriedly put a stage and  
throne back together for John Paul, back on his feet after a bout 
of flu on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	About 500,000 faithful flocked to the site where John Paul was  
originally scheduled to say prayers Tuesday night, when the pope 
was forced to stay in bed with a fever. 
</P>
<P>
	``May God reward you for your saintly patience,'' he told the  
crowd after brief prayers. ``I would never stand such a pope. He's 
coming, he's not coming, then he does come ...'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Never mind,'' the crowd chanted.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm glad you say it doesn't matter,'' he replied. ``I'll go  
back to Rome with a clear conscience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then he flew by helicopter for a previously unscheduled stop in  
Czestochowa, where Poland's holiest shrine, the Black Madonna, is 
kept at the Jasna Gora monastery. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to stay but they tell me I have to go,'' the rushed  
pope told 250,000 people gathered there. 
</P>
<P>
	His planned departure today for Rome was pushed back to 6:15  
p.m. (12:15 p.m. EDT) to allow for the sidetrips. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, the pope said a private Mass for a few dozen friends  
and guests at Krakow's 14th century Wawel Cathedral, where he 
celebrated his first Mass upon becoming a priest in 1946. 
</P>
<P>
	As in his past trips, he also stopped at Rakowicki cemetery,  
where his parents and elder brother are buried. Shielded from a 
light rain by a white umbrella, he lighted a candle by the graves 
and prayed on his knees for five minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday night, John Paul departed from his prepared text to  
share a flood of memories with thousands in Wadowice, a small town 
where he grew up outside Krakow. 
</P>
<P>
	Sitting in the market square renamed in his honor, he reminisced  
about his past, from happy times sharing sweets with school chums 
to the dark days when the town lost its Jews during World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	His recollections sometimes brought tears to people's eyes, as  
when he recited the inscription on a sundial he saw outside his 
window every day: ``Time flies, eternity awaits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later, he recalled his family's Jewish landlord. ``I don't know  
what happened to him. I think he is dead,'' he said somberly. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know that Wadowice Jews went through hard trials and many  
died in ghettos, then in Nazi extermination camps.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The nostalgic side of his 13-day trip was in doubt after John  
Paul came down with a slight fever Monday night. But the Vatican 
said Wednesday the pope had recovered, after canceling all public 
appearances Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the Vatican dropped a last-minute trip to Armenia planned  
for Friday and postponed a Sunday visit to a Rome sanctuary to give 
him more time for rest after he returns home. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
