<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Family Goes Online After Flooding / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) -- Kent and Ali Bahl cannot reach most of  
their north-central North Dakota farmland by tractor to plant their 
spring crops. More than 12 inches of rain since May 1 have made 
that impossible. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Bahls have created access to their flooded land in a  
different way. It's an Internet page showing aerial pictures of the 
flooding, and it has sparked worldwide interest from people 
intrigued by the overwhelming amount of water. 
</P>
<P>
	``We sit out here in rural North Dakota, and we've had responses  
from Geneva, Switzerland; Buenos Aires, Argentina; a lot of heads 
of state agencies,'' Kent Bahl said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bahls hope their Web page will help people understand the  
devastation facing families in the flooded area. The site has 
received more than 4,500 hits in two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Ali Bahl designs Web pages from the family farm nine miles south  
of the Canadian border in Renville County, about 20 miles from 
Mohall, N.D. 
</P>
<P>
	Her business, Ali's Creative Home Page Design, has been mainly a  
hobby. But it could be a source of income this year, given the 
sorry state of the family's waterlogged fields. The Bahls hope 
their Internet site will generate money from advertisers and 
business from prospective Web page customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to keep shoes on the girls' feet. It will butter  
our bread,'' said Ali Bahl, a self-taught computer buff and mother 
of two. The Bahls are expecting a third child in September. 
</P>
<P>
	Kent Bahl was going out Thursday to seed 100 acres -- a crop he  
concedes probably won't reach maturity by the time the ground 
freezes. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like going up to the ... dice table and throwing the dice  
and not knowing what's going to happen,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's more of an addiction than anything,'' he added. ``We  
gotta have something. It's a long time until the next payday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bahl said his fields are so wet that he will plant only about  
800 acres this year. In normal years, he plants 4,000 acres -- 
mostly durum and spring wheat, sunflowers and canola. 
</P>
<P>
	He said an 80-acre field across the road normally contains two  
sloughs. At the peak of the torrents last month, he counted 38 
pools of water that had gobbled up farmland. ``My dad is 80, and 
he's never seen not being able to farm,'' Bahl said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bahls aren't alone. Farmers throughout the region have been  
flooded this spring. The situation is worse to the east, in 
Bottineau and Rolette Counties. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Albright, executive director for the Renville County Farm  
Service Agency, estimates between 33 percent and 40 percent of the 
county's farmland will go unplanted this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Bahl and other swamped farmers are using a crop insurance method  
called ``prevented planting'' to stay in business. Farmers have the 
option of not planting the crop and receiving crop insurance 
payments that are less than what they would get if they planted a 
crop that later was wiped out. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers say the flooding effects will trickle down to rural  
economies already struggling because of low commodity prices and 
crop disease. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's total devastation, and the trickle-down effect is going  
to be unbelievable,'' Bahl said. ``We love to spend money if we 
have it, but if we don't, the checkbook is shut.'' 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- The Bahls' Web page address is:  
www.ndak.net/(tilde)laj/rain.html on the Internet. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
