<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GoTo.com Plans IPO As Market Cools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- Fledgling Web search engine company  
GoTo.com Inc. plans to go public Friday, hitting the market just as 
investors appear to be losing their appetite for Internet stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	GoTo.com executives hope the initial public offering raises a  
windfall of cash, as stock offerings have done for other Internet 
companies over the past year. 
</P>
<P>
	But the big, easy money from IPOs may be a thing of the past,  
analysts say. A steady slide in Internet stocks suggests investors 
have begun to look askance at sky-high valuations and are deciding 
that some stocks aren't a good bet. 
</P>
<P>
	``Investors have become more discriminating in their choice of  
IPOs,'' said Youssef Squali, an analyst with Ladenburg Thalmann &AMP; 
Co. ``We're in the process now where we will continue to see 
successful IPOs, but nothing compared to what we've seen in the 
past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	GoTo.com plans to sell 5 million shares at $13 to $14 per share  
in a bid to raise up to $70 million for the company that emerged 
last year from idealabs!, the Pasadena, Calif., incubator founded 
by Bill Gross. 
</P>
<P>
	Like many Internet companies, GoTo.com has yet to turn a profit.  
In filings with the Securities and Exchange Commission, the company 
said it has lost $21 million since it was founded in 1997 and will 
continue to lose money for the foreseeable future. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues have grown, however, jumping in the first quarter of  
1999 to $1.4 million from $38,000 a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	SEC rules prohibit company officials from commenting in the  
period before an IPO is launched. 
</P>
<P>
	IPOs have provided big initial returns for other companies that  
have yet to make money. Just last month, Santa Monica, Calif.-based 
eToys Inc. raised $166 million with an offering in which the share 
price jumped from $20 to $85 as investors snapped up the company's 
stock. 
</P>
<P>
	But since its hefty opening, eToys has fallen more than 50  
percent from its high, trading Thursday at $40 on the Nasdaq Stock 
Market. 
</P>
<P>
	Other high-profile Internet stocks, including Amazon.com Inc.  
and Priceline.com Inc. have taken a beating in recent weeks. 
National Discount Brokers Group, an online stock brokerage, on 
Tuesday canceled its plans to sell 2.6 million new shares because 
of market conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet stocks did get a slight bounce this week, sending the  
Dow Jones Internet Index up 22 percent on Wednesday. The market was 
up slightly in trading Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	But even with the jump, the index was down 36 percent since  
peaking on April 13. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors are likely to remain cautious in the long term, said  
Jack Staff, chief economist at Zona Research. 
</P>
<P>
	``What you're finding now is the Internet is starting to  
mature,'' he said. ``We have long said that as soon as some of the 
Internet companies start to make their first profits, there will be 
a softening in the Internet sector as a whole because Internet 
stocks will go from being stocks of possibility to stocks of 
reality.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There are indications GoTo.com's pay-for-play business model may  
be working. In GoTo.com's system, clients bid a price they are 
willing to pay for a high ranking on results pages. The name of the 
highest bidder appears at the top of the page, with others ranked 
in descending order according to their bid. 
</P>
<P>
	A note attached to each link on GoTo.com's results page tells  
users how much a company paid to be there. For example, a search 
for ``books'' turned up Best Buy at the top of the list; it paid 57 
cents for the placement. (Amazon.com was second -- it paid 56 
cents). 
</P>
<P>
	This system contrasts with most other search engines, which make  
money from selling ads that appear on their Web pages. 
</P>
<P>
	Users don't seem to mind. Between Jan. 1 and April 30, searches  
via GoTo.com increased 85 percent to more than 1 million per month, 
and the clientele of paying advertisers grew 150 percent to more 
than 7,500. 
</P>
<P>
	During April, GoTo.com attracted 7.2 percent of all Web surfers,  
placing it 10th among search engines, according to Media Metrix. 
</P>
<P>
	In its IPO, GoTo.com has an advantage in its connection to the  
entrepreneur Gross, said Squali. His idealabs! was home to other 
successful startups, including eToys, CitySearch and PetsMart. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now I think the Internet companies that can still make it are  
companies that are relatively dominant in their niche market or 
companies that have strong backing from well-known venture 
capitalists or have a very strong management team,'' said Squali. 
``I think GoTo.com falls in the second category.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
