<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	House OKs Posting of 10 Commandments  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House voted today to allow the Ten  
Commandments to be posted in schools and other government 
buildings. By 248-180, lawmakers approved Rep. Robert Aderholt's 
amendment to a juvenile crime bill that would allow states to 
decide whether to permit such displays on government property. The 
amendment, Aderholt said, was a ``first step'' for government in 
reinstilling the value of human life in children influenced by 
violent culture. 

</P>
<P>
	U.K. Official: Serbs Killed 10,000  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Gruesome accounts of almost routine  
torture and death emerged in Kosovo today, and a British official 
estimated that Serb forces killed more than 10,000 people during 
two months of war and ethnic violence. At least 10,000 ethnic 
Albanians -- and probably many more -- were killed by Serbs in more 
than 100 massacres even while NATO bombed Yugoslavia during the 
78-day air campaign that ended last week, the British foreign 
office said. Officials from Moscow and Washington met in Finland 
again today to try to resolve the role of Russian peacekeepers in 
Kosovo. Moscow is insisting on a separate sector for its 
peacekeepers; NATO says that won't happen though President Clinton 
predicted a ``successful conclusion.'' Secretary of State Madeleine 
Albright joined the Finland talks today. 

</P>
<P>
	Reports: North Korea To Test Missile  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- North Korea is preparing to test launch an upgraded  
ballistic missile with a range of up to 3,700 miles -- long enough 
to reach Alaska, news reports said today. The hard-line Stalinist 
state has been conducting propulsion tests on a long-range 
Taepodong-2 missile, Japanese national broadcaster NHK reported, 
quoting unidentified U.S. military sources. 

</P>
<P>
	Amtrak: Good Service or Free Travel  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Amtrak, wooing people to take the train, not  
the plane, today promised all passengers good service or a voucher 
for a free ride. The railroad, which must wean itself from federal 
operating subsidies by 2003, hopes planned service improvements 
will hike revenues by 85 million in a three-year period. ``We will 
treat our customers as valued guests..., so they will choose to 
ride our trains over and over again,'' said George Warrington, 
Amtrak's president and chief executive. 

</P>
<P>
	Leader of British Catholics Dies  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Cardinal Basil Hume, spiritual leader of the 4.6  
million Roman Catholics of England and Wales, died today. He was 
76. Hume died just hours after his official spokesman announced 
that his cancer had reached its final stages. The cardinal had 
asked for renewed prayers. Hume, widely respected by people of all 
faiths, became one of the most influential figures in British 
public life after his appointment as Archbishop of Westminster in 
1976. 

</P>
<P>
	Belgium Keeps Ban on Coke, Sprite  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The Belgian government said today it  
was dropping its nationwide ban on some soft drinks produced by 
Coca-Cola Co. but keeping the ban on Coke, Fanta and Sprite pending 
further investigation into what caused dozens of Coke drinkers to 
fall ill. In France, meanwhile, the government announced it was 
relaxing a ban on canned Coca Cola products to allow sales to 
resume from one of Coke's two French plants. 

</P>
