<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Retreat / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grains and soybean futures were mostly lower  
Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade as investors awaited 
additional details on harvesting and growing weather. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybeans early in the session were supported by private  
forecasts for hot, dry weather in western growing regions of the 
Midwest. But prices drifted lower as investors noted National 
Weather Service forecasts and European models that called for 
normal temperatures across the entire region. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures rose amid forecasts for dry, warm weather that  
will aid harvesting in the winter wheat belt. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery fell 2 1/4 cents to $2.55 a bushel; July  
corn fell 1/4 cent to $2.17 1/4 a bushel; July oats fell 1 3/4 cents to 
$1.17 a bushel; July soybeans fell 1 1/2 cents to $4.63 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef and lean hog futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange, while pork bellies rose sharply. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle fell .72 cent to 64 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell .48 cent to 77.32 cents a pound; July lean hogs 
fell 1.60 cents to 49.67 cents a pound; July pork bellies rose 1.03 
cents to 43.85 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
