<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Campaign Finance Hearings Open Anew </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A House committee opened a new round of  
campaign finance hearings Thursday, but Democrats criticized them 
as a ``sham'' designed to delay adoption of proposals most 
lawmakers endorsed last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``What are we doing? Why are we here?'' asked Maryland Rep.  
Steny Hoyer, senior Democrat on the House Administration Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The House passed a campaign finance bill last August after  
numerous hearings and more than 50 hours of floor debate, Hoyer 
noted. 
</P>
<P>
	He said additional hearings, planned into July, will waste time.  
``It is time for us to move on and not to further delay addressing 
this critical issue,'' Hoyer said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Rep. John Boehner, R-Ohio, who chaired the hearing, said it  
was an ``important first step in the orderly committee process that 
will help fulfill the speaker's promise to bring campaign reform 
legislation to the House floor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., has promised a vote on the issue  
in September. But supporters of a proposal passed last year by the 
House fear that it won't leave the Senate enough time to act before 
Congress retires for the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats are rounding up support for a petition to bypass the  
committee and force the issue to the floor for a vote. The effort, 
which requires signatures from 218 members, has been signed by 202, 
including six moderate Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	More than two dozen reform proposals are pending.  
</P>
<P>
	Last August, the House voted 252-179 in favor of a bill that,  
among other changes, would eliminate what is known as ``soft 
money'' -- unlimited and unregulated donations that the political 
parties solicit to finance political activities. The bill also 
would have regulated issue advertising and expanded disclosure 
requirements. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote on that bill, sponsored by Reps. Christopher Shays,  
R-Conn., and Marty Meehan, D-Mass., came only after a similar 
petition neared the 218 signature mark. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure, however, failed to reach a final vote in the  
Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Meehan criticized the new hearings as an ``insult'' to the  
American people, saying that ``this bill has literally been talked 
to death.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boehner countered that Democrats were ``trying to silence  
meaningful examination of the campaign reform issue by rushing it 
to the floor.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
