<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 14:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon Keeps Vietnam Crypt Empty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Tomb of the Unknowns will probably never  
again contain a symbolic victim of the Vietnam War, the Pentagon 
said Thursday. A new inscription on the crypt will instead honor 
those who remain missing. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense Secretary William Cohen ``has determined not to inter  
remains in the Tomb unless and until it can be assured in 
perpetuity that the remains of the American serviceman would be 
forever unidentifiable,'' said Rudy de Leon, undersecretary of 
defense for personnel and readiness. 
</P>
<P>
	Scientific advances, particularly the use of DNA matching  
techniques, makes it at least possible to eventually identify all 
the remains the United States has collected so far, de Leon said. 
That means there are no suitable unknown remains to substitute for 
those of a pilot whose exhumed body was identified last year, 
defense officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vietnam War crypt at the Tomb of the Unknowns at Arlington  
National Cemetery has remained empty since the body of Air Force 
1st Lt. Michael J. Blassie was removed in May last year. The Tomb 
was opened under pressure from Blassie family members who believed 
his was the body laid to rest there 14 years earlier as a symbolic 
unknown war victim. 
</P>
<P>
	Blassie's body was identified using DNA technology, and he was  
reburied by his family. 
</P>
<P>
	On National POW/MIA Day Sept. 17, Cohen will dedicate a new  
inscription on the crypt cover that will read: ``Honoring and 
keeping faith with America's missing servicemen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There are still more than 2,000 Americans listed as missing from  
the Vietnam War. 
</P>
<P>
	About 200 sets of bones, teeth and other remains await  
identification in the Army's Central Identification Laboratory in 
Hawaii, and the United States continues to receive new remains from 
the Vietnam War, as crash sites are excavated and the Vietnamese 
government hands over recovered bodies. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that as long as there are living relatives of some of  
our missing men, there will always be a hope that remains that are 
now at the lab will be identifiable at some point,'' de Leon said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tomb also holds remains of unidentified soldiers from World  
War I, World War II and the Korean conflict. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 18:40:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hackers Exploit Microsoft Flaw </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A small software company is giving away a tool  
that lets computer hackers exploit a major security flaw in a 
Microsoft program that runs about 1.4 million Web sites. 
</P>
<P>
	The security threat could expose personal data such as credit  
card numbers to thieves, although no such attacks on Web sites have 
yet been reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft's antagonist, a company called eEye, said it released  
the tool on the Internet because Microsoft wasn't acting fast 
enough to fix the problem. But Microsoft and many people discussing 
the controversy on the Internet Thursday decried the tactic as a 
dangerous publicity stunt. 
</P>
<P>
	``If people have a problem with Microsoft that is one thing, but  
don't arm the hackers with tools to vandalize Microsoft's 
customers,'' said Michael Spencer, a contributor to an Internet 
message board who identified himself as a programmer in Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft's Windows NT Internet Information Server runs Web  
sites by Disney, barnesandnoble.com, the Nasdaq Stock Market and 
many others. It is one of three major programs, along with rival 
products from Netscape and Apache, that are used on the vast 
majority of Web sites. 
</P>
<P>
	The security problem was deemed serious enough to prompt a  
warning on the Internet Wednesday by the Computer Emergency 
Response Team at Carnegie Mellon University, the same 
government-sponsored group that battles computer viruses. 
</P>
<P>
	eEye reported the flaw to Microsoft last week. Microsoft began  
developing a remedy, but released a temporary ``patch'' to 
deactivate the defect on Tuesday when eEye publicized its discovery 
and posted the hacking tool. Microsoft said Thursday a permanent 
repair for the program was ``imminent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The flaw involves a mechanism that allows people to change their  
passwords for using Web sites, and could be exploited by computer 
hackers with only basic programming ability to take control over or 
crash a site. 
</P>
<P>
	No such intrusions, however, have been reported to either  
Microsoft or the Pittsburgh-based Computer Emergency Response Team. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers have only recently grown comfortable giving credit  
card numbers over the Internet following assurances by Web 
merchants that they are safe. As a result, online shopping has been 
booming since the holiday season. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts noted Thursday that confidential data gathered by many  
Web site operators is usually scrambled and stored on a different 
computer than the one that runs a site. 
</P>
<P>
	``If someone is running a vulnerable version of (the program),  
it's possible that any transaction taking place over the Web could 
be observed by an intruder, altered by intruder, or denied by 
intruder,'' said Shawn Hernan, a member of the Carnegie Mellon 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	``But this vulnerability doesn't allow someone to go and get all  
the information'' a consumer may be providing, said Hernan. Still, 
he added, ``this software is widely deployed, and that makes this a 
serious problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	eEye said on its Web site that ``This is a very serious hole and  
needs to be given the attention it deserves. 
</P>
<P>
	Defending its decision to go public and release the hacking  
tool, the company said, ``If our team starts hiding the facts, 
we'll be no better than a software vendor that rushes insecure 
products to market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft expressed dismay at eEye's moves, saying it was  
standard protocol in the software industry to wait until a full 
remedy is ready for distribution before making a security risk 
public. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't know why they did that. All it does is put an  
extraordinary number of people at risk,'' said Jason Garms, the 
lead product manager for Windows NT security. 
</P>
<P>
	``I vehemently reject the notion that we were dragging our heels  
on this. The absolute minimum expected to fix these things is two 
weeks,'' said Garms. The eEye tool ``enabled even nontechnical 
person to attack any Web site running this software.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 08:11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Knicks Fall to Spurs, Foul Trouble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Maybe what Larry Johnson should have done was  
come out, hit a couple of shots and take the rest of the night off, 
the way Willis Reed did for the New York Knicks in another NBA 
Finals 26 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the Knicks' wounded star picked up two quick fouls in  
the first 2 1/2 minutes of Game 1 against San Antonio, touching off a 
player rotation crisis for coach Jeff Van Gundy. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Knicks already short-handed because of Patrick Ewing's  
season-ending torn Achilles' tendon, Van Gundy's substitution 
pattern follows precise guidelines. In Wednesday's 89-77 loss, it 
was thrown out of whack by whistles. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, nursing a sprained right knee, was a non-factor,  
playing just 21 minutes and getting as many fouls (five) as points. 
He took just three shots and had only one rebound. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought gave us a good effort,'' Van Gundy said. ``He gave  
us what he could. We just have to fight this as far as injuries and 
come back strong on Friday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Almost as quickly as Johnson got his two personals, Marcus Camby  
had three. With their playing time limited by foul trouble, the 
Knicks were caught in a corner. They managed just 10 points in the 
second period, the second-lowest single quarter total in NBA Finals 
history. That took them from six points ahead to eight behind and 
they never recovered. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got into foul trouble early, something I'm not used to,''  
Camby said. ``I picked up my first foul in seven seconds. Then they 
seemed to be coming and coming. I got some cheap fouls. I know my 
teammates need me to be on the court, so I've got to use better 
judgment on defense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Allan Houston, who scored 19, said he thought the Knicks were a  
little frantic, especially in the second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just kind of lost our poise a little bit on the offensive  
end instead of passing the ball to each other, being a little more 
unselfish and taking the shots we need to take,'' he said. ``I 
think we lost a little rhythm, we got some guys in foul trouble. We 
weren't able to stay disciplined on the defensive end and we lost 
our poise on the defensive end, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kurt Thomas gave New York a lift with 13 points and 16 rebounds.  
He thought the two quick fouls on Johnson had set a negative tone 
for the Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to keep our heads up,'' he said. ``It's just one  
game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's also the first time in this season's playoffs that the  
Knicks have lost the opener. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it makes us more hungry,'' Houston said. ``You can't  
expect to go out and win every Game 1 just because it's been done 
in the past. It's still a seven-game series and I think we're even 
more hungry to go out Friday and learn from what we did wrong.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
