<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 17:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Duval's Burns Make Headlines  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PINEHURST, N.C. (AP) -- No matter how hot his golf game gets,  
David Duval does not want to open the newspaper this weekend and 
see headlines about him ``burning'' up the course at the U.S. Open. 
</P>
<P>
	Also high on his list of banned phrases: ``Duval strikes while  
irons are hot.'' And especially: ``Duval wakes up to smell the 
coffee.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There's a reason why, although Duval doesn't find it  
particularly funny. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Friday, while boiling water for coffee, Duval reached for a  
teapot on a gas stove and burned his right thumb and forefinger. It 
might have been the most embarrassing domestic boo-boo by an 
athlete since baseball's Glenallen Hill turned up on the disabled 
list with carpet burns, bumps and bruises. Hill's explanation? He 
dreamt he was being chased by spiders and fell down some stairs 
while sleepwalking. 
</P>
<P>
	Duval didn't have to own up to anything nearly that silly, but  
he is understandably tired of telling the story. And yet, even 
while insisting the burns were a non-issue, he still had tape on 
both fingers Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's some tenderness in my forefinger,'' he said, ``but  
nothing bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	We can probably take Duval at his word, especially since he  
backed it up with a 67 over Pinehurst No. 2 that left him in a 
four-way tie for the opening-day lead. 
</P>
<P>
	The round was typical Duval in at least one other sense. Not  
only was it largely free of physical pain, by missing just four of 
14 fairways and hitting 15 greens, Duval made sure that stress 
wasn't much of a factor, either. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was pretty pleased with all of it today,'' he said. ``I  
drove the ball well and hit my iron shots where I was trying to. 
I'd be very content to do that for three more days.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forget the fingers for a moment. What made Duval's round seem  
even more impressive were the distractions going on around him. His 
threesome included father-to-be Phil Mickelson, who had a beeper 
stashed in his golf bag alongside the scoring clubs he cleverly 
wielded while cobbling together a 67 of his own. 
</P>
<P>
	``I try not to have to do those things,'' Duval said, apparently  
referring to Mickelson's scrambling and not his impending 
fatherhood. ``I find it to be less stressful. To accomplish that, 
obviously you have to hit the ball well and I did that today. So I 
very much enjoyed the day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whether he really expected to do so, Duval wouldn't say. The  
burns prevented him from practicing during the weekend and limited 
him to working on his short game Monday. Then along came Tom Loss, 
a Seattle doctor who moonlights as a U.S. Golf Association rules 
official, who convinced Duval to lance the blisters on both 
fingers. 
</P>
<P>
	Good thing, that. Because while Duval came to Pinehurst without  
expectations for his play, he might have been the only one. He's 
won 11 tournaments in the last 17 months, which makes him the 
hottest player in the game at the moment. But since none of those 
wins has come in major championships, it also makes Duval, along 
with Mickelson and Scotsman Colin Montgomerie, a contender for best 
player never to win a major. 
</P>
<P>
	If Duval hadn't been able to compete here -- let alone practice --  
because of a brush with a teapot, he would have never been able to 
live down the embarrassment. 
</P>
<P>
	It would have been comparable to Irish miler Eamonn Coghlan  
pulling out just before the 1980 Olympics because a dog bit him 
during a training run in a Dublin park. Or former Mets pitcher Bob 
Ojeda missing most of a season after severing a finger (later 
reattached by doctors) while trimming a hedge. Or even boxer Julio 
Cesar Chavez getting head-butted by his 4-year-old son just days 
before a scheduled fight with Oscar De La Hoya. 
</P>
<P>
	And yet, despite the 67, Duval could not make talk of the burned  
fingers go away completely. 
</P>
<P>
	``Did you put a topical anesthetic on the fingers?'' a reporter  
asked. 
</P>
<P>
	``I did the first few days,'' Duval replied.  
</P>
<P>
	``Did it affect your touch on the club?''  
</P>
<P>
	``No, because I didn't touch a club, really, until Tuesday.''  
</P>
<P>
	On and on it went, until someone asked Duval whether he'd quit  
drinking coffee, or at least brewing it himself. 
</P>
<P>
	``Same old, same old,'' he replied, smiling, ``just not on gas  
stoves.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlitke@ap.org. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
