<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Olympic Cup for American Audience </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- For many U.S. Olympic hopefuls, the road to  
Sydney will include a welcome pit stop this summer at San Diego's 
arenas, pools, beaches and fields. 
</P>
<P>
	A year before the Summer Games, part of the world will come here  
for the inaugural U.S. Olympic Cup Sept. 9-12. Americans will face 
top international competition in women's basketball, men's and 
women's swimming, women's softball, boxing and men's and women's 
beach volleyball. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really a great opportunity for us American athletes to be  
able to race the best athletes from around the world, in a venue in 
our back yard,'' swimmer Ashley Tappin said Thursday during a news 
conference announcing the Olympic preview. ``You can't beat that. 
One year out from the Olympics, we'll pretty much take any 
opportunity we can. 
</P>
<P>
	``Secondly, I'd like to say it's also a great opportunity for us  
American athletes to be able to show the American audience just how 
strong we're going to be this summer and next. Because we're going 
to whup on 'em this summer, and we're going to do it even more in 
12 months.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tappin, 24, was on the winning 400-meter freestyle relay team at  
Barcelona in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Olympic Cup replaces the U.S. Olympic Festivals, which  
folded after 1995 because they became too unwieldy and costly to 
the U.S. Olympic Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``This event may be a little shorter in quantity but richer in  
quality than those U.S. Olympic Festivals in the past,'' said Dave 
Ogrean, a USOC marketing executive. ``This is going to be a big 
step on the road to Sydney for a lot of our athletes. This is an 
event that is really, really needed by our athletes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among the expected highlights: WNBA players fresh off their  
season jumping into international competition, U.S boxers fighting 
the Russians and the United States versus Australia in softball. 
The United States, which won the first Olympic softball tournament 
in 1996, will have picked its team the previous weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	The beach volleyball tournament includes a previously scheduled  
Olympic qualifier. Karch Kiraly, the only volleyball player to win 
three Olympic gold medals, likely will compete as the top eight 
American teams play the top eight international pairs. 
</P>
<P>
	The women's basketball field will include Australia, Brazil and  
Poland, while Canada and New Zealand are the other softball teams 
due to compete. Japan and Canada are tentatively scheduled to 
compete against the United States in swimming, while boxers from 
Mexico and Ukraine are due to join the Russians in fighting 
Americans in eight weight classes. 
</P>
<P>
	Basketball, swimming and softball will be held at UC San Diego,  
boxing at the Concourse downtown and beach volleyball at Mission 
Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a great event for the U.S. boxers,'' Larry Mosley, a  
19-year-old welterweight from Los Angeles, said. ``We've been 
getting dominated by Cuba and Russia, so this is a great 
opportunity to get the experience that we need for 2000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some 336 athletes are expected, and ESPN2 is scheduled to  
televise 6 1/2 hours of competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``People who can't go to Sydney for the Olympics, come here and  
watch this,'' Tappin, who lives in Laguna Beach, said. ``It's going 
to be a mini-Olympics.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
