<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airlines Announce Service Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Buffeted by customer complaints and threatened  
by congressional action, the airlines industry today announced a 
package of voluntary measures to improve passenger service. 
</P>
<P>
	They include ensuring that airlines tell customers of the lowest  
available price, notify people of delays and cancellations, provide 
prompt ticket refunds, handle bumped passengers with fairness and 
meet customers' essential needs during long on-aircraft delays. 
</P>
<P>
	``We heard the bell ring, we have felt the whip,'' said Gerald  
Greenwald, chairman of United Airlines and of the Air Transport 
Association Executive Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The measures were prompted by several highly publicized  
incidents last winter when passengers were made to sit on runways 
for hours without access to food or restrooms. They followed 
several months of negotiations among the industry, the Department 
of Transportation and members of Congress who had introduced 
legislation that would have mandated airline companies to take 
steps to improve service. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., chairman of the Senate Commerce  
Committee and sponsor of a ``passenger rights'' bill, said the 
industry had taken ``some very significant steps.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he said they have yet to work out the issue of notifying  
passengers of overbooking and he would still seek legislation 
requiring the Transportation Department's inspector general to 
monitor the industry to make sure they were complying with their 
promises. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., co-sponsor of the passenger rights  
bill, said the industry measures were inadequate and he would still 
push for legislation. ``This was the airline industry asking the 
passengers to accept a wink and a nod,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Transportation Committee chairman, Rep. Bud Shuster,  
R-Pa., said the airlines' approach was a ``step in the right 
direction and I will take a serious look at their proposal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he added: ``I don't believe airline service will improve  
dramatically until we have real competition in the airline 
industry.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
