<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> L.A.'s Perez Doesn't Regret Tantrum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- If only Carlos Perez got his hits on the  
field. 
</P>
<P>
	After getting booed off the field, the Los Angeles pitcher  
picked up a bat and took 13 severe swings Wednesday night that 
destroyed a couple of water coolers in the dugout. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was the first time it's happened,'' Perez said Thursday,  
a night after the Dodgers' 6-5 win over Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	Perez left after walking the bases loaded in the fourth inning.  
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes you get mad like that and everything goes away, so I  
just grabbed a bat and hit a cooler. I felt better and I slept 
good. I also talked to my family, and that made me calm down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perez, 2-8 with a 7.38 ERA in 11 starts and one relief  
appearance, will have some extra time to calm down. The Dodgers are 
off Monday, and manager Davey Johnson is skipping his turn in the 
rotation. 
</P>
<P>
	``As soon as I get my mechanics back, I know I'm going to get my  
fastball back,'' said Perez, who signed a $15.5 million, three-year 
contract during the offseason. ``And that's one of the big problems 
I have right now. I've been watching the video for the last year 
and my delivery has been fine, but right now there's a big 
difference.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perez, who met privately with Johnson on Thursday, said he has  
no regrets about venting his frustrations. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're going to hit something, grab a bat,'' Perez said.  
``I remember a couple of years ago when John Wetteland and I were 
in Montreal. He kicked the garbage can, broke his finger and missed 
almost two months. And that's not going to happen to me. I'm not 
going to use my hands or my legs, because I don't want to get 
hurt.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
