<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls on Greenspan Comments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell against most major currencies  
Thursday as Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan's comments 
suggesting an interest rate increase may be coming were in line 
with market expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0339, up  
from $1.0305 late Wednesday. The dollar fell to 119.25 Japanese yen 
from 120.43 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan testified before Congress and suggested that the  
central bank was still considering raising interest rates despite 
few signs of inflation. Just a day earlier, the government reported 
that the consumer price index held steady in May after a 0.7 
percent rise in April. But Greenspan said the Fed may take 
``pre-emptive'' action to protect the economy from overheating. 
</P>
<P>
	The currency markets have already been expecting a modest rise  
in rates at the Fed's policy-making meeting later this month, and 
the inflation report relieved some observers who feared larger rate 
hikes were coming. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Gargano, managing director of currency derivatives at First  
National Bank in Charlotte, N.C., said Greenspan's comments 
suggested a modest rate hike of perhaps a quarter percentage point 
is likely. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, he said a new private survey of business sentiment  
in Germany was unexpectedly strong and suggested the German 
manufacturing sector may be improving. That helped the euro recover 
as it traded as low as $1.0288 during the day, only slightly above 
its record low of $1.0260 set June 7. 
</P>
<P>
	Against other currencies, the dollar was quoted at 1.5427 Swiss  
francs, down from 1.5483, and 1.4632 Canadian dollars, up from 
1.4599. The British pound rose to $1.5926 from $1.5883. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on the euro's exchange rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8918 
German marks, down from 1.8979; 6.3452 French francs, down from 
6.3654; and 1,872.66 Italian lire, down from 1,879.70. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
