<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cards Option Drew, Disable Painter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- The St. Louis Cardinals optioned rookie  
outfielder J.D. Drew, healthy after a rehab stint, to Triple-A 
Memphis on Thursday to allow him to continue to work on his stroke. 
</P>
<P>
	The Drew move was one of several on another busy day for the  
Cardinals. The team also announced that Shawon Dunston had dropped 
his appeal of a three-day suspension for charging the mound in Los 
Angeles earlier this season and placed left-hander Lance Painter on 
the 15-day disabled list with a strained shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	Dunston had a meeting scheduled Friday with NL president Leonard  
Coleman from the May 23 incident that led to a bench-clearing 
brawl, and had been seeking to have the suspension reduced to two 
games. He began serving his time Thursday, perhaps because he's 
battling lingering hamstring problems anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	``That might have something to do with it,'' manager Tony La  
Russa said. 
</P>
<P>
	Drew has recovered from a quadriceps injury and was batting .300  
with eight RBIs in 13 games at Memphis. He began the year hitting 
second in the order ahead of Mark McGwire and batted .230 with two 
homers and nine RBIs in 25 games with the Cardinals. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the team decided to skip Painter's scheduled  
Friday start due to a shoulder injury suffered in a checked swing. 
Painter, 0-4 with a 5.55 ERA, said the injury was not serious 
enough to put him out for 15 days, except that the Cardinals are 
now a bit shorthanded. 
</P>
<P>
	The team recalled right-hander Curtis King from Triple-A  
Memphis. King has pitched with the Cardinals parts of the last two 
seasons, and was 2-0 with a 3.53 ERA and two saves in 36 games last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're a little vulnerable unless we get some innings from our  
rotation,'' La Russa said. ``Even without that, if we had gotten 
five straight complete games, we wouldn't have sent Paint out 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kent Mercker made his first start since May 11 Thursday night  
against the New York Mets and Juan Acevedo had his turn moved back 
a day to Friday because he dropped a 45-pound weight on his right 
toe after his last start. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really not as bad as what people would think,'' Painter  
said. ``I understand the reasoning behind it. It's really not a 
15-day injury.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Painter warmed up on Wednesday and threw fastballs and changeups  
without pain, but had some pain when he tried to throw breaking 
balls. He also developed a blister on his pitching thumb in his 
last start. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
