<DOCNO> APW19990617.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 13:30:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore, Bush: Slicksters Made-for-TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore and George W. Bush entered the  
presidential sweepstakes this week with slick, made-for-television 
inaugural campaign trips that improved their footing atop the 
crowded field of White House candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	Both accomplished their No. 1 goals.  
</P>
<P>
	Gore, the Democratic front-runner, distanced himself from his  
boss' personal transgressions while claiming credit for the Clinton 
administration's economic record. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, the Republican governor of Texas, showed a deft hand at  
working crowds and issues -- easing doubts about his readiness as a 
candidate and potential president. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a good week for both of them,'' said Stephen Hess of  
the Brookings Institute, a Washington think tank. ``They did well 
by doing no harm.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Their efforts left other presidential campaigns starving for  
attention as Gore and Bush solidified their money-raising and 
poll-rating prowess. 
</P>
<P>
	And it could get worse for the other candidates.  
</P>
<P>
	Bush supporters are predicting he will raise as much as $20  
million by the end of June, which would be 10 times as much as some 
rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	Like the media, Gore and Bush seem more fixated on each other  
than their intra-party rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore alluded to Bush repeatedly in his Wednesday address,  
accusing a certain Republican of trying to ``duck the issue'' of 
abortion, doling out ``crumbs of compassion'' and shielding gun 
manufacturers from lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush poked fun at Gore for claiming the Internet as his  
invention. The Clinton administration ``did not invent 
prosperity,'' Bush said, ``any more than they invented the 
Internet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The candidates' campaigns had some similarities.  
</P>
<P>
	Both men spoke briefly in Spanish to crowds that were almost  
exclusively white and English-speaking. Hispanics are a key voting 
bloc for 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	They both promoted the use of government money to help charities  
ease social problems such as hunger and housing shortages. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore explained the concept in clunky, bureaucratic terms,  
calling for a ``true politics of community by working more closely 
with faith-based organizations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With a lyrical flourish, Bush ditched the phrase ``faith-based  
organizations'' for ``a quiet river of goodness and kindness that 
cuts through stone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On style, the early edge went to Bush. He courted voters with a  
playful grin, a quick wit and a flirtatious style. 
</P>
<P>
	To say Bush shook hundreds of hands doesn't capture his first  
campaign foray. 
</P>
<P>
	Consider his visit to an Iowa charity. Bush was sitting in a  
circle of local women discussing their plight when one of them, 
Ruby Myles, stretched her hand toward the governor. Bush accepted 
her hand into his, squeezed it and didn't let go until the event 
ended. 
</P>
<P>
	In New Hampshire, he spotted a baby in one crowd and alerted  
news photographers. ``I've always been a sucker for baby 
pictures!'' he shouted. 
</P>
<P>
	Taking the baby from his mother, Bush planted a big kiss on a  
chubby check. ``One more kiss!'' a photographer shouted. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush obliged.  
</P>
<P>
	``Turn around!'' another photographer instructed.  
</P>
<P>
	Bush obliged.  
</P>
<P>
	``Hold him up!''  
</P>
<P>
	Bush obliged.  
</P>
<P>
	The next day, Gore was in his hometown of Carthage, Tenn., when  
a small group of supporters coaxed him to the edge of a security 
area to shake hands. He made his way down a line of greeters until 
he reached a woman holding a baby. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore reached across the metal barrier.  
</P>
<P>
	And shook the baby's hand.  
</P>
<P>
	On policy, Gore brings a record of achievement as vice president  
and a fluency in topics ranging from Social Security to Russian 
politics. Bush's stump speech is less substantial than Gore's, and 
he is prone to stumbling. 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas governor called residents of Timor ``Timoreans'' in an  
interview between campaign stops with The New York Times. The 
proper term is Timorese. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet the Texas governor nimbly handled several difficult  
questions at a New Hampshire news conference. He put to rest some 
doubts, including those harbored by supporters, about his campaign 
skills. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore also met with reporters, using a series of interviews to  
condemn President Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky. He 
also predicting that he would not hesitate to disagree with the 
president in public. 
</P>
<P>
	Voicing a sentiment that could apply to Bush or Gore, the vice  
president said: ``Everything changes ... when I become a 
candidate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Ron Fournier is chief political reporter for The  
Associated Press. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
