<DOCNO> APW19990617.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 20:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Advance / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices advanced in morning trading  
Friday, buoyed by gains on Wall Street. The dollar was lower 
against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 121.84 points,  
or 0.70 percent, to 17,592.29 by the end of the morning session. On 
Thursday, the index gained 260.27, or 1.51 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 119.66 yen in early dealings, down 0.38 yen  
from late Thursday in Tokyo but above its late New York level of 
119.25 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, share prices rose on continued bullish  
sentiment supported by gains in U.S. stocks, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although foreign investors have been actively buying, domestic  
institutional investors remain sellers of Japanese stocks,'' said 
Kunihiro Hatae, general manager at Tokyo Securities Co. ``It may 
take some time ... but the key index could try the 18000 level as 
early as next week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday in New York, the Dow Jones industrial average rose  
56.68 points to close at 10,841.63. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks there were boosted on remarks by U.S. Federal Reserve  
Chairman Alan Greenspan, who indicated to Congress that only a 
modest interest rate rise may be in order to keep inflation 
well-tamed. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan said that while inflation remains in check, the Fed  
should consider taking pre-emptive action to avert any threat to 
continued economic growth. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed's Open Market Committee, which sets the central bank's  
interest rate policy, meets June 29-30. The Fed has warned recently 
it might raise interest rates to guard against a surge in 
inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange was up 7.46 points, or 
0.53 percent, to 1,406.63. The TOPIX finished up 16.00 points, or 
1.16 percent, the previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, fears of further market intervention by  
the Bank of Japan following its aggressive dollar-buying operation 
earlier this week kept the U.S. currency from falling further, 
traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	But they said investors were likely to test the dollar's low  
intra-day of 119.10 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 123.61 yen, down  
from 123.90 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond was  
down to 1.6950 percent Friday morning after finishing Thursday with 
a yield of 1.725 percent, pushing its price up to 97.47 yen from 
97.22 yen a day earlier. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
