<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Knicks Fall to Spurs, Foul Trouble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Maybe what Larry Johnson should have done was  
come out, hit a couple of shots and take the rest of the night off, 
the way Willis Reed did for the New York Knicks in another NBA 
Finals 26 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the Knicks' wounded star picked up two quick fouls in  
the first 2 1/2 minutes of Game 1 against San Antonio, touching off a 
player rotation crisis for coach Jeff Van Gundy. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Knicks already short-handed because of Patrick Ewing's  
season-ending torn Achilles' tendon, Van Gundy's substitution 
pattern follows precise guidelines. In Wednesday's 89-77 loss, it 
was thrown out of whack by whistles. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, nursing a sprained right knee, was a non-factor,  
playing just 21 minutes and getting as many fouls (five) as points. 
He took just three shots and had only one rebound. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought gave us a good effort,'' Van Gundy said. ``He gave  
us what he could. We just have to fight this as far as injuries and 
come back strong on Friday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Almost as quickly as Johnson got his two personals, Marcus Camby  
had three. With their playing time limited by foul trouble, the 
Knicks were caught in a corner. They managed just 10 points in the 
second period, the second-lowest single quarter total in NBA Finals 
history. That took them from six points ahead to eight behind and 
they never recovered. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got into foul trouble early, something I'm not used to,''  
Camby said. ``I picked up my first foul in seven seconds. Then they 
seemed to be coming and coming. I got some cheap fouls. I know my 
teammates need me to be on the court, so I've got to use better 
judgment on defense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Allan Houston, who scored 19, said he thought the Knicks were a  
little frantic, especially in the second quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just kind of lost our poise a little bit on the offensive  
end instead of passing the ball to each other, being a little more 
unselfish and taking the shots we need to take,'' he said. ``I 
think we lost a little rhythm, we got some guys in foul trouble. We 
weren't able to stay disciplined on the defensive end and we lost 
our poise on the defensive end, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kurt Thomas gave New York a lift with 13 points and 16 rebounds.  
He thought the two quick fouls on Johnson had set a negative tone 
for the Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to keep our heads up,'' he said. ``It's just one  
game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's also the first time in this season's playoffs that the  
Knicks have lost the opener. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it makes us more hungry,'' Houston said. ``You can't  
expect to go out and win every Game 1 just because it's been done 
in the past. It's still a seven-game series and I think we're even 
more hungry to go out Friday and learn from what we did wrong.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
