<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Ill. Deaths Linked to Rail Killer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GEORGETOWN, Texas (AP) -- A suspected serial killer, a drifter  
known to hop freight trains, may be linked to the slayings of two 
more people found near railroad tracks in Illinois. And he may be 
responsible for even more deaths, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rafael Resendez-Ramirez has been wanted in connection with five  
Texas killings and one in Lexington, Ky., since August 1997. All of 
the victims were beaten to death near railroad tracks. On 
Wednesday, authorities in southern Illinois identified him as a 
suspect in the killings this week of a man and his daughter in a 
home 100 yards from a rail line. 
</P>
<P>
	The bodies of George Morber, 80, and Carolyn Frederick, 52, were  
found Tuesday in Gorham, Ill. A truck missing from the scene was 
recovered Wednesday from a school parking lot in Cairo, about 60 
miles south of Gorham. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whoever is killing these people is certainly a very brutal,  
brutal individual,'' said Texas Department of Public Safety 
spokesman Mike Cox. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday afternoon, FBI agents and Cairo police were  
circulating photographs of Resendez-Ramirez to residents of Cairo, 
at the southern tip of Illinois and just over the Ohio River from 
Kentucky. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't not consider him a suspect, but I can't say that he's  
my prime suspect, either,'' Jackson County Sheriff Bill Kilquist 
told The Southern Illinoisan newspaper in Carbondale. 
</P>
<P>
	In Texas, meanwhile, authorities determined late Wednesday that  
a man at first thought to be Resendez-Ramirez was not their man 
after realizing that a snake tattoo identified with the suspected 
rail-riding killer was on the wrong arm. 
</P>
<P>
	Computerized fingerprint comparisons between Resendez-Ramirez  
and the man who was taken into custody also did not match. The FBI 
will do its own fingerprint tests sometime today, Cox said. 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as we're concerned, at this point it's not  
Resendez-Ramirez,'' Cox said. ``I suppose there is still a click of 
a possibility, but there's not much of one at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The man in custody, who has not been identified, was arrested  
along with four other people while riding a Union Pacific freight 
train between Round Rock and Hutto in Williamson County, about 30 
miles north of Austin. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides the southern Illinois killings, authorities say  
fingerprints and other forensic evidence link Resendez-Ramirez to 
five Texas killings -- two in the Houston area and three near 
Weimar, 80 miles west of Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	Resendez-Ramirez is also considered a suspect in the East Texas  
slaying of an 87-year-old woman two months ago. Police say the 
victim was robbed and beaten to death in her home near a railroad 
track. 
</P>
<P>
	And he is wanted for questioning in the 1997 slaying of a  
21-year-old University of Kentucky student who was struck in the 
back of the head as he and his girlfriend took a shortcut along 
some railroad tracks in Lexington. 
</P>
<P>
	An FBI task force composed of local, state and federal officers  
has been hunting for Resendez-Ramirez since authorities began 
connecting the killings last week. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
