<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kellogg May Close Part of Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BATTLE CREEK, Mich. (AP) -- The nation's largest cereal maker  
announced today it is considering closing part of its historic 
Battle Creek cereal plant and eliminating up to 64 percent of the 
jobs at the facility. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the proposal, up to 700 of the current 1,100 jobs at the  
Kellogg Co. plant would be eliminated as early as the first quarter 
of 2000, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Streamlining our operations and avoiding future costs would  
help keep our North American cereal business cost-competitive going 
into the 21st century,'' new chief executive Carlos M. Gutierrez 
said in a written statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The news comes seven months after Kellogg cut 525 jobs -- 21  
percent of its salaried workforce -- as part of a reorganization of 
its North American operations. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Battle Creek-based cereal maker decides to close part of  
the plant, the company said some of the operations would be 
relocated to other Kellogg North America cereal plants for an 
estimated annual savings of $35 million to $45 million. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the 700 jobs that would be cut would not be replaced at  
other plants, Joseph Stewart, Kellogg's executive vice president of 
communications, said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Parts of plant date back to 1907, the year after the Kellogg Co.  
made Battle Creek its headquarters, and the company cannot afford 
to keep it running because it's so inefficient, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The plant was at one time a major tourist attraction. An  
estimated 175,000 people visited it each year before the tours 
ended in the mid-1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, a nonprofit group opened Cereal City USA in downtown  
Battle Creek. The company contributed millions to help build the 
attraction, which features exhibits on cereal history, a simulated 
cereal production line and a show featuring the characters used in 
Kellogg's advertising. 
</P>
<P>
	Kellogg will make a final decision about the closure after  
discussions with the union that represents the plant's hourly 
workers. The company met will all employees this morning 30 minutes 
before making its announcement to reporters gathered for a news 
conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Gutierrez said in April that although Battle Creek produces a  
lot of cereal, the plant would have to remain competitive and 
continue to improve its productivity. 
</P>
<P>
	And analysts have previously said Kellogg needs to do more if it  
is to regain its shrinking market share. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, Kellogg reported a 30 percent drop in first-quarter  
earnings, but the cereal maker pointed to an increase in sales as 
an indicator of future growth. 
</P>
<P>
	The results were in line with Wall Street estimates.  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
