<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AGs Want Sweepstakes Warning Labels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Sweepstakes companies could soon stuff  
warning labels into their contest envelopes if they adopt new 
industry guidelines being proposed by state attorneys general. 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana Attorney General Jeff Modisett and others want the  
industry to include the following note of caution in their 
mailings: ``You have not yet won. Enter for free. Enter as often as 
you like. Buying won't help you win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Otherwise, Modisett vowed to push for federal laws requiring  
such disclaimers. 
</P>
<P>
	The suggestion is one of many that members of the National  
Association of Attorneys General will present at a meeting in 
Nashville next week. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that sweepstakes marketers should not imply that a  
person is a winner, or stands a better chance than anyone else, 
unless that is in fact the case,'' Modisett said. ``We want the 
industry to take responsibility for not taking advantage of 
vulnerable consumers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report also wants the industry to:  
</P>
<P>
	-- Stop implying that a person won or is in a unique position to  
win or that ordering a product increases the odds of winning. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Create a simple and uniform way to enter the contests.  
</P>
<P>
	-- Stop multiple deadlines for a single sweepstakes contest.  
</P>
<P>
	-- Make getting off sweepstakes mailing lists easier.  
</P>
<P>
	-- Stop including checks that often look like they've been issued  
or endorsed by the federal government. 
</P>
<P>
	Two leading sweepstakes companies insist they already use many  
of the consumer advisories being outlined by NAAG. 
</P>
<P>
	``We support clear disclaimers. We've already done it for a  
year,'' said Jeanne Meyer, a spokeswoman for American Family 
Publishers, the company that uses Ed McMahon and Dick Clark in its 
mailings. 
</P>
<P>
	Christopher Irving, director of consumer affairs for Publishers  
Clearing House, said his company wasn't sure if another piece of 
paper would be the best way because it could become lost with the 
other inserts. 
</P>
<P>
	``A stand-alone slip may not do that,'' he said. ``That  
information might better be communicated on the entry order form, 
which the consumers may be more apt to read.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Modisett, who chairs the Subcommittee on Sweepstakes and Prize  
Promotion for NAAG, said the suggestions could become law if the 
industry doesn't practice more self-regulation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have observed over the last year a distinction between  
statements of the industry and the actions of the industry,'' he 
said. ``The proof will be in the pudding. If they do not follow, we 
would recommend that these be adopted nationally. It would take 
federal legislation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana, South Carolina, West Virginia and Florida agreed to a  
$4 million settlement with AFP last month. It included a pledge to 
stop the mailings that duped hundreds of people into thinking they 
were winners. Iowa and Connecticut are still in negotiations with 
the company and could sign on later. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
