<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brooding Belle Hasn't Changed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- The youngster eagerly stretched his arm over  
the railing, tightly gripping a baseball as the Baltimore Orioles 
walked off the field after batting practice. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Belle, would you please sign this? It would really make my  
day,'' the boy said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know what, kid? I'm sure it would,'' replied Albert Belle,  
never breaking stride as he disappeared into the dugout. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the same Albert Belle who recently purchased baseball  
tickets for 400 children in Texas and put his name on college 
scholarships for four students. 
</P>
<P>
	It's virtually impossible to get a definitive read on Albert  
Belle, a reclusive slugger whose demeanor changes as often as a 
traffic light. It's always been that way, and nothing has changed 
in his first season with the Orioles. 
</P>
<P>
	When Belle signed a five-year, $65 million contract in December,  
he spoke of bonding with Orioles fans and forging a workable 
relationship with the media. 
</P>
<P>
	That hasn't happened. The fans gave him a standing ovation when  
he homered on opening day, and he shocked more than a few of them 
by stepping from the dugout to tip his cap. But after he went into 
a prolonged slump and occasionally failed to hustle on groundballs, 
Belle heard plenty of boos at Camden Yards. 
</P>
<P>
	His association with the Baltimore media is nonexistent. Belle  
stopped speaking to the press after reporters wrote about a 
clubhouse tirade during spring training that occurred in front of 
his locker immediately after a sixth-inning strikeout. 
</P>
<P>
	Reporters kept their distance until last week. After being  
replaced in the ninth inning of a game against the Florida Marlins 
after failing to run out a grounder, Belle exchanged angry words 
with manager Ray Miller. When approached by reporters after the 
game, Belle rattled off a string of expletives. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller said he intended to replace Belle in the bottom of the  
ninth anyway. But he benched the right fielder in the next game to 
end his run of consecutive games at 392, then the longest active 
streak in the major leagues. 
</P>
<P>
	Belle has since been on a tear at the plate, going 10-for-22 in  
five games to raise his batting average 20 points to .264. 
</P>
<P>
	When they signed Belle as a free agent, the Orioles had no idea  
whether he would behave differently than he did with the Cleveland 
Indians and Chicago White Sox, when he was suspended six times. But 
team officials figured he would at least maintain his pace of 
hitting at least 30 homers and 100 RBIs the past seven seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Thus far, Belle actions on and off the field have been  
consistent. He usually starts hitting well when the weather heats 
up, and his performance this week seems to indicate he's right on 
schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	``Albert's been fine. I think we all got frustrated with the way  
the club has played the first two months, and his frustration was 
intensified by the fact that he wasn't hitting as he would have 
liked,'' Orioles general manager Frank Wren said. ``But he's 
starting to pick it up lately, so hopefully that's all behind 
him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Orioles can only hope his erratic behavior will change, too.  
In April, during a three-game series in which he managed only two 
hits, Belle threw a beer bottle through a television set in the 
visitors clubhouse at Tropicana Field in Tampa Bay. He paid for the 
damage and was not fined. 
</P>
<P>
	Belle usually is far less obtrusive in the Orioles clubhouse. He  
likes to play cribbage with teammates before games, but for the 
most part he performs his pregame rituals in solitude. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Johnson, whose locker is separated from Belle's by one  
vacant cubicle, said, ``You see his preparation for the game and 
what he goes through. He's a serious competitor who really cares 
about his game. ... Regardless of what people say about how he 
plays the game, to me it says a lot that he's the first to get here 
and the last to leave.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Belle has a no-trade clause through 2001, so these first months  
are seemingly the beginning of a long relationship, for better or 
worse. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a big bat in the middle of the lineup. If he hits like we  
know we can,'' Wren said, ``then we'll have the guy we were looking 
for.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
