<DOCNO> APW19990617.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 12:20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Education Dept. Lowers Loan Fees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Education Department, under fire for  
forgiving loans for students who falsely claimed death or 
disability, defended the cost and operation of its direct loan 
program to lawmakers on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Woods, who oversees the Education Department's loan  
division, touted a package of student loan fee discounts expected 
to save 2 million borrowers an average of $631. The new savings, 
modeled on discounts private lenders often give borrowers who repay 
early or electronically, were announced Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. John Mica, R-Fla., who oversees domestic issues on the  
House Government Reform and Oversight Committee, criticized the 
department nonetheless. 
</P>
<P>
	Department officials testified about the results of an internal  
audit, which found that nearly $4 million in student loans over a 
2 1/2-year period were forgiven for borrowers who were supposed to be 
dead but turned out to be alive and earning wages. Also, more than 
$73 million in loans were forgiven for people who claimed permanent 
disabilities but continued to work. 
</P>
<P>
	Woods told the panel the department would use wage garnishment  
and other means to recover the loans. The loans were forgiven 
mostly because the department didn't made sure lenders got original 
or certified copies of death certificates for discharges of loans 
based on a borrower's death. 
</P>
<P>
	He said department improvements include the new discounts --  
which will go to borrowers repaying loans electronically and those 
who consolidate their loans while they are in school or during the 
grace period before they are officially responsible for loan 
repayment. 
</P>
<P>
	The average total savings will be $631 over the life of a loan  
for the average graduate with a debt of $10,000 and a standard 
10-year repayment plan. A student with a loan that size will save 
an estimated $100 on the origination fee, $157 for the interest 
rate reduction for electronic debit repayment, and $374 for the 
in-school or grace consolidation savings. 
</P>
<P>
	These discounts are similar to those now offered to students by  
private lenders and guaranty agencies subsidized by the department 
to make loans. 
</P>
<P>
	The department's direct loans, begun in 1994, account for a  
third of the $32 billion student loan market. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
