<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> World Cup Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	To make sure they are up to the task, the 15 World Cup referees  
and their 16 assistants had to take the Cooper test Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The fitness test, which many people will remember from high  
school gym classes, includes two 50-meter sprints that must be 
completed in nine seconds each; a 12-minute run which must cover at 
least 2,400 meters; and two 200-meter sprints that must be 
completed in under 32 seconds apiece. 
</P>
<P>
	With the fitness test under their belts the referees and the  
assistants can start preparing for the opening games on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SOCCER LAB TEACHES KIDS THE ROPES:* New York's Bryant Park  
filled up with kids in soccer jerseys Thursday, ready to learn some 
new tricks in the Adidas Soccer Lab. They could practice their 
penalty shots, run an obstacle course or test their goal-keeping 
abilities. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't all soccer, though. To attract other kids, there was a  
concert with such upcoming acts as Billie, C-Note and Cha Cha. 
</P>
<P>
	``The future is always the youth; we're really trying to capture  
the next generation with this,'' said Marla Messing, the president 
of the organizing committee of the Women's World Cup. ``Soccer is 
enormous with young kids in the U.S. The challenge is to keep them 
in the sport as they grow older.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To make sure kids would come to the park, the organizer of the  
soccer lab, Nicole Vollebregt, invited schools from all over the 
New York metropolitan area to participate. 
</P>
<P>
	The park was filled with several school classes. Some of the  
kids came wearing the soccer jerseys of the teams they played for. 
Others, like Jennifer Lesley, hadn't played soccer before. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the most fun I've had in a while,'' said 12-year-old  
Lesley. She had taken a shot at being a goalkeeper, had her picture 
taken with her friend and waited for the C-Note concert. 
</P>
<P>
	Similar Soccer Labs will also be held in the other World Cup  
cities of Boston and Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SUDDEN DEATH:* This Women's World Cup will be the first played  
with sudden-death overtime. The rule was introduced in youth 
competition and used in last year's men's World Cup in France. 
</P>
<P>
	In case of a tie after 90 minutes, the rule calls for two  
overtime periods of 15 minutes each. As soon as one of the teams 
scores, the game is over. In previous FIFA events, the full 30 
minutes of overtime was played, regardless of how many goals were 
scored. 
</P>
<P>
	In the men's World Cup, the France-Paraguay quarterfinal was  
decided in overtime, and France went on to win the title. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *FAMILY VALUES:* The Women's World Cup is making sure it's a  
family event. Game times are planned for late afternoons and early 
evenings to make sure the matches can be a ``family oriented 
thing'' in the stadiums, and for television, said Marla Messing, 
head of the organizing committee. 
</P>
<P>
	To attract not only young children but also teen-agers to  
matches, the organizers have planned concerts at the opening 
doubleheader. The group 'N Synch and British teen sensation Billie 
will appear. 
</P>
<P>
	Billie, only 16 herself, also sings the official song of the  
Women's World Cup ``Because We Want To.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Messing stresses the Women's World Cup is not  
exclusionary and welcomes all soccer fans, she does admit girls are 
an important audience for the games. and they have a strong 
connection with the teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly teen-age girls make up a significant population of  
soccer players, they're a key market,'' Messing said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
