<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Salt Lake Under Fire From IOC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- A senior member of the International  
Olympic Committee today said the biggest scandal in the movement's 
history was ``born from the people in Salt Lake City.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Our marvelous, wonderful movement ... will always have been  
besmirched,'' Mexico's Mario Vazquez Rana told the Salt Lake 
organizers. `This is something that comes from that wonderful 
country that is the USA.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rana, the media magnate who heads the world's national Olympic  
associations, was commenting on a progress report presented to the 
IOC by Mitt Romney, the new head of the Salt Lake Organizing 
Committee, and members of his team. 
</P>
<P>
	Romney said the vote-buying scandal surrounding Salt Lake's bid  
for the 2002 Winter Games stemmed from the actions of a few bid 
committee officials who have since been removed and are under 
investigation by both state and federal agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	``We share the concern, the sense of outrage that something as  
lofty as the Olympic spirit could be tarnished by the actions of a 
few,'' Romney said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are dedicated to the principle that a few people cannot  
ruin anything so great as the Olympics. The people of Salt lake 
City ... did not take those inappropriate actions. A few people 
did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But referring to the state and federal investigations into the  
bribery scandal, IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch suggested 
some IOC members might be reluctant to visit the United States for 
fear they might be subpoenaed or charged. 
</P>
<P>
	Noting that the IOC executive board plans to meet in Salt Lake  
next year, Samaranch said, ``I hope before this meeting, as soon as 
possible, these problems can be over ... The past is past. The past 
was a good lesson for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At least four IOC members were reportedly questioned by the FBI  
last month when they attended a Coordination Commission meeting in 
Salt Lake. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten IOC members either resigned or were expelled for receiving  
cash and other improper inducements from Salt Lake bidders. The 
former two top Salt Lake bid and organizing committee officials 
lost their jobs in the scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Regarding Vazquez Rana's charge that the people of Salt Lake  
were mostly at fault, Romney told a news conference: ``I'd suggest 
that perhaps the percentage of blame has been allocated too 
strongly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Salt Lake City was also criticized for underestimating the cost  
of the games when its bidding committee submitted its estimated 
budget, forcing the new organizing committee to cut costs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I remember when we voted for Salt Lake four years ago, the  
budget was $790 million, not $1.45 billion,'' said Alex Gilady of 
Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	He suggested Salt Lake and other bidding cities ``like to  
decorate'' their proposed budgets ``so we'll like it when we are 
voting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Romney said the reason Salt Lake's budget was so low was because  
``there is no effective equivalent of accounting principles passed 
from one games to the next. 
</P>
<P>
	``When our team got into the games, they learned they had been  
very naive and incomplete. They didn't know what the full cost 
would be. They didn't know information technology would be $200 
million ...'' 
</P>
<P>
	Romney said his organizing committee hopes to leave a detailed  
accounting that can be used by other cities in assessing costs and 
submitting bids. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
