<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Ethnic Albanians Return to Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	MORINI BORDER CROSSING, Albania (AP) -- NATO forces, Albanian  
policemen and Kosovo rebels struggled to control the thousands of 
ethnic Albanian refugees lining up Thursday in battered trucks and 
tractors to go home. International aid agencies urged the refugees 
to wait a few more days. NATO forces appeared unprepared to deal 
with the flood of desperate people. Accelerating the returns were 
reports in the camps of Albanian looters crossing the border to 
prey on the abandoned homes of refugees. KLA rebels -- unarmed and 
in civilian clothes -- were helping the German soldiers who are 
running the border station recognize Albanians mixed among the 
refugees and turning them back. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S.-Russia Talks Snagged  
</P>
<P>
	HELSINKI, Finland (AP) -- U.S. and Russian negotiators failed  
today to reach agreement on Moscow's peacekeeping role in Kosovo. 
The sticking point is Russia's insistence on having its own sector 
to patrol. The talks headed by Defense Secretary William Cohen and 
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and their Russian 
counterparts were to resume tomorrow morning, a spokesman said. 
Officials said Cohen was urging the Russians to accept a geographic 
patrol area within one of the already established five peacekeeping 
sectors in Kosovo, thereby avoiding a split between NATO and 
non-NATO areas. 

</P>
<P>
	NASA Discloses Space Station Botch  
</P>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Flight controllers botched an  
attempt to move the new international space station out of the way 
of a speeding piece of space junk, but the rocket debris ended up 
passing at a safe distance. The incident was disclosed by NASA 
today. NASA said the sequence of computer commands sent up by 
flight controllers to fire the station's engines failed because of 
human error. If the rocket debris had collided with the space 
station, it could have destroyed the empty outpost, which has been 
in orbit for only seven months. The first residents are not due to 
arrive until next spring. 

</P>
<P>
	Treasury Candidate Plans Status Quo  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lawrence Summers, apparently on track for  
swift Senate approval as Treasury secretary, assured lawmakers 
today he would continue policies aimed at fostering economic 
growth. Summers now holds the No. 2 slot at the Treasury Department 
and is seeking to succeed Robert Rubin, who announced plans last 
month to leave the post. Summers received the support of many 
members of the Senate Finance Committee, which held a hearing on 
his nomination. The committee's chairman, William Roth, R-Del., 
said his panel expects to approve Summers' nomination Tuesday. 

</P>
<P>
	House OKs Posting of 10 Commandments  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Searching for a way to curb youth violence,  
the House today approved posting the Ten Commandments in schools 
and other state-owned facilities and braced for a showdown over gun 
control. The vote was 248-180. Critics said the provision was 
unconstitutional. Separately, in a second victory for the 
entertainment industry in as many days, the House rejected a 
proposal to require labeling of violent content in entertainment 
products such as video games. 

</P>
<P>
	Pope Bids Poland an Emotional Adieu  
</P>
<P>
	KRAKOW, Poland (AP) -- Pope John Paul II stretched out his Polish  
pilgrimage for a few hours of emotional visits with adoring 
faithful before flying off today, blessing ``my homeland, beloved 
country'' and hinting he may return. Some wept openly as he bade 
farewell before his plane took off on a two-hour flight that 
arrived in the evening in Rome. It was a rousing finish to the 
longest trip to any single country of his 20-year papacy. 

</P>
<P>
	Study: Internet Users Climb to 92M  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of people over 16 in the United  
States and Canada using the Internet has climbed to 92 million, 
with almost as many women as men online, according to a survey 
released today. The study also shows dramatic increases in the 
number of women who made at least a single purchase using the 
Internet, rising 80 percent over nine months ago. The survey said 
54 percent of people on the Internet are men -- although men still 
represent a slightly higher proportion, 62 percent, of all online 
buyers. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends 56.68 Higher  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks pushed higher today. At the close on Wall  
Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up 56.68 at 10,841.63. 
NYSE gainers outnumbered losers 1,845-1,199. The Nasdaq composite 
index gained 26.32 to 2,544.15. 

</P>
<P>
	Duval, Mickelson Lead U.S. Open  
</P>
<P>
	PINEHURST, N.C. (AP) -- Phil Mickelson shot a 3-under 67 today in  
the rain at Pinehurst No. 2 to tie playing partner David Duval for 
the clubhouse lead in the U.S. Open. Billy Mayfair and Paul Goydos 
also shot 67s, and 21 other players were within two shots of the 
lead after rains softened the domed greens of Pinehurst. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
