<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Labor Strike Overshadowed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Thousands of South Korean metal  
workers walked off the job Thursday in a one-day strike that drew 
little worker support amid rekindled military confrontation with 
communist North Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	The militant Korea Confederation of Trade Unions called on its  
member unions to strike in protest of an alleged government plot to 
break the labor movement. 
</P>
<P>
	But only about 7,000 workers in six small work sites heeded the  
call, joining 20,000 workers already on strike for unrelated 
disputes. 
</P>
<P>
	A similar one-day strike call Wednesday by another umbrella  
group, the Korea Federation of Trade Unions, drew fewer than 10,000 
workers, the Labor Ministry said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ministry spokesman Lee Jeong-taik attributed the lack of support  
to heightened tension off the west coast of the divided Korean 
peninsula, where North and South Korean navy vessels exchanged fire 
in disputed waters three days ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are concerned about the national security,'' Lee said.  
``For now, labor unrest is not a big problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two labor groups have threatened strikes by ``hundreds of  
thousands of members'' since media reported last week that 
prosecutors incited an illegal strike last year to give them an 
excuse to crack down on the labor movement. 
</P>
<P>
	State prosecutors were accused of plotting with managers of the  
government-run Korea Security Printing and Minting Corp. to trick 
unionized workers into staging an illegal strike by announcing 
large layoffs. The government denied the accusation and said it was 
willing to let an independent prosecutor probe the case. 
</P>
<P>
	The two unions, which claim 2 million members, said they will  
organize bigger strikes later this month when they hoped the 
military tension will have subsided. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
