<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stanley Cup Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- The Buffalo Sabres were longshots before the  
Stanley Cup finals started. Now they're facing even bigger odds 
after losing 2-0 to the Dallas Stars on Thursday night and falling 
behind 3-2 in the series. 
</P>
<P>
	In 15 previous finals tied 2-2, the winning team in Game 5 has  
gone on to win the Stanley Cup 12 times. 
</P>
<P>
	The teams who lost Game 5 who won the title: the Detroit Red  
Wings in 1950, the Toronto Maple Leafs in 1964 and the Montreal 
Canadiens in 1971. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *CLOSE AS CAN BE:* The Stars and Sabres split two regular-season  
games and there hasn't been much to separate them in the finals. 
</P>
<P>
	They have either been tied or a goal apart for all but 5:05 in  
the first five games, including an overtime battle in Game 1. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *VETERAN LINEUP:* There was an experienced lineup on the ice for  
Thursday night's Stanley Cup finals game, and it wasn't only the 
players. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of the on-ice officials had worked a total of 32 Stanley  
Cup finals among them: 18 for linesman Ray Scapinello and eight 
each for referees Kerry Fraser and Don Koharski. Linesman Jay 
Sharrers was the only one without experience in the finals. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *A REAL DALLAS STAR:* The Dallas Stars brought out their big gun  
Thursday night. No, not Brett Hull. 
</P>
<P>
	It was B.J. Thomas, who sang the national anthem.  
</P>
<P>
	Whenever Thomas sings it, the Stars are unbeaten. Thursday  
night's game made the record a perfect 6-0. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BLACK AND BLUE LINE:* One of the Dallas Stars' lines on  
Thursday night featured three players recently hobbled by injuries 
-- Brett Hull (groin), Mike Modano (wrist) and Benoit Hogue (knee). 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *CROWDED:* The crowd of 17,001 at Thursday night's Stanley Cup  
finals game marked the 49th straight sellout at Reunion Arena. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TAKING HIS SHOT:* Dallas Stars rookie Jon Sim has made it a  
habit of shooting the puck the length of the ice into the opposing 
team's net after every pregame skate. It sends a charge through the 
stands and an annoying message to the other team. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday night, the Sabres turned their net over so Sim  
couldn't do it. Sim instead shot the puck at Dwayne Rolossn as the 
Buffalo goalie was exiting the ice. Roloson shot the puck back, and 
Sim quickly returned the favor before the goalie gloved the puck 
and skated off. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, one of the Reunion Arena crew turned the net up so Sim  
could make his shot. Buffalo's Rob Ray, still hanging around at the 
Stars' end, playfully put a puck into the Dallas net. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *FATHER'S DAY:* What better way to spend the Father's Day  
weekend than to watch your son coach in the Stanley Cup finals? 
</P>
<P>
	Leeson Ruff will have that opportunity this week.  
</P>
<P>
	Ruff, of course, is the father of Buffalo Sabres coach Lindy  
Ruff. He flew into Dallas to watch Thursday night's Game 5 between 
the Stars and Sabres at Reunion Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	When the series shifts to Buffalo for Game 6 on Saturday, Leeson  
Ruff will be there, too. 
</P>
<P>
	A retired farmer, he has been driving a school bus.  
</P>
<P>
	``He missed the first couple of games but got there for the home  
games, and I think it is great,'' Ruff said of his father. ``It is 
an opportunity of a lifetime for both of us, and it is great to 
enjoy this time of year with him. 
</P>
<P>
	``He spent a lot of time hauling me from rink to rink when I was  
a kid, along with my three other brothers. Finally, he gets to reap 
a little bit of the benefits 30 years later.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *NERVOUS TIME:* Buffalo's Dixon Ward says playing in the Stanley  
Cup finals is ``nerve-wracking.'' Still, he loves it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wouldn't be any fun if it wasn't nerve-wracking,'' he said  
prior to Thursday night's Game 5 against Dallas. ``It wouldn't be 
worth fighting for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His least enjoyable times at the finals?  
</P>
<P>
	``Sitting and waiting, it's tough to deal with,'' Ward said.  
``You just want to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *RANDY'S ROLLING:* The last week has been a real stretch for  
Randy Cunneyworth, who played in the American Hockey League's 
Calder Cup finals before coming into the Stanley Cup finals in Game 
4. 
</P>
<P>
	The difference between the two finals?  
</P>
<P>
	``Down there, you were talking to one or two reporters after  
games,'' said the Buffalo Sabres forward as dozens of reporters and 
cameramen jammed the overcrowded Sabres locker room and jockeyed 
for position. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *GOALIES' GLORY:* Goals are tough to come by in this year's  
finals and Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock says it has been a tribute to 
the goaltenders. 
</P>
<P>
	``These games are 2-1 because of the guys in goal,'' Hitchcock  
said, referring to the Stars' Ed Belfour and Dominik Hasek of the 
Sabres. ``They are not 2-1 because of the style of the game. There 
are a lot of scoring chances. ... these games easily could be 4-3 
or 5-3.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres and Stars combined for 17 goals in the first four  
games -- the lowest total in 30 years in the finals. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BUFFALOED AT HOME:* Ken Hitchcock had better watch his behavior  
during games, especially when he's shown on television after a 
mistake by one of his players. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dallas coach displayed his frustration in no uncertain terms  
after the Stars gave up a goal to the Sabres after a breakdown in 
Game 4. It was caught on television, naturally, and he had to 
answer to it at home. 
</P>
<P>
	``Boy, my wife gave it to me for that,'' Hitchcock said. ``That,  
and spitting ... whoa!'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DYNAMIC DIXON:* How important has Dixon Ward been to the Sabres  
in the playoffs? They're 7-0 when he scores, that's all. 
</P>
<P>
	``That sums up that line,'' Sabres coach Lindy Ruff says of the  
line including Ward, Michael Peca and Vaclav Varada. ``When our 
so-called checking line scores, it puts us in real good shape.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SEVEN UP? With the Sabres and Stars so evenly matched, it's not  
unlikely the Stanley Cup finals will go seven games. If it does, it 
will be a rarity. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the finals were extended to a best-of-7 series in 1939,  
there have been only 10 of the 60 series that have gone the limit. 
The last to do it were the New York Rangers and Vancouver Canucks 
in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Another rarity in this year's finals: The teams were tied 2-2  
after four games. That hasn't happened since the 1991 finals 
between Pittsburgh and Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *FRONT-RUNNERS:* Don't let the Buffalo Sabres get the lead on  
you going into the third period. They're 9-0 in such situations in 
this year's playoffs, including 7-0 at home. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
