<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Warner-Lambert Loses in Pfizer Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Drugmakers Pfizer and Warner-Lambert are  
studying making the first pill that controls both high blood 
pressure and high cholesterol. 
</P>
<P>
	About 27 million Americans suffer from both conditions, which  
increase the risk of having a heart attack. 
</P>
<P>
	The partnership is just the latest for the two pharmaceutical  
titans. For two years, they have worked together to sell Lipitor, 
the nation's biggest selling cholesterol-lowering drug with sales 
expected to reach $3.3 billion this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Now they want to combine its benefits with those of Pfizer's  
Norvasc, the nation's top selling blood pressure drug in what could 
be a blockbuster. Norvasc, Pfizer's top drug, had $2.6 billion in 
1998 sales. 
</P>
<P>
	A combination Lipitor-Norvasc pill could take four years or more  
to bring to market, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Pfizer on Wednesday gave Warner-Lambert the right to  
co-promote and split profits of its upcoming migraine drug Relpax. 
The move fulfills their 1997 agreement to co-market Lipitor. 
</P>
<P>
	But it's highly doubtful that Relpax will make even half as much  
money as Lipitor. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, Lipitor should generate $3.3 billion in sales -- five  
times the $600 million in expected peak sales of Relpax. 
</P>
<P>
	Warner-Lambert retains the option to re-open the deal with the  
New York-based Pfizer if it is unsatisfied with Relpax sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem Warner-Lambert faced in completing its drug  
marketing deal with Pfizer is that its partner had nothing in its 
pipeline expected to garner sales approaching Lipitor's level. The 
Morris Plains, N.J.-based Warner-Lambert reportedly was seeking to 
share profits from multiple Pfizer drugs, but Pfizer maintained 
their agreement only called for it to share rights to a single 
product. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither company would comment on the details of the Lipitor  
agreement, except that Warner-Lambert said it retains most of 
Lipitor profits. 
</P>
<P>
	By 2002, Lipitor sales are expected to hit $5 billion, making it  
the world's best-selling prescription drug. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is difficult to get a quid (pro quo) on any product the  
magnitude of Lipitor,'' said Peter B. Corr, president of research 
and development at Warner-Lambert's drug division Parke-Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	Warner-Lambert officials maintain they're getting a good deal  
from Pfizer. Relpax should do well because studies show it works 
more quickly than existing migraine drugs, they say. Still, about 
95 million Americans have high cholesterol compared to about 20 
million who suffer from migraine headaches. 
</P>
<P>
	Relpax is awaiting federal approval, which is expected to come  
later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Lipitor, which benefited greatly from Pfizer's massive field  
staff, has made Warner-Lambert the fastest growing major drugmaker 
the last two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were hoping the completion of the Pfizer deal could  
have provided an incremental earnings boost. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was the wild card in Warner-Lambert's bull story, and I  
think the wild card has come up empty,'' said Jack Lamberton, an 
analyst with HSBC Securities. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 08:00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Poll Finds Support for Gambling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans strongly support legal gambling  
despite concerns about the integrity of sporting events and the 
threat of addiction, a new poll shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly two-thirds of American adults approve of legal gambling,  
according to a Gallup poll released Wednesday. Three-quarters of 
those surveyed said they approve of state lotteries, while 67 
percent said that opening a casino helps a community's economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of those who approve of gambling reasoned that people  
should have the right to choose what to do with their money and how 
to enjoy their free time. 
</P>
<P>
	But the poll did not represent an unqualified endorsement of  
gambling, which has grown substantially in the past two decades. 
Thirty-seven states and the District of Columbia now run lotteries; 
commercial casinos operate in 10 states, and Indian tribes have 
opened casinos in at least 22 states. 
</P>
<P>
	Almost half of those polled favored maintaining the current  
level of legal gambling, while 22 percent favored expansion, 16 
percent wanted to roll it back and 13 percent supported a gambling 
ban. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a clear distinction in Americans' minds about the  
economic benefits of casinos and the social impact on the 
communities in which they operate,'' Gallup reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifty-five percent of the adults surveyed said legalized  
gambling ``is creating a compulsive gambling problem in this 
country,'' and 68 percent said they believe sports betting leads to 
cheating or fixing games. 
</P>
<P>
	The gambling industry may face a popularity problem in the  
future, as the teen-agers who were polled, more than the adults, 
saw a dark side to gambling. 
</P>
<P>
	Only 52 percent of teen-agers polled said they approve of legal  
gambling, compared with two-thirds of the adults. Asked to assess 
the statement that gambling harms respect for the value of hard 
work, 58 percent of the teens agreed strongly or somewhat, compared 
with 43 percent of adults. 
</P>
<P>
	Gallup's telephone poll of 1,523 adults and 501 teen-agers from  
April 30-May 23 carries an error margin of plus or minus 3 
percentage points for adults, 5 percentage points for teen-agers. 
</P>
<P>
	Jack Ludwig, vice president at Gallup, cautioned that teen-agers  
have a more narrow definition of ``gambling'' than do adults, a 
majority of whom included stock market trading and office pools 
under the term. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, he said, ``Teens tend to be a little more conservative  
than adults, a little more skeptical toward gambling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gallup timed the poll to precede a lengthy report on gambling in  
America. After two years of work, the nine-member National Gambling 
Impact Study Commission will release its report Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission's report and Gallup's poll are in concert on core  
concepts: They agree that many Americans enjoy gambling, that 
casinos bring jobs with them when they enter a community, but that 
there are consequences, chief among them gambling addiction. 
</P>
<P>
	In the poll, a majority of adults approved of a wide variety of  
gambling, from bingo to horse-racing, but disapproved of two forms: 
video poker machines at local establishments and betting on 
professional sports. 
</P>
<P>
	Similarly, the commission frowned upon the proliferation of  
video poker machines and, in a divided vote, recommended a ban on 
legalized betting on collegiate sports. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
