<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Open Lower / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened lower today as fears of inflation  
inched back and investors swept in to take profits on recovering 
technology shares. 
</P>
<P>
	At 10 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 41.15 at 10,743.80. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq composite index fell 0.19 to 2,517.64 after rising  
103.16 Wednesday for its largest one-day point gain. Profit-takers 
and Compaq Computer's announcement of another disappointing profit 
outlook halted the Nasdaq's advance today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell 3.39 to 1,327.02.  
</P>
<P>
	Investors were warily waiting for Federal Reserve Chairman Alan  
Greenspan's appearance today before Congress, hoping for further 
clues on the Fed's plans. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed has issued strong hints that it will increase interest  
rates -- for the first time in four years -- at its next meeting June 
29-30 or later this year to keep the expansion in check. This week, 
Greenspan warned that recent increases in American workers' 
productivity, which have so far held down inflation, cannot last 
forever. 
</P>
<P>
	So far this year, the annual rate of inflation felt by consumers  
is 2.6 percent, compared to a 1.6 percent rise for all of 1998, the 
smallest in a dozen years. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 9-to-7 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 87.19 million shares, 
down from Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 1.35 at 630.82, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 2.18 at 762.74. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 1.17 percent. In  
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.72 percent, 
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.83 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 
1.44 percent. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
