<HEADLINE> Ex-Judge Denies Fixing Murder Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A former judge imprisoned on a racketeering  
conviction denied he ever sold leniency to murder defendants. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bribes? Definitely not,'' said former Circuit Judge Thomas  
Maloney, who arrived in court Wednesday in chains and a bright 
orange federal inmate jumpsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Maloney testified in the case of William Bracy and Roger  
Collins, whom he sent to death row. The men are seeking a new trial 
because they claim Maloney treated them severely to camouflage his 
leniency in other cases. 
</P>
<P>
	Maloney is serving a 15-year sentence for his 1993 conviction on  
four charges involving payoffs to fix cases. Supreme Court Chief 
Justice William Rehnquist once wrote that Maloney's trial showed he 
was ``thoroughly steeped in corruption.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his conviction, the 74-year-old former jurist repeatedly  
denied Wednesday that he took bribes or was unjustly severe, and 
said witnesses who claimed he did so were corrupt themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	Maloney's attorney opened the proceedings by telling U.S.  
District Judge William T. Hart he had urged his client to invoke 
the Fifth Amendment and refuse to answer any questions. 
</P>
<P>
	But Collins said Maloney wanted to testify, apparently to avoid  
any suggestion that he was finally admitting guilt. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
