<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Would Welcome Run by First Lady </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore says a U.S. Senate bid by  
first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton would be ``a positive force'' and 
generate Democratic enthusiasm throughout the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Heading into New York on his first full day as a formal  
presidential candidate, Gore was talking ``real specifics'' about 
his programs, but also was asked what impact the first lady would 
have in a key campaign state. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm all for it,'' Gore told reporters on Air Force Two as it  
flew to New York for Gore to give an outdoor speech on Wall Street. 
``It will generate enthusiasm here and around the country. Aides 
were even more direct, saying likely Republican assaults on Mrs. 
Clinton would galvanize women voters. 
</P>
<P>
	Campaign chairman Tony Coelho said Mrs. Clinton would  
undoubtedly draw heated attacks during such a race, drawing 
resentment from women voters about the GOP attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans are already honing charges she's a carpetbagger, and  
are certain to revisit sex scandals at the White House and 
financial investigations in Arkansas. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love the idea of Republicans attacking her,'' said Coelho.  
``If Republicans want to beat up on women, that's fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton has announced plans to form an exploratory  
committee and is widely expected to seek the U.S. Senate seat in 
New York, a campaign that is certain to get heavy national 
attention. 
</P>
<P>
	Her husband told reporters over dinner in Cologne, Germany, that  
nothing is definite. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really have no idea what she's going to do,'' President  
Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	There have been some suggestions that Mrs. Clinton would compete  
with Gore for campaign cash in a state that traditionally bankrolls 
Democratic presidential candidates, but Coelho dismissed that 
possibility. Gore's fund raising will largely be over by the time 
the fall campaign heats up, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those people who talk about conflicts don't know about the  
business of fund raising,'' said Coelho. 
</P>
<P>
	Even some Republicans maintain there is plenty of money for both  
Gore and Mrs. Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think she's potentially a huge factor in his campaign, but  
not financially,'' veteran New York GOP operative Jay Severin said. 
``They are both going to have more money than they need. 
</P>
<P>
	``The greatest danger is not financial, but ideological,''  
Severin said. ``It is that Gore (in New York) gets caught in the 
gravitational pull of Hillary, and it may not help him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore stuck to familiar campaign themes at an appearance Thursday  
night at the Hotel Pierre in Manhattan, promising to work toward 
greater equality for women and minorities, guarantee after-school 
programs for children at-risk and quality preschool for all 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	He talked of family values -- saying his mother, one of the  
earliest graduates of Vanderbilt Law School, inspired him to work 
for women's causes and his father instilled a belief of civil 
rights. 
</P>
<P>
	``In his honor, I begin this campaign with a pledge that the  
progress we've made towards civil rights in America is only the 
beginning ... We have much more work to do to get to the promised 
land in the 21st century to banish prejudice and inequality.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Aides said Gore was beginning to stake out his own record in the  
delicate job facing every vice president seeking the top spot, 
trying to distance himself from the White House while not seeming 
disloyal. 
</P>
<P>
	``To begin unshackling from the vice presidency is the key,''  
said Coelho. ``We need to break free of the vice presidency.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
