<HEADLINE> POLITICAL NOTEBOOK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANDAN, N.D. (AP) -- Slapping a tariff on imported wheat would  
help deter foreign sales in the United States at a time when 
American farmers are not covering their own costs, Republican 
presidential candidate Pat Buchanan said Thursday in North Dakota. 
</P>
<P>
	He advocates a tariff on imported farm commodities to equalize  
the price with U.S. production. The revenue can be used to cut 
taxes elsewhere, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the price of wheat falls below the cost of production,  
why are you importing wheat? That simply kills your family farms,'' 
Buchanan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan was making his second campaign trip in four months to  
North Dakota, where Republicans are holding an early statewide 
presidential caucus on Feb. 29. The newspaper columnist and 
television commentator was opening his state headquarters in 
Bismarck during the trip. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, the state held a February presidential primary  
election, which was won by Bob Dole, the eventual GOP nominee. 
Buchanan finished third among eight candidates, behind Dole and 
publisher Steve Forbes. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials in both parties, as well as wheat farmers and  
agricultural groups, often complain about Canadian wheat exports 
into the United States, claiming the wheat is being sold below its 
own cost of production. Buchanan said agricultural interests are 
given short shrift in trade negotiations. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Conservative activist and talk show radio host  
Alan Keyes, who failed in a 1996 bid for the Oval Office, formed a 
presidential exploratory committee on Thursday for the 2000 
presidential election. 
</P>
<P>
	Keyes, who twice ran for the U.S. Senate in Maryland, has also  
worked as a State Department official. He is now the host of a 
radio talk show popular with many conservatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Keyes is a conservative African-American who argues abortion and  
a decline in religion are behind the nation's woes. He spares 
neither Democrats nor Republicans and has criticized ``a political 
elite so utterly estranged from any connection to the people,'' as 
he said in Iowa last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Keyes has gotten little attention, he has the potential  
to split the votes of social conservatives who like his message 
even though his chances of winning seem remote. 
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- GOP presidential hopeful Gary Bauer, who  
was in Memphis Thursday for a fund raiser at a private residence, 
accused President Clinton and Vice President Gore of weakening 
national defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Standing before the Memphis Belle, a famous WWII bomber on  
display at a Memphis park, he accused the Clinton administration, 
including Democratic front-runner Gore, of failing to fund national 
defense adequately. 
</P>
<P>
	``We now have military capacity at dangerous levels at the same  
time that the president and the vice president have made more and 
more (military) commitments abroad,'' Bauer said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he favors a $50 billion increase in defense spending  
over the next five years. 
</P>
<P>
	That money, Bauer said, could come from a budget surplus and  
wasteful government programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is plenty of waste in Washington,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
                              *------	 
</P>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO (AP) -- Dan Schnur, a veteran Republican media  
strategist, on Thursday was named communications director of Sen. 
John McCain's GOP presidential campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Schnur has political ties to two McCain rivals, Texas Gov.  
George W. Bush and former Vice President Dan Quayle, but said 
McCain's policy stands and personal background drew him to the 
Arizona senator. 
</P>
<P>
	``After eight years of Clinton, voters are ready for someone who  
talks to them straight, and who's got the personal credibility to 
make it stick,'' Schnur said. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain called Schnur ``one of America's best political  
communicators,'' and cited his experience in California politics as 
a key reason for his appointment. 
</P>
<P>
	California is holding its earliest-ever primary in March, and  
McCain has said he is making the state a key target of his 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Schnur said in a phone interview that his job would be to make  
sure that all the people in key states like New Hampshire and 
California ``can recite the John McCain story by heart by next 
January.'' 
  	   	
</P>
