<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Philly Tears Down Sinking Homes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- As newly homeless owners watched, workers  
moved into a neighborhood today and began tearing down 70-year-old 
rowhouses that were slowly sinking into the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	But Hegerman Street residents at least got some good news today  
with word that authorities planned to provide state aid to help 
cover their losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Reports of sliding eggs and floors so slanted that the doors  
stuck were nothing new to residents on Hegerman, who for years had 
complained of construction problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Roseanne Allen recalled what happened when she was recently  
visiting her son, David. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was cooking an egg in the frying pan, and it slid out and  
fell on the kitchen floor,'' Allen said. ``I couldn't believe my 
eyes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The homes were built in the 1920s on old creek beds filled with  
a 21-foot layer of ash and cinders. As residents complained about 
crooked floors and windows, the city buttressed several of the 
homes, then determined two months ago that the problem had 
worsened. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, an immediate evacuation was ordered for residents of  
seven small, meticulously maintained rowhouses. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers began the demolition today by hammering bricks and  
taking out a window, as homeowners and neighbors lined the sidewalk 
across the street to watch. 
</P>
<P>
	Frank Washburn, 59, was upset that he and his family had to  
vacate their house on such short notice. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just wonder what the response would be if I walked up to  
(Mayor Edward G.) Rendell and said, 'Hey, you and your family, get 
out.' It would be a little different story, wouldn't it?'' said 
Washburn, a millwright. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials were expected to announce $1.25 million in state aid  
to the homeowners at a news conference this afternoon, The 
Philadelphia Inquirer reported. The money is the first government 
aid to be awarded. 
</P>
<P>
	Rendell initially said the city would not reimburse residents  
because the neighborhood was built before the city regulated home 
construction. Residents said their homeowners insurance policies 
will not cover the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	City and state officials are inspecting the site to determine  
whether sewer work done by the city in 1996 worsened the problem. 
That possibility was raised this week after a resident produced a 
videotape he shot that shows stream water flowing through a 30-foot 
trench dug by the crews. 
</P>
<P>
	The evacuation order for seven homes came Friday. City-leased  
moving vans rumbled down the narrow street and crews hurriedly 
loaded belongings from the small rowhouses. People scrambled to 
pack; many cleaned and swept out their homes before closing the 
doors forever. Some residents went to stay with relatives; others 
stayed in hotel suites paid for by the city. 
</P>
<P>
	Inspectors also are looking over five more homes on Devereaux  
Avenue to determine whether they, too, must be evacuated. 
</P>
<P>
	``At this point, my house is already condemned -- I won't be able  
to sell it now. I'm a working-class stiff. What am I supposed to 
do?'' said Joseph McDowell, a 22-year resident of the block. ``I'll 
end up paying a mortgage on a hole in the ground.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Building houses over stream beds and flood plains was standard  
practice during the early part of the century in Philadelphia and 
across the country, said Anne Whiston Spirn, professor of landscape 
architecture and co-director of urban studies at the University of 
Pennsylvania. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether such homes will eventually cave in depends on the type  
of fill and the construction of the foundations, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Philadelphia has seen the problem before. In 1987, the city paid  
about $20 million to bail out homeowners in the Logan section after 
about 1,000 homes were found to be sinking. Underground streams had 
eroded the ash landfill under the 80-year-old homes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 20:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Frontier Won't Act on Qwest Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Frontier Corp., a small long-distance telephone  
company, said Thursday it would take no action on the $11.3 billion 
unsolicited takeover offer from upstart Qwest, and would proceed 
with its plans to merge with Global Crossing Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest Communications International Inc. made its bold offer to  
Frontier on Sunday along with a companion $32.3 billion bid to 
acquire U S West Inc., a Denver-based Baby Bell telephone company. 
Both U S West and Frontier, based in Rochester, N.Y., have agreed 
to combine their operations with Global Crossing, a nascent 
communications company that is building a vast undersea cable 
network for Internet traffic. 
</P>
<P>
	``The current circumstances surrounding the Qwest proposal do  
not warrant any change at this time in our current initiatives that 
are designed to move Frontier's transaction with Global Crossing 
toward a prompt closing,'' Joseph P. Clayton, Frontier's chief 
executive officer, said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest's takeover offers, which consist mostly of Qwest stock,  
quickly lost much of their appeal Monday as skeptical investors 
bailed out, sending Qwest's shares down 24 percent. The stock has 
since recovered slightly, but only enough to make the combined bid 
of $43.6 billion neck-and-neck with the $43.9 billion offer from 
Global Crossing. 
</P>
<P>
	Faced with Frontier's stalling tactic, Qwest has at least three  
options: sweeten its bid, take the offer directly to Frontier's 
shareholders, or walk away. 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest, based in Denver, is the No. 4 long-distance phone  
company, but has grand visions of becoming a global provider of 
high-speed Internet communications. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for Qwest, however, said the company has no plans to  
raise the stakes. ``We are comfortable with our bid and we are 
positive that as Frontier continues to review our proposal they 
will find it superior'' to Global Crossing's, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the other camp, Robert Annunziata, Global Crossing's chief  
executive officer, took Frontier's inaction as a victory sign. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're pleased that the Frontier board of directors has  
reaffirmed its commitment to complete the merger with Global 
Crossing as planned,'' he said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	A call to U S West was not immediately returned.  
</P>
<P>
	Qwest offered a $2 per share premium if both U S West and  
Frontier agreed to the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The Internet is revolutionizing the telecommunications industry  
and is driving a string of merger bids. Companies are hoping that 
the next generation of high-speed Internet technologies will link 
more homes and businesses, providing a wealth of new opportunities 
to sell goods and provide information and entertainment. These 
hopes have prompted telecom and cable companies to make big bets on 
mergers so they can gain the size and market share that will be 
keys to new profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, AT&AMP;T Corp., the nation's largest long-distance  
company, won a bidding war against Comcast Corp. for MediaOne, a 
large cable company. And in Europe, upstart Olivetti SpA won a 
fight with Deutsche Telekom for control of Telecom Italia SpA. 
</P>
<P>
	Frontier released its statement after the markets had closed.  
Frontier's stock closed off 12 1/2 cents at $57.75 on the New York 
Stock Exchange, where U S West ticked down 6 1/4 cents to $56.93 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest's stock closed up 25 cents $36 on the Nasdaq Stock Market,  
where Global Crossing ended up 56 1/4 cents at $48.81 1/4. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 18:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Drugmaker Ads Can Backfire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK -- Television, newspaper and magazine advertisements for  
prescription drugs succeed in getting patients to ask doctors for 
the medication, a new study confirmed Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	But patients sometimes leave their physician's office with a  
prescription for a competing medication, a health industry 
researcher said at a conference where the findings were released. 
</P>
<P>
	And that is one of the biggest risksto promoting prescription  
drugs directly to consumers: Unlike any other product promotion, no 
matter how well an ad persuades consumers to ask for a drug, they 
still need a physician's permission to get it. Many of those 
doctors prefer a different remedy. 
</P>
<P>
	The study reported that about a third of the consumers who saw a  
drug ad have talked to a doctor about it. Of those inspired to 
request a particular drug because of an ad, about one in four 
received a prescription from their doctor, but not necessarily for 
the drug they requested. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey of 1,000 adults was commissioned by both Time and  
Health magazines and had a margin of error of plus or minus 5 
percentage points. The magazines are among those to have profited 
from the rise in pharmaceutical advertising directed at consumers, 
which took off in 1997 when the Food and Drug Administration 
relaxed rules governing disclosure of risks and side effects. 
</P>
<P>
	Pharmaceutical companies spent $1.35 billion on  
direct-to-consumer advertising in 1998, a 24 percent increase over 
1997 and three times the 1995 amount, according to market research 
firm IMS Health. 
</P>
<P>
	The rise of consumer advertising is a major factor behind the  
recent surge in pharmaceutical sales, experts say. Prescription 
drug sales totaled $94 billion in 1998, a 16 percent increase from 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Spending big dollars on consumer targeted drug campaign can pay  
big dividends. For example, Schering-Plough spent $136 million 
advertising allergy drug Claritin last year and generated $1.9 
billion in U.S. sales. 
</P>
<P>
	But such consumer marketing campaigns can also backfire.  
</P>
<P>
	``The highest spending does not equate to generate the most  
prescriptions. A lot of money is spent on new products but doctors 
write prescriptions for competitive products,'' said Suzanne 
Ramspacher, an official with market research firm IMS Health of 
Plymouth Meeting, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, Merck spent $41 million on consumer advertising for  
its cholesterol-lowering drug Zocor last year, six times the amount 
its competitor Warner-Lambert spent promoting its drug, Lipitor, 
according to Competitive Media Reporting. 
</P>
<P>
	Merck may have inadvertently helped Lipitor with its campaign,  
said Ramspacher. That's because Merck's heavy advertising drove 
consumers to doctors for the medication, but physicians 
increasingly have prescribed Lipitor. In the last two years, 
Lipitor has dominated the U.S. cholesterol-lowering market, and now 
outsells its nearest competitor, Zocor, almost 2-to-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Bristol-Myers Squibb's cholesterol-lowering drug Pravachol has  
met a similar fate as Zocor. Bristol Myers spent a total of $126 
million advertising Pravachol in 1997 and 1998, only to lose market 
share to Zocor. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the risk they take going out there,'' said Julie Kline,  
marketing analyst with Scott-Levin, a drug industry consulting firm 
in Newtown, Pa. ``Bristol unintentionally helped Warner-Lambert ... 
and that's not what you want to happen when you spend $67 
million.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bristol-Myers has since discontinued its consumer advertising of  
Pravachol. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 15:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Ruling Helps Va. Juveniles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- A Virginia Supreme Court ruling last week  
that both parents must be notified when a juvenile is arrested 
could enable thousands to challenge their convictions and has 
already spared the life -- at least temporarily -- of a death row 
inmate who committed murder at 17. 
</P>
<P>
	The execution of Douglas Christopher Thomas was halted on  
Wednesday, just hours before he was to die by injection and five 
days after the high court ruling. Back in 1990, only Thomas' mother 
was told of his arrest in the shooting deaths of his girlfriend's 
parents. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas became the first condemned man in Virginia to take  
advantage of the Supreme Court ruling. As many as three other men 
on death row for crimes committed before they were 18 are expected 
to raise similar challenges. 
</P>
<P>
	The reprieve doesn't mean Thomas will necessarily get a new  
trial. The Supreme Court is expected to consider the case during 
its September session. 
</P>
<P>
	In its ruling last Friday, the high court ordered a new trial  
for Jeramie Baker, who was convicted at 17 of trying to rob a 
convenience store and stabbing a clerk. Only his mother was 
notified of his arrest, despite a 1991 state law that requires 
summonses go ``to the parents'' of the juvenile. 
</P>
<P>
	The Supreme Court said the use of the plural ``parents'' means  
both the mother and father. 
</P>
<P>
	More than half of all juveniles sentenced in criminal cases in  
Virginia come from single-parent homes or families headed by 
someone other than their biological parents. And for years, it was 
common practice for Virginia prosecutors to notify only one parent. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, prosecutors said the ruling means thousands of  
convictions over the past eight years could be open to challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	David Botkins, a spokesman for state Attorney General Mark L.  
Earley, said every claim of improper notification will have to be 
raised individually ``and we will be prepared to argue those as 
necessary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Virginia should not be greatly concerned about a mass exodus  
of juvenile offenders from detention facilities,'' Botkins said. 
Any jailed youth seeking release would have to go back to court, go 
through another trial and risk getting a stiffer sentence when 
retried, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Three other men are on death row in Virginia for murders  
committed before they were 18: 
</P>
<P>
	-- Chauncey Jackson. He had just turned 16 when he killed a man  
in 1994 as the man sat in a car. ``I understand his biological 
father was not notified,'' said Rob Lee, director of the Virginia 
Capital Representation Resource Center, which represents death row 
inmates. Lee said he will raise the issue in court by July 1. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Shermaine Johnson. He was sentenced to die for the 1994  
stabbing death and rape of a woman when he was 16. His lawyer did 
not immediately return calls. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Steven Roach. He received a death sentence for the 1993  
shotgun slaying of a woman when he was 17. His lawyer,, Steven M. 
Schneebaum, said he recalled that only Roach's father attended a 
1994 hearing on whether to transfer the case from juvenile to adult 
court. Prosecutor Daniel Bouton said he could not remember who was 
notified in the case. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
