<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 08:00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Education Dept Lowers Fees on Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- More than 2 million students will be eligible  
to save an average of $631 on the loans they get from the federal 
government, modeled on discounts private lenders often give 
borrowers who repay early or electronically. 
</P>
<P>
	The Education Department also announced Wednesday that it would  
reduce the upfront fee that students now pay in its direct-loan 
program. Discounts will also go to borrowers repaying loans 
electronically and borrowers who consolidate their loans while they 
are in school, or during the grace period before they are 
officially responsible for loan repayment. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many students are struggling to pay their way through school,  
and every dollar helps,'' Education Secretary Richard W. Riley said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The average total savings will be $631 over the life of a loan  
for the average graduate with a debt of $10,000 and a standard 
10-year repayment plan. A student with a loan that size will save 
an estimated $100 on the origination fee; $157 for the interest 
rate reduction for electronic debit repayment; and $374 for the 
in-school or grace consolidation savings. 
</P>
<P>
	These discounts are similar to those now offered to students by  
private lenders and guaranty agencies subsidized by the department 
to make loans. 
</P>
<P>
	The department's direct loans, started in 1994, account for a  
third of the $32 billion loans market. 
</P>
<P>
	Private lenders and other critics of the department's loan  
administration say the programs are not saving anyone money because 
operating costs keep rising. An internal audit backed that 
assertion. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, department officials will testify about the results of  
another internal audit, which found that nearly $4 million in 
student loans over a 2 1/2-year period were forgiven for borrowers who 
were supposed to be dead but turned to be alive and earning wages. 
Also, more than $73 million in loans were forgiven for people who 
claimed permanent disabilities but continued to work. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
