<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sabres Figure Out Nieuwendyk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- The Buffalo Sabres are convinced they took Joe  
Nieuwendyk out of Game 4 of the Stanley Cup finals. The Dallas 
Stars' playoff scoring leader says they didn't. 
</P>
<P>
	To settle the debate, a check of the statistics sheet is in  
order. 
</P>
<P>
	Nieuwendyk's numbers before the Sabres' series-tying 2-1  
victory: 12 points in his previous nine playoff games, including 
two goals in Game 3. 
</P>
<P>
	Nieuwendyk's statistics in Game 4: No goals, no assists, one  
shot, only one good scoring chance. 
</P>
<P>
	Sounds like the Sabres were doing something right, even if the  
Stars could find no wrong with the way their leading playoff scorer 
played. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a solid effort, top to bottom,'' the Sabres' Dixon Ward  
said Wednesday. ``We're going to have to sustain that emotion and 
intensity if we're going to have any chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To shut down Nieuwendyk, the biggest scorer in the  
lowest-scoring Stanley Cup finals in 30 years, Sabres coach Lindy 
Ruff made two key strategic changes. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first three games, the Sabres' No. 1 line of Ward,  
Michael Peca and Vaclav Varada almost exclusively opposed the 
Stars' top line of Brett Hull, Mike Modano and Jere Lehtinen. 
</P>
<P>
	With Hull out Tuesday with a groin injury, Ruff switched the  
Peca line to oppose Nieuwendyk, who scored both goals in Dallas' 
2-1 victory in Game 3. Ruff also made sure the line played shorter 
shifts to match the Stars' quick line changes. 
</P>
<P>
	The results seemed to be evident. Nieuwendyk, who has 11 playoff  
goals and six game-winners; Jamie Langenbrunner; and Dave Reid 
combined for only four of the Stars' 31 shots and no goals. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nieuwendyk's line is so strong down low,'' Ward said.  
``Nieuwendyk's too good to totally take him out of the game. He's 
just too talented. But we did a better job of keeping them to the 
outside and limiting their chances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ruff had the advantage of making the last line change at home,  
and used it to make sure Peca opposed all of Nieuwendyk's shifts in 
the third period. He won't have that edge on the road tonight in 
Game 5 at Reunion Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	Stars coach Ken Hitchcock questions if it will make a  
difference, saying Nieuwendyk's line was as effective as ever. 
</P>
<P>
	``They had as much bite as they did any other time,'' Hitchcock  
said. ```We don't mind that matchup at all. It's a good matchup 
maybe for both teams. We're not going to change that matchup at all 
-- we like it. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was some time at the start of the game where some of the  
players got after us physically but, toward the end of the game, if 
you look at the chances for us scoring-wise, Nieuwendyk's line was 
in the middle of most of them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Hull returns tonight, Ruff must decide if he can afford to  
concentrate his best line, Peca's, against the Stars' No. 2 line, 
centered by Nieuwendyk. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've got some great individuals on that team, and they're  
an extremely hard-working team,'' Ruff said. ``We have to match 
their work ethic. Both goalies are playing tremendous, and it's 
inch by inch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nieuwendyk must have felt the same way while unsuccessfully  
trying to find open ice against Peca's line. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted to be physical and not allow them to outwork us down  
low,'' Peca said. ``They do a great job of outworking a lot of 
lines and creating good chances in front of the net. We felt good 
with the matchup most of the night.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
