<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Union Help Allowed for Agency Probes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal employees have the right to a union  
representative's help when they are questioned by an agency 
inspector general, the Supreme Court ruled today. 
</P>
<P>
	Under federal law, unionized federal employees are entitled to a  
union official's aid when an agency representative questions them 
in a matter that might lead to discipline. Today's 5-4 decision 
said an inspector general represents agency management and 
therefore the right to union representation applies. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision upheld a federal appeals court ruling that the  
National Aeronautics and Space Administration and its inspector 
general committed an unfair labor practice by restricting a union 
representative's efforts to aid an employee during a questioning 
session. 
</P>
<P>
	``In common parlance, the investigators employed in NASA's OIG  
(office of inspector general) are unquestionably representatives of 
NASA when acting within the scope of their employment,'' Justice 
John Paul Stevens wrote for the court. 
</P>
<P>
	``Representation is not the equivalent of obstruction,'' Stevens  
added. ``In many cases the participation of a union representative 
will facilitate the fact-finding process and a fair resolution of 
an agency investigation -- or at least Congress must have thought 
so.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993, the NASA inspector general's office was told that an  
employee of the George C. Marshall Space Flight Center in 
Huntsville, Ala., was suspected of authoring documents that 
threatened violence against coworkers. 
</P>
<P>
	The documents outlined ways of getting revenge, including carbon  
monoxide poisoning and exploding natural gas under a house. 
</P>
<P>
	An inspector general's investigator sought to interview the  
employee and agreed to his request to have a lawyer and union 
representative present. But when the interview began, the 
investigator said the union official could only observe and could 
not offer the employee advice. The employee, who was not identified 
in court documents, eventually was fired. 
</P>
<P>
	The union, the American Federation of Government Employees,  
filed unfair labor practice charges against NASA and the inspector. 
The Federal Labor Relations Authority ruled for the union, ordering 
NASA and the inspector general not to restrict union officials' 
actions in such interviews in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals agreed. Even though  
inspectors general have ``a significant degree of independence'' 
from the agencies they monitor, they still should be considered 
agency representatives in questioning employees, the appeals court 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Each federal agency's inspector general is appointed by the  
president and is under the general supervision of the agency head, 
but the agency head cannot interfere in any investigation. That 
structure is intended to keep agency managers from covering up 
wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	In appealing to the Supreme Court, Justice Department lawyers  
said an inspector general is more like the FBI than a 
representative of management. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, the nation's highest court disagreed. Under the inspector  
general law, ``NASA-OIG's investigators are employed by, act on 
behalf of, and operate for the benefit of NASA,'' Stevens said. 
</P>
<P>
	His opinion was joined by Justices Anthony M. Kennedy, David H.  
Souter, Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Clarence Thomas,  
Sandra Day O'Connor and Antonin Scalia dissented. 
</P>
<P>
	Writing for the four, Thomas said an inspector general ``serves  
more than just agency concerns'' and should not be considered a 
representative of the agency. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is NASA vs. Federal Labor Relations Authority, 98-369.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
