<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lacy Brings Experience to Liberty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Venus Lacy got a rough welcome from the New York  
Liberty. 
</P>
<P>
	Kym Hampton greeted her with an elbow to the mouth at practice,  
causing a cut that required seven stitches. 
</P>
<P>
	Lacy, a member of the 1996 U.S. Olympic team, is expected to  
help fill the gap left by Rebecca Lobo's season-ending injury when 
she makes her belated debut for the Liberty against Los Angeles 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``What Venus brings to the table is defense, rebounding and  
experience,'' Liberty coach Richie Adubato said of the 6-foot-4 
center. 
</P>
<P>
	Lobo's season ended 42 seconds into the opener against Cleveland  
June 10. She is expected to have surgery at the end of the month. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unfortunately, Lobo went down,'' Adubato said. ``So from our  
standpoint, we're lucky, because now we have a big body up front.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lacy, who was activated Tuesday after a week on the injured  
list, played for the defunct ABL's Nashville team. She'll bring her 
average of 10.2 points and 6.5 rebounds to a New York team missing 
its leading rebounder. 
</P>
<P>
	Lacy's extensive basketball resume includes two trips to the  
White House after winning the NCAA title at Louisiana Tech in 1988 
and the Olympic gold medal in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	She has been a late addition before. Lacy joined the Olympic  
team midway through its 52-0 year-long exhibition tour to add size 
in the paint. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's just as fiery and intense as I am,'' Teresa Weatherspoon  
said. ``Venus is a very intimidating person. She's very physical, 
taking up the paint as if it's hers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite her experience, she was among four Atlanta Olympians not  
drafted by a WNBA team. The others were four-time Olympian Teresa 
Edwards, Katrina McClain and Katy Steding. 
</P>
<P>
	``Things happen for a reason,'' said Lacy, who was looking for a  
teaching and coaching job in Ruston, La., before joining the 
Liberty June 1. ``I'm here now, and that's all I'm concerned about. 
I'm happy that (general manager) Carol (Blazejowski) decided to 
give me a chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lacy is surrounded by familiar players on the Liberty. Lacy and  
Lobo were teammates at Atlanta; Lacy played with Weatherspoon on 
the championship team at Louisiana Tech; and she played against 
Hampton and Sue Wicks during her six-year professional career in 
Japan, Italy and Greece. 
</P>
<P>
	``And I played against Crystal Robinson in the ABL,'' Lacy said.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a loving family,'' she added. ``We do a lot of things  
together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lacy will face Lisa Leslie, another Olympic teammate, in  
Friday's game against the Sparks at Madison Square Garden. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're good friends,'' Lacy said. ``She's a great player. She  
can play three positions because she has a wonderful outside shot. 
She's got that quick step on you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lacy, who is playing on her fourth team in four seasons, has  
helped teams to the finals at every level. It began with a state 
championship at Brainerd High School in Chattanooga, Tenn., where a 
nearby parkway is named after her. It continued with the NCAA title 
at Louisiana Tech and a European championship while playing for 
Greece in 1995-96. 
</P>
<P>
	Lacy started her ABL career in Seattle and led the Long Beach  
StingRays to a runner-up finish against the Columbus Quest in 
1997-98. 
</P>
<P>
	After the ABL folded in December, Lacy finished her  
undergraduate degree in sociology. She planned to work on her 
master's degree in education this summer when her agent called. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was ready to leave the next day,'' Lacy said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
