<HEADLINE> Grain, Soybean Futures Rise / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices rose early today  
on the Chicago Board of Trade amid concerns Midwest weather 
conditions will turn inhospitable for crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybean futures were supported by private forecasts for  
hot, dry weather in western growing regions of the Midwest. Gains 
were tempered, however, by National Weather Service forecasts and 
European models that indicated there will be normal temperatures 
across the entire region. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat rose in step with corn and soybeans. Prices also were  
supported by unexpected export business. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 1 1/4 cents to $2.58 1/2 a bushel; July  
corn rose 1 1/4 cents to $2.18 3/4 a bushel; July oats rose 1 cent to 
$1.19 3/4 a bushel; July soybeans rose 4 1/4 cents to $4.68 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meat and livestock futures were mixed on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle fell .05 cent to 64.67 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell .05 cent to 77.75 cents a pound; July lean hogs 
fell .57 cent to 50.70 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell .02 
cent to 42.80 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
