<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 14:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Showers and thunderstorms struck much of the East Coast on  
Thursday, with cool temperatures in much of the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	Rain spread across portions of Pennsylvania, New York, northern  
Virginia, Maryland, New Jersey and Massachusetts. 
</P>
<P>
	To the south, showers and thunderstorms stretched across the  
mid-Atlantic coast, including eastern North Carolina. Afternoon 
heat created scattered thunderstorms across Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	High pressure brought fair and dry weather, along with some cool  
temperatures, from the central Plains east across the Mississippi, 
Tennessee and Ohio Valleys. 
</P>
<P>
	Many morning record low temperatures were set across the central  
Plains. The records include a reading of 44 degrees in Dodge City, 
Kan., which bested the record of 46 set in 1945. In Salina, Kan., a 
low of 49 degrees beat the 1952 record of 51. 
</P>
<P>
	In the West, scattered showers and thunderstorms dampened parts  
of Montana, Utah and New Mexico The heaviest activity is located 
across southern New Mexico. Skies were cloudy from Washington state 
to California. 
</P>
<P>
	The afternoon high in the Lower 48 states was 99 degrees in  
Phoenix. The low was 35 degrees in Saranac Lake, N.Y., and 
Rhinelander, Wis. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 18:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Panel OKs Anti-Shutdown Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Amid a brewing budget confrontation between  
President Clinton and Congress, a House committee approved 
legislation Thursday that would prevent federal shutdowns during 
spending fights between the two sides. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure would also permit projected surpluses on the  
non-Social Security side of the budget to be used for tax cuts or 
spending increases. That would be a boon to Republicans, whose 
agenda this year includes an $800 billion, 10-year tax reduction, 
to be paid for by that portion of the surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill may end up being little more than a symbolic GOP  
statement of how it would change the budget process. White House 
budget chief Jacob Lew has said he would urge President Clinton to 
veto it, and a Senate bill overhauling budget law is less 
far-reaching. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Budget Committee approved the measure by 22-12. The  
only Democrat to support it was Rep. David Minge, D-Minn., who 
along with Rep. Benjamin Cardin, D-Md., helped write it with 
Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill provides that if spending bills are not enacted by the  
Oct. 1 start of a new fiscal year, budgets for affected agencies 
would continue at the prior year's level until the new bill is 
completed. That scenario could occur this fall, because Congress is 
on track to propose spending billions less than Clinton wants for 
many domestic programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``At least we don't make everyone suffer'' by shutting down the  
government during budget fights, said Rep. Jim Nussle, R-Iowa, one 
of the bill's authors. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats said the measure would advantage lawmakers who oppose  
proposals to cut or increase spending, and remove too much pressure 
for completing spending bills. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to have the maximum incentive to reach agreement, to  
do our jobs,'' said Rep. David Price, D-N.C. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 12:30:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3:20 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S., Russia Troops Deal Hits Snag  
</P>
<P>
	HELSINKI, Finland (AP) -- The United States and Russia struggled  
today to clinch an agreement on Russia's peacekeeping role in 
Kosovo under NATO command, still snagged on U.S. objections to 
giving Moscow control over any part of the province, U.S. officials 
said. During two days of talks, the two sides reached accord on how 
Russians will work under NATO command and on arrangements for 
sharing peacekeeping duties at the Pristina airport, where about 
200 Russian troops have been holed up since their surprise arrival 
Saturday ahead of NATO peacekeepers, the officials said. But 
Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said there would be no deal unless 
all outstanding issues were settled. 

</P>
<P>
	Milosevic a Block to Aid  
</P>
<P>
	COLOGNE, Germany (AP) -- President Clinton won the support of  
French President Jacques Chirac today for denying any 
reconstruction aid to Belgrade as long as Yugoslav President 
Slobodan Milosevic remains in power. ``Humanitarian aid, yes,'' 
Chirac said. ``Development aid, economic aid, no.'' Clinton said he 
agreed: ``We're all together on that.'' British Prime Minister Tony 
Blair has taken the same stand, virtually assuring a moratorium on 
any Western rebuilding help for Milosevic after 78 days of NATO 
bombing. The two discussed the fate of post-bombing Yugoslavia in 
two hours of talks at the Elysee Palace in Paris before Clinton 
flew here for this weekend's meetings of the world's seven biggest 
industrial powers and Russia. 

</P>
<P>
	House OKs Posting of 10 Commandments  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House, working on a bill to deter juvenile  
crime, voted today to permit the display of the Ten Commandments in 
schools as lawmakers headed toward a showdown on gun control. By 
248-180, lawmakers approved Rep. Robert Aderholt's amendment to a 
juvenile crime bill that would allow such displays. Aberhold called 
it a ``first step'' for government in reinstilling the value of 
human life in children influenced by violent culture. 

</P>
<P>
	Hatch May Launch Presidential Bid  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah is strongly  
considering joining the crowded race for the Republican 
presidential nomination, GOP sources said today. These Republicans, 
who spoke only on condition of anonymity, said Hatch, a fourth-term 
senator and chairman of the Judiciary Committee, had begun to 
search for staff in the event of a candidacy. Asked whether he was 
thinking about entering the race, Hatch said: ``I've had people 
come to me and I'm certainly courteously listening. I'm not pushing 
them away.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Vietnam Crypt To Stay Empty  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The crypt that once held the symbolic unknown  
dead from the Vietnam War will remain empty for now, the Pentagon 
said today. Scientific techniques for identifying remains has 
advanced to the point that it's not suitable to bury the remains of 
any other unknown soldiers from the war to substitute for those of 
a pilot whose exhumed body was identified last year, U.S. defense 
officials explained. 

</P>
<P>
	Amtrak: Good Service or Free Travel  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Amtrak, wooing people to take the train, not  
the plane, today promised all passengers good service or a voucher 
for a free ride. The railroad, which must wean itself from federal 
operating subsidies by 2003, hopes planned service improvements 
will hike revenues by 85 million in a three-year period. 

</P>
<P>
	Leader of British Catholics Dies  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Cardinal Basil Hume, spiritual leader of the 4.6  
million Roman Catholics of England and Wales, died today. He was 
76. Hume died just hours after his official spokesman announced 
that his cancer had reached its final stages. The cardinal had 
asked for renewed prayers. Hume, widely respected by people of all 
faiths, became one of the most influential figures in British 
public life after his appointment as Archbishop of Westminster in 
1976. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Gains 28, Nasdaq Gains 22  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was up 28.82 at 10,813.77. NYSE gainers outnumbered losers 
1,667-1,253. The Nasdaq composite index was up 22.04 at 2,539.87. 

</P>
<P>
	Duval, Mickelson Lead U.S. Open  
</P>
<P>
	PINEHURST, N.C. (AP) -- David Duval shot a nearly flawless  
3-under 67 in the rain at Pinehurst No. 2 today to tie playing 
partner Phil Mickelson for the early lead in the U.S. Open. Showing 
no ill effects from burns he suffered on his hand last week, Duval 
didn't make a bogey all day and birdied two of the last four holes 
to pull even with Mickelson and share the clubhouse lead. 

</P>
<P>
	Sabres, Stars Serve Up Cup Thrills  
</P>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- What's being considered a truly competitive series  
in the Stanley Cup playoffs goes into Game 5 tonight in Dallas with 
the hometown Stars and the Buffalo Sabres tied 2-2. The previous 
four seasons saw 4-0 sweeps in the finals. ``This is as tight a 
matchup as you'll find,'' Stars forward Brian Skrudland said. 
``Both teams deserve a lot of credit for where they are.'' 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by PRUDENCE HELLER  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
