<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DNA Leads to Arrest in 1976 Murder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EVERETT, Wash. (AP) -- New DNA-testing methods have led police  
back to the man first charged in the murder of his sister-in-law 23 
years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	James Lucius Stephens Jr. was arrested Wednesday in the rape and  
stabbing of Kimberly Marie Kuntz, 18, who was attacked in 1976 
while baby sitting for Stephens' 3-year-old daughter in Lynnwood. 
</P>
<P>
	After the slaying, Stephens was charged with first-degree murder  
and first-degree rape, but the charges were dismissed without 
prejudice -- meaning they could be refiled -- because of lack of 
evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephens was scheduled to be arraigned today in Snohomish County  
Superior Court. 
</P>
<P>
	The 46-year-old Stephens, who now lives in West Seattle and  
works for a shipping company, has been under intermittent 
surveillance for some time, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators reopened the case two years ago, when advances in  
DNA technology allowed for very good results even when the evidence 
was in bad shape. A major break came this week after they found a 
perfect match between a recent blood sample taken from Stephens and 
a semen stain on the shirt worn by Ms. Kuntz when she was killed. 
The sample was obtained under court order. 
</P>
<P>
	``Twenty years is a long time, but it's not impossible by any  
stretch of the imagination,'' said George Riley, scientific 
director of GeneLex, the Seattle-based laboratory that performed 
the key DNA tests. 
</P>
<P>
	Scientists say the DNA profile from the semen stain, which would  
have been considered too small for adequate results even a few 
years ago, is found in only one in every 377 million Caucasians. 
</P>
<P>
	That profile was a perfect match for Stephens' DNA, Snohomish  
County Deputy Prosecutor Paul Stern said in court papers. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Kuntz was found stabbed to death in the apartment occupied  
by her sister Donna, Stephens' estranged wife, and the couple's 
daughter. 
</P>
<P>
	Court papers said Mrs. Stephens told officers that her husband  
had recently bound her with tape and assaulted her in the bedroom 
where Ms. Kuntz's body was found. Stephens subsequently pleaded 
guilty to second-degree assault of his wife. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time of his first arrest, Stephens admitted visiting the  
apartment the evening of the slaying. He said he had tried to talk 
with his sister-in-law about his marital problems but she ``didn't 
have much to say.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
