<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) -- The new director of Brazil's Federal  
Police on Thursday denied accusations that he tortured a priest 
during the country's military dictatorship and threatened to sue 
his accusers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am innocent. I have never seen an instrument of torture in  
the police stations where I worked,'' Joao Campelo told Congress' 
committee on human rights during five hours of testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	A day earlier, Jose Antonio Magalhaes Monteiro, the former  
priest who is now a philosophy professor at University of Alagoas, 
told the committee that Campelo interrogated him while another 
office slapped him around, hit him and kicked him in the back. He 
also said Campelo helped fasten him onto a torture device. 
</P>
<P>
	Monteiro said he was arrested for running a school that taught  
students social awareness while it taught them to read. The 
generals that ran Brazil from 1964 to 1985 considered the 
instruction subversive. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- Soccer holligans broke windows,  
destroyed traffic signs and battled police Thursday in a violent 
celebration after their favorite team, Palmeiras, won a Latin 
American soccer tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Riot troops used tear gas and truncheons to disperse crows in  
the city's financial district shortly after the Sao Paulo squad 
defeated Deportivo Cali of Colombia to win the South American club 
championship, known as the Copa Libertadores. 
</P>
<P>
	The violence started during the game Wednesday night, when a  
group of fans without tickets tried to crash stadium gates and were 
repelled by police. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said the the group of Palmeiras fans is known for  
fighting with rival fans. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) -- Juan Marichal, the  
sports minister and Hall of Fame pitcher, said Thursday that people 
accusing him of corruption only want to damage his reputation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to demonstrate to the Dominican people that the name  
Juan Marichal is clean and it will stay that way forever,'' 
Marichal said. 
</P>
<P>
	Marichal was questioned by Judge Julio Ibarra Rios for nearly  
six hours Wednesday about accusations that he skimmed at least $6 
million from the purchase of sports equipment for the ministry and 
that he benefited financially from bets placed on cockfighting 
matches. 
</P>
<P>
	Marichal, 64, played in the major leagues for 16 seasons, mostly  
with the San Francisco Giants. He was inducted into the Hall of 
Fame in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Continental Airlines said Thursday that it had  
pulled out of talks to refloat Peru's flagship air carrier 
Aeroperu, which had grounded its flights in March saddled with $174 
million in debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Aeroperu officials had announced two weeks ago that the  
Houston-based Continental had agreed to take over 49 percent of 
Aeroperu shares worth about $30 million as part of a debt 
restructuring agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Aeroperu's shutdown left Peru with just one major air carrier,  
Aerocontinente, to serve its internal market. Tours operators said 
the lack of competition was affecting tourism. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Two eruptions at the Popocatepetl volcano  
outside of Mexico City sent a light fall of ash over a nearby 
community Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Center for the Prevention of Disasters reported a  
light increase in activity at the volcano, 40 miles southeast of 
Mexico City, the government news agency Notimex reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The 17,925-foot volcano has been spewing vapor, ash and rock  
intermittently since December 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Construction work at Venezuela's  
largest oil refining complex resumed Thursday after President Hugo 
Chavez dispatched 200 National Guardsmen to control labor unrest. 
</P>
<P>
	Three projects to build additional refining capacity were  
suspended on Tuesday after industry officials said they could no 
longer guarantee employee safety. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision to stop construction was made in response to weeks  
of protests by unions and unemployed workers demanding payment of 
suspended salaries and the rehiring of laid-off employees. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jose complex employs more than 22,000 people both directly  
and indirectly. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- President Fidel Castro and Premier Owen Arthur of  
Barbados signed economic and sports agreements Thursday designed to 
strengthen already friendly relations between the two Caribbean 
nations. 
</P>
<P>
	The economic agreement, aimed at stimulating foreign investment,  
would guard investors from being taxed twice by both countries. The 
second would increase sports exchanges between Cuba and Barbados. 
  	   	
</P>
