<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Compaq Issues Earnings Warning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Compaq Computer Corp. dismayed Wall Street for a  
second time in two months this morning, disclosing an unexpected 
quarterly financial loss and a restructuring aimed at slashing $2 
billion in annual costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Compaq, which ousted its chief executive in April after another  
unexpected financial hit, said the restructuring includes job cuts, 
yet to be determined. Compaq tied its troubles to computer price 
wars, sluggish sales and a bloated cost structure at the company. 
</P>
<P>
	The company predicted it would report a loss of up to 15 cents a  
share in the second quarter, compared to a profit of 20 cents 
expected by Wall Street analysts. 
</P>
<P>
	The news sent Compaq's stock swooning as much as 10 percent  
before recovering somewhat in morning trading. Compaq shares were 
trading at $21.93 3/4, down 31 1/4 cents a share, or 1.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said it will revamp into three business groups. The  
groups, focused on enterprise solutions and services, personal 
computers and consumers, will each have separate profit-and-loss 
accountability. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the two months since the change of management at the  
company, we have taken a deep look into the strengths and 
challenges of Compaq,'' said Benjamin Rosen, Compaq's chairman and 
acting chief executive officer. Rosen said the changes are aimed at 
speeding up the company's reaction to the market and accelerating 
sales. 
</P>
<P>
	On April 9, Compaq announced first-quarter profits would be half  
of what analysts expected. Nine days later, Compaq ousted chief 
executive Eckhard Pfeiffer, and chief financial officer Earl Mason 
quit. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosen said the problems that afflicted first-quarter earnings  
continued. Revenues were expected to be flat to down, sequentially 
from the first quarter. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
