<DOCNO> APW19990617.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 09:10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion Today  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- People seldom list progress toward Christian  
unity as a hallmark of Pope John Paul II's reign. In fact, critics 
sometimes treat his two decades on the throne of Peter as a dry 
period for ecumenism. Yet 1999 is turning out to be an important 
year in spiritual geopolitics. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the Vatican's negotiations with other Christians were  
launched before John Paul took office, but he has fostered the 
process and his 1995 encyclical ``Ut Unum Sint,'' or ``That They 
May Be One,'' reaffirmed the centrality of the task. 
</P>
<P>
	To ordinary churchgoers, the theological issues involved in  
these talks seem arcane. But they have defined whole cultures for 
centuries and continue to sunder Christianity. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest breakthrough occurred last week. The Holy See,  
representing a billion believers, and the Lutheran World 
Federation, with a flock of 57 million, announced an accord on 
``justification,'' the doctrine that first caused Martin Luther to 
launch the Protestant Reformation. The agreement will be signed 
Oct. 31 in Augsburg, Germany, 482 years to the day after Luther 
posted his ``95 Theses'' against the papacy. 
</P>
<P>
	The heart of the new Lutheran-Catholic accord reads:  
</P>
<P>
	``Together we confess: By grace alone, in faith in Christ's  
saving work and not because of any merit on our part, we are 
accepted by God and receive the Holy Spirit, who renews our hearts 
while equipping and calling us to good works.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If salvation doesn't depend on a person's charitable deeds or  
piety, that sounds just like what Luther said St. Paul taught in 
the New Testament. But both sides now explain that, despite past 
misunderstandings, Protestants and Catholics really agree on this. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lutherans endorsed the main agreement a year ago. But Rome  
had more of a struggle over certain technical points so the two 
sides had to work out a further ``annex'' to the main document. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lutheran accord came a month after release of a discussion  
paper on church authority from theologians representing the Vatican 
and the 55 million Anglicans and Episcopalians. The text says that 
Christian teaching normally is stated collectively by bishops and 
accepted by the church membership. But ``in certain circumstances'' 
the pope by himself can defining doctrine, and that authority is 
``a gift to be received by all the churches.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No accord is on the horizon here, just discussion. At the moment  
it seems unlikely that Anglicanism would ever accept papal teaching 
authority. 
</P>
<P>
	Those disputes are young compared with the rift between Rome and  
the churches of the East, which date back a millennium or more. 
Here too, the parties are talking. 
</P>
<P>
	Such discussions won't change church life tomorrow, or next  
year. But ``seeds are being sown'' to overcome misunderstandings 
that have persisted for centuries, said the Rev. Richard John 
Neuhaus, a Lutheran turned Catholic and editor of First Things 
magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to see this in terms of the next 50 to 100 years,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Theologically, Rome is far closer to the 223 million Eastern  
Orthodox than to the Protestants. And the pope from Poland has put 
priority on healing a breach that dates from A.D. 1054. At one time 
he hoped some grand gesture of Orthodox-Catholic reconciliation 
would usher in the new millennium. But progress is agonizingly slow 
and the dream has died. 
</P>
<P>
	No doubt it's a severe disappointment for John Paul II. ``That  
was his great vision and he pursued it relentlessly,'' says George 
Weigel, author of a forthcoming biography of the pope. ``This is a 
great historical tragedy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, in May the pope managed a successful pilgrimage to  
Romania, the first Orthodox land he has been able to tour. And he 
plans to visit Orthodox Armenia and honor its prime churchman, the 
ailing Catholicos Karekin I. 
</P>
<P>
	Rome is prepared for full communion, but Orthodoxy is suspicious  
of Catholicism for historical reasons. The fall of European 
communism worsened matters by stirring rivalries over property and 
souls in Eastern Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Another irritant is the existence of Eastern Rite Catholics, who  
embrace papal authority while following Orthodox forms of worship. 
The Orthodox generally feel that Catholicism should keep off their 
ancestral turf. The warm reception that the pope received from 
Romania's 84-year-old Patriarch Teoctist was significant, given the 
historic rivalry between the Orthodox and the vital Eastern Rite 
presence that Rome maintains in Romania. 
</P>
<P>
	Patriarch Alexy II of Moscow has been less friendly, and John  
Paul will not make his long-desired trip to Russia without Orthodox 
consent. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the pope's pending visit to Armenia further  
underscores the complexity of the Orthodox opening. The Romanians 
and Russians are Eastern Orthodox, united with Istanbul's 
ecumenical patriarch, who follow the teachings of seven ancient 
church councils held before the split with Rome. 
</P>
<P>
	The Armenians belong to a separate branch known as the Oriental  
Orthodox, along with independent sister churches in Syria, Egypt, 
Ethiopia and India. These churches broke with the rest of 
Christendom in the 6th century and accept only the doctrines of 
Christianity's first three councils. Enormous obstacles to 
reconciliation remain, but when Karekin visited Rome in 1996 he 
issued a joint declaration of faith with the pope. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1990, Oriental Orthodox and Eastern Orthodox theologians  
reached a preliminary agreement on the divinity and humanity of 
Christ. Just as Vatican theologians are doing, they recognized that 
their two branches are united on important issues of faith and that 
the differing terminology used to express those beliefs need no 
longer divide them. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 16:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
