<DOCNO> APW19990617.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 11:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Greenspan Fears Economic Imbalance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan told  
Congress today that inflation remains in check for now, but the 
central bank should consider taking pre-emptive action to prevent 
any threat to continued economic growth. 
</P>
<P>
	By using the word ``pre-empt,'' Greenspan was sending a signal  
the Fed will act soon to raise short-term interest rates to slow 
the economy before signs of inflation begin to show, economists 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second such hint from Greenspan this week. However,  
economists disagreed over how many rate increases the Fed might be 
contemplating. 
</P>
<P>
	``This removes all doubt that the Fed is ready to move'' to  
raise interest rates, said David Jones, chief economist for Aubrey 
G. Lanston &AMP; Co. in New York. ``He is clearer than usual.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In order to keep the economy growing, ``It is useful to pre-empt  
forces of imbalance before they threaten economic stability,'' 
Greenspan said. Sometimes that is not possible because the future 
``can be too opaque to penetrate,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we can be pre-emptive, we should be, because modest  
pre-emptive actions can obviate the need of more drastic actions at 
a later date that could destabilize the economy,'' Greenspan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan's testimony before the Joint Economic Committee came  
just a day after the government reported that inflation remained 
tame during May. 
</P>
<P>
	The stock market showed little adverse reaction to today's  
speech. Some economists said that was because traders already had 
factored in an expected rate increase. 
</P>
<P>
	``They had been worried that he would say something worse,''  
said economist Sung Won Sohn of Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. in Minneapolis. 
``I think what we are getting from the markets is a sigh of relief. 
They are not overjoyed but the fear is diminished.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones said he believes the Fed may raise rates as many as three  
times this year, beginning at its next meeting June 29-30. But Sohn 
said that for now, he believes the Fed is only certain to raise 
rates one time. 
</P>
<P>
	New evidence of continued strong employment came today from the  
Labor Department, which reported that the number of Americans 
filing new claims for unemployment benefits fell by 28,000 last 
week to 297,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's trade deficit held steady at a record high of $18.9  
billion in April, matching the March figure, the Commerce 
Department said today. After a five-month drop, U.S. exports rose 
1.2 percent but imports continued to climb, by 1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because monetary policy operates with a significant lag, we  
have to make judgments, not only about the current degree of 
balance in the economy, but about how the economy is likely to fare 
a year or more in the future,'' Greenspan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Democrats were critical of Greenspan's message, worrying  
that average Americans now benefiting from the strong economy might 
be hurt if it is slowed by higher interest rates. ``I very much 
hope the (Fed) won't adopt a so-called pre-emptive strategy without 
finding any basis or foundation in any of the economic trends,'' 
said Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan reiterated what he told Congress earlier this week,  
that increases in American workers' productivity linked to 
improvements in technology have so far kept inflation in check, a 
significant change over the way the economy operated in years past. 
</P>
<P>
	However, he said, ``Despite its extraordinary acceleration,  
labor productivity has not grown fast enough to accommodate the 
increased demand for labor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The economy is in the middle of an exceptional period of strong  
growth and continued low inflation, Greenspan said. ``For the 
period immediately ahead, inflationary pressures still seem 
well-contained.'' But he added: ``There are developing imbalances 
that give us pause and raise the question: Do these imbalances 
place our economic expansion at risk?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed has not raised interest rates in more than two years.  
When interest rates go up, borrowing becomes more expensive, 
consumers and businesses tend to spend less and thus the economy 
tends to slow. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Fed policy-makers said they were leaning toward  
raising short-term interest rates. Some long-term interest rates 
already have begun to climb a bit because of expectations that the 
Fed might eventually raise short-term rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Strong consumer demand has kept the U.S. economy growing even as  
some foreign countries have suffered through two years of 
recession. Now those countries, especially in Asia and Latin 
America, ``are clearly on firmer footing, though in some cases 
their turnarounds appear fragile,'' Greenspan said. 
</P>
<P>
	If American consumers continue their buying binge as demand for  
American goods picks up elsewhere, that could tax production 
capacity and perhaps eventually lead to inflationary pressures, 
many economists believe. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan said that one of the things Fed policy-makers must  
take into account is the relative importance to place on stock 
market prices. Stock prices can climb to unsustainable levels even 
when underlying product prices are relatively stable, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	While it is unclear if the current high stock market prices  
represent a ``bubble,'' Greenspan noted that ``bubbles generally 
are perceptible only after the fact.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even when bubbles burst, ``the consequences need not be  
catastrophic for the economy,'' Greenspan said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
