<HEADLINE> No. 1 Amateur Pick Hospitalized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) -- Josh Hamilton, the No. 1 overall pick  
in this month's amateur baseball draft, remained hospitalized a 
second day Wednesday with a stomach ailment after arriving for the 
start of his rookie league season. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton accompanied his new teammates on a 14-hour bus trip  
Monday from St. Petersburg, Fla., to the Tampa Bay Devil Rays' 
Class A affiliate in Princeton. 
</P>
<P>
	But by Tuesday morning, he was vomiting and had a slight fever.  
He was taken to Princeton Community Hospital, where he remained 
Wednesday night. A nursing supervisor said he had gastroenteritis, 
a stomach and intestinal disorder. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton's teammates Tuesday began workouts at Hunnicutt Field a  
half-mile away in preparations for Friday's Appalachian League 
season opener against the Bluefield Orioles. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton, 18, was the first high school player to be taken with  
the first pick since Seattle selected Alex Rodriguez in 1993. 
Hamilton batted .529 with 13 homers and 35 RBIs in 25 games as a 
senior at Athens Drive High in Raleigh, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton agreed to a $3.65 million signing bonus, the largest  
ever given to a drafted amateur player who signed with the team 
that selected him. In rookie ball, however, he'll earn less than 
$1,000 a month and be given $20 a day in meal money on the road. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite going 18-3 as a pitcher the last two seasons, Tampa Bay  
plans to develop him as a right fielder. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton's status for the opener is uncertain.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be an honor to be able to work with a kid like  
that,'' said Princeton batting coach Mike Tosar. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
