<HEADLINE> Tourists Evacuated From Yosemite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YOSEMITE NATIONAL PARK, Calif. (AP) -- About 200 tourists were  
evacuated from their cabins after a geologist warned there could be 
more rockslides like that one that killed a climber over the 
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	After studying the area from a helicopter and on foot, the U.S.  
Geological Survey geologist determined there were additional 
fractures on the side of the cliff where the first boulders broke 
loose Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He felt it was ready to go,'' Yosemite spokesman Scott Gediman  
said Wednesday. ``It could be in the next few hours or the next few 
weeks. Predicting rockslides is not an exact science.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 80 wood and tent cabins used by visitors were evacuated  
Wednesday evening. Seventy-six park employee cabins were emptied 
Sunday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Although accommodations are hard to come by during the summer  
season, last-minute cancellations and people leaving the park ahead 
of schedule enabled the visitors to find new cabins, Gediman said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
