<HEADLINE> Jury Rejects $30M Claim Against GM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOUNT CLEMENS, Mich. (AP) -- A jury today rejected a $30 million  
claim that General Motors Corp. was responsible for a Florida crash 
that killed Philadelphia Eagles star Jerome Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	The eight-member Macomb County Circuit Court jury reached a  
unanimous verdict on the suit filed by Brown's survivors, a court 
secretary said. 
</P>
<P>
	Next week marks the seventh anniversary of the crash that killed  
Brown, an All-Pro defensive tackle, and his 12-year-old nephew. 
</P>
<P>
	Edward Ricci, a lawyer for Brown's relatives, said GM never  
specifically tested the Corvette ZR1 -- the model Brown was driving 
-- for inadvertent air bag deployment that the plaintiffs claim 
caused the crash. 
</P>
<P>
	GM said Brown was speeding the wrong way down a one-way street  
and was not wearing a seat belt. 

  	   	
</P>
