<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thomas Delivers Off Bench for Knicks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Kurt Thomas' numbers in Game 1 of the NBA  
Finals looked like they belonged on San Antonio's side of the 
boxscore. 
</P>
<P>
	Coming off the bench, Thomas had 13 points, 16 rebounds and four  
steals for the New York Knicks, no small feat against 7-footers 
David Robinson and Tim Duncan. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't matter,'' Thomas said. ``If I get 16 rebounds, if I  
get 20 rebounds, if we lose it doesn't matter. This is all about 
winning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And that's something the shorthanded Knicks couldn't manage in  
the opener of the championship series, losing to the Spurs 89-77. 
</P>
<P>
	If the loss had a bright side for the Knicks it was the work of  
Thomas. He would have started if Larry Johnson had not. As it was, 
he saw plenty of playing time, logging 31 minutes because New 
York's other big men, including Johnson, were in early foul 
trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas brought a simple philosophy to the battle with Duncan and  
Robinson. 
</P>
<P>
	``I try to use my quickness, my strength, my knowledge of  
defense and just play,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	That's a lot more than he was able to do the last two years when  
injuries limited him to 23 games, 18 with Miami in 1996-97 and then 
five with Dallas last season and left the onetime NCAA scoring 
champion in basketball limbo as a free agent. 
</P>
<P>
	The lost year in Dallas was particularly tough with Thomas  
reduced to assistant coach status. He was not exactly the key 
player in designing game plans, though. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was just sitting, trying to learn as much as possible to  
help my game as a player,'' Thomas said. ``I was doing rehab and we 
didn't have a big man coach. It was a way to keep me around the 
guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even after the year off, he had plenty of teams offering  
contracts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I talked to Cleveland, Houston, Miami, Denver,'' he said. ``I  
had a lot of teams willing to take a chance on me. I felt I was 
worth more than one year and $1 million.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New York went for two years for $3.68 million, bargain basement  
prices in current basketball economics, and Thomas signed on. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had no doubt in my ability,'' he said. ``You can't find a  
6-9 guy who can do the things I can do and not take a chance with 
it. The only question was whether I could stay healthy. All the 
doctors said my ankle would be fine. All I needed to do was to take 
a year off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas battled his way in to the starting lineup and averaged  
8.1 points and 5.7 rebounds. He was bounced to the bench during the 
Indiana playoff series when Jeff Van Gundy decided to start Latrell 
Sprewell, but it seemed he would be starting again in Game 1 
because of Johnson's sprained knee. Then LJ decided he could play 
and Thomas became the sixth man again. 
</P>
<P>
	It didn't bother him.  
</P>
<P>
	``When he calls your number, you've got to be ready,'' Thomas  
said. ``I wasn't surprised at what I did. I know my ability to do a 
lot of things. I knew I had to be aggressive and attack the 
glass.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That, Thomas said, is how the Knicks must approach Game 2 on  
Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to play more as a team, get the assists up and the  
turnovers down,'' he said. ``We've got to pick and choose when we 
double team and we've got to get to the free throw line.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
