<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Burned Dog Pound Stirs Mass. Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOLLAND, Mass. (AP) -- People used to roll their eyes when  
Patricia Mumper stood up at meetings and told town leaders to build 
a better dog pound. 
</P>
<P>
	She may have meant business.  
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Mumper stands charged with burning the dog pound down.  
</P>
<P>
	The 57-year-old animal rights activist has pleaded innocent to  
arson, which carries up to 10 years in prison. But hours before the 
fire on June 1, she warned a Holland selectman she would ``do 
something to embarrass the town,'' and she was seen near the pound 
around the time of the fire. 
</P>
<P>
	No animals were there, and no one was hurt.  
</P>
<P>
	The pound, which is now a charred ruin, was a simple  
25-by-25-foot wooden shed with four separate runs, each with a dog 
house. 
</P>
<P>
	Christian Petersen, Holland's dog catcher, told town leaders in  
May that the pound was in ``deplorable condition.'' Even so, he 
said, whoever set the fire ``took a decent, reasonable facility 
from the animals -- and left them with nothing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Stephen Dean, head of the Springfield-based Dog Adoption  
Network, the burning of Holland's dog pound was an act of civil 
disobedience. 
</P>
<P>
	``This burning of the dog shelter was a symbol of total  
frustration in the minds of people who felt that the animals were 
incarcerated there,'' he said. ``The only thing worse than being a 
lost dog in Holland was being a found dog -- and being put there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dean came to know Ms. Mumper several years ago, when both were  
newly arrived summer residents in this central Massachusetts town 
of 2,300 people on the Connecticut line. 
</P>
<P>
	They joined to help form a local group that tried to get town  
leaders to replace the shed where stray dogs are kept to await 
their owners. ``She was much more vested in it and emotional,'' 
Dean said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Mumper, a married administrative assistant at an insurance  
company, began living in town full-time within the past year. She 
became a fixture at meetings, where she held forth at length on the 
pound: disgraceful, not fit for a dog. 
</P>
<P>
	Some even agreed more or less, but many eventually rolled their  
eyes. They had heard it all before from her. 
</P>
<P>
	The pound ``wasn't a giant issue -- just to one person,'' said  
Paul Dimond, who owns a convenience store. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't see her as a threat -- a nuisance, yes, but never a  
threat. She'd never let you forget,'' said Paul Gillis, a selectman 
who retired this month. 
</P>
<P>
	When Ms. Mumper warned Gillis she would ``do something to  
embarrass the town,'' Gillis expected a lawsuit. Instead, the pound 
went up in flames that evening. 
</P>
<P>
	Mumper disputed Gillis' memory. She said that she did not tell  
him the night of the fire that the town would be embarrassed. 
Instead, eight months or a year before the pound burned down she 
said at a town meeting: ``Do I have to embarrass the town by taking 
this to the media?'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Ms. Mumper said she was at the pound on the day of the  
fire just to take photographs, according to Irene Loureiro, an 
animal rights activist who has worked with Ms. Mumper for more than 
20 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a long-languishing proposal to build a new pound  
remains on hold. 
</P>
<P>
	The dog catcher said he might bring dogs to a veterinarian in a  
nearby town and pay for temporary shelter. But he said that in the 
meantime, the town may need to set up some kind of temporary pound, 
probably with worse conditions than in the old one. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
