<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 13:20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> D-Backs Bell Hits With the Big Boys </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Take a look at the home run leaders in the  
National League: Sammy Sosa, Jeff Bagwell, Jay Bell. 
</P>
<P>
	Jay Bell?  
</P>
<P>
	What's the second baseman of the Arizona Diamondbacks, who has  
never hit more than 21 homers in any of his nine full major-league 
seasons, doing with the big swingers of the game? It makes about as 
much sense as a second-year franchise winning the NL West title. 
</P>
<P>
	So far it's been that kind of year.  
</P>
<P>
	Sixty-six games into the season, Bell has 20 home runs, only two  
fewer than Sosa and Bagwell and one more than Mark McGwire. 
Comfortable in the No. 2 spot in Arizona's batting order, behind 
speedy Tony Womack and ahead of Luis Gonzalez and Matt Williams, 
Bell is a big reason the Diamondbacks have a four-game lead in the 
NL West and were the first team in the league to win 40 games. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got the ability to do a lot of things when Tony gets on  
base,'' Williams said. 
</P>
<P>
	``When Tony gets on base, they're coming right after Jay and  
he's making them pay. When he gets his pitch, he's not missing it. 
That's all it is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bell's polite, studious manner masks an intense competitive  
drive. After striking out recently, he could be seen pummeling the 
water cooler in the dugout. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year was tougher.  
</P>
<P>
	He was the first free agent to sign with the Diamondbacks, and  
his five-year, $34 million deal was widely criticized. Then, as one 
of the few experienced major leaguers on an expansion team, Bell 
hit just .251 batting average with 129 strikeouts, 67 RBIs, and 79 
runs scored. Late in the year, he accepted a move from shortstop to 
second without complaint. 
</P>
<P>
	``He and Matt took on the onus of the world last year, and you  
wouldn't want it any other way,'' manager Buck Showalter said. 
``But it doesn't always make a productive hitter when you've got 
that mentality that `Hey, I've got to do it. Nobody else is going 
to do it.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Nobody is saying Bell is overpaid these days. With the club's  
free-agent spree in the off-season, Bell has plenty of help. But 
don't look for him to claim any vindication. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think Jay is that type of person,'' Showalter said.  
``I think he has a real grip on the realities of this world and how 
fickle people can be. As long as he has the respect of his peers, 
that's what's important to him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bell doesn't expect to stay with the Sosas and McGwires all  
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to allow myself to get caught up in the home  
runs and that kind of stuff, even though they're fun,'' Bell said. 
``Certainly there are times in the game where you need one and 
hopefully it comes, but I haven't done anything out of the ordinary 
to produce those kinds of numbers, and I'm not going to start 
now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Showalter said Bell's experience is a factor. He hit his  
career-high 21 with Kansas City two seasons ago, then had 20 last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think a lot of players as they get older have more of an  
idea of what they have to do to be successful,'' Showalter said. 
``He knows when to cut down on his swing. I think he knows the 
certain counts and sequences that he can go for the pump a little 
more. He's a very intelligent hitter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bell, 33, agrees that experience plays a part, but not the  
biggest part. 
</P>
<P>
	``The knowledge of pitchers around the league and knowing what  
type of hitter I am,'' he said. ``But 95 percent of the credit goes 
to my teammates. They're the ones who have allowed me to have 
success.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bell has a team-high 55 strikeouts. But some of that is because  
he must take a few pitches to allow Womack a chance to steal. He 
has 30 walks, 50 RBIs and a .288 batting average. 
</P>
<P>
	Bell is most proud of his NL-best 60 runs scored.  
</P>
<P>
	``I know what Mark's going to do or what Sammy's going to do or  
what Matt's going to do. These guys are bonafide home run 
hitters,'' Bell said. ``They'll hit 40 or 50 or 60. For me, I'm 
going to try to get on base and score as many times as I possibly 
can. That's what's been fun.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
