<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sugar Futures Rise Sharply  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Sugar futures prices rose sharply Thursday on the Board of Trade  
of the City of New York on speculation that a recent surge in 
Russian buying has sharply reduced available supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, pork futures fell sharply, as did cocoa  
futures. 
</P>
<P>
	Sugar jumped as European buyers reported a shortage of available  
white sugar, which boosted speculation a world glut may be waning. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian importers in recent weeks have been snapping up  
available supplies, hoping to take delivery before an Aug. 1 
increase of tariffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia is the world's largest sugar importer, but recently moved  
to boost tariffs to protect farmers in its domestic sugar-beet 
market. That, however, leaves importers vulnerable to paying 
sharply higher rates later this year, should domestic production 
fail to live up to expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	Sugar for July delivery rose 0.23 cent to 5.52 cents a pound.  
</P>
<P>
	Pork futures fell sharply on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange  
amid expectations the government on Friday will report the amount 
of pork in storage has climbed to a new record. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Agriculture Department was likely to report supplies of  
pork bellies, or uncured bacon, rose to 107.5 million pounds, 
according to average analyst estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders say increased demand for pork during the summer grilling  
season has been overshadowed by continued-large supplies. Pork 
producers have been struggling to slash large herds, but a supply 
glut continues unabated. 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, meatpackers appear to have secured enough supplies for  
the foreseeable future, leaving little room for gains even if 
consumer demand rises. 
</P>
<P>
	July lean hogs fell 1.6 cents to 49.67 cents a pound.  
</P>
<P>
	Cocoa futures retreated on the New York Board of Trade on  
speculation chocolate makers have secured enough supplies to last 
until the next West African harvest. 
</P>
<P>
	Speculators bailed out of the market as cocoa purchases appeared  
to dry up, erasing concerns about declining cocoa sales from 
exporters in Ghana and Ivory Coast, the world's largest growers. 
</P>
<P>
	Chocolate makers had stepped into the market recently to snap up  
cheap supplies that came as growers flooded the market with the 
smaller of two harvests each year. 
</P>
<P>
	Market participants also noted weather conditions have been  
largely favorable in those countries, which could promote a bumper 
main crop for harvesting this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	September cocoa fell $28 to $1,075 a ton.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
