<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Deficit Holds at Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- America's trade deficit held steady in April --  
though still at a record high -- amid early signs that U.S. 
companies are selling more products to foreign countries recovering 
from recession. 
</P>
<P>
	``While it cannot be said that the world's markets for U.S  
products is booming again, it certainly does look as if the bottom 
has been reached,'' said Joel L. Naroff, chief economist at Naroff 
Economic Advisors in Holland, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	April's trade deficit of $18.9 billion matched a revised  
estimate of the deficit in March, the Commerce Department said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The government originally had pegged the March deficit at $19.7  
billion. The new, lower March estimate, however, was still a record 
high. 
</P>
<P>
	Global economic troubles that started nearly two years ago in  
Asia have hampered America's trade performance as overseas markets 
for U.S. products have dwindled and a flood of cheap imports causes 
stiff competition for domestic producers. 
</P>
<P>
	Highlighting how badly America's trade picture has deteriorated,  
the government released a separate report Thursday showing that the 
deficit in the current account -- the broadest measure of trade -- 
hit an all-time high of $68.6 billion in the first three months of 
this year. The current account covers not only trade in merchandise 
and services, which are reflected in the regular monthly report, 
but also investment flows and foreign aid. 
</P>
<P>
	American exports have started to pick up this spring, however,  
as other countries have begun a tentative recovery from recession. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. exports, which had fallen for five previous months, staged  
a small comeback in April, rising 1.2 percent to $78 billion. The 
improvement touched all product categories from foods to consumer 
goods such as appliances, and industrial supplies including cotton 
cloth and chemicals. 
</P>
<P>
	Imports also continued to rise, climbing 1 percent to $97  
billion in April, a record high. Nevertheless, there were several 
bright spots. 
</P>
<P>
	Imports from Japan dropped for the first time since November,  
pulling the sensitive deficit with the Asian economic powerhouse 
down 13.1 percent to $5.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the trade deficit with Mexico, a partner in the  
controversial North American Free Trade Agreement, also declined in 
April by 32.5 percent to $1.7 billion due to a sharp drop in 
imports. 
</P>
<P>
	And imports of motor vehicles and parts declined in April by 5.9  
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, National Association of Manufacturers president  
Jerry Jasinowski said that ``slow economic growth abroad is 
continuing to hurt manufacturers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	America's deficit with the 15-nation European Union increased by  
9.7 percent to $2.9 billion in April. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, imports from China rose to $5.8 billion, the highest since  
November. That helped push the U.S. trade deficit with China -- the 
second-biggest with any country behind Japan -- up by 15.7 percent 
to $4.8 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the April deficit with countries belonging to the  
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries -- which agreed this 
spring to limit production in the face of falling world demand for 
oil -- more than doubled in April to $1.8 billion, the most since 
October 1997. That was largely due to a sharp spike in oil and gas 
prices because of the production limits. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton administration officials have argued that while such a  
high overall trade deficit is not sustainable indefinitely, it has 
a positive side: As the only major economy doing well, the United 
States is playing a valuable role providing markets for other 
countries struggling to get back on their feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists also note that cheap imports have helped keep  
inflation low here during a period of unusually high employment and 
heavy spending by Americans. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
