<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House OKs Posting of 10 Commandments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House, working on a bill to deter juvenile  
crime, voted today to permit the display of the Ten Commandments in 
schools as lawmakers headed toward a showdown on gun control. 
</P>
<P>
	By 248-180, House members approved Rep. Robert Aderholt's  
amendment to allow states to decide whether to permit such displays 
on government property. The amendment, Aderholt said, was a first 
step toward reinstilling the value of human life in children 
influenced by violent culture. 
</P>
<P>
	One lawmaker, Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., said recently that if the  
Ten Commandments had been posted at Columbine High School, the 
April 20 massacre there would never have happened. The amendment's 
sponsor didn't go that far. 
</P>
<P>
	``I understand that simply posting the Ten Commandments will not  
instantly change the moral character of our nation,'' Aderholt, 
R-Ala., said. ``However, it is an important step to promote 
morality, and an end of children killing children.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The vote prompted a sharp rebuke from groups that say the  
amendment violates the separation of church and state. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think this is just one more sad example of religion being  
used as a political football by a Congress which apparently cannot 
find any real solution to the problem under debate,'' said Barry 
Lynn, executive director of Americans United for Separation of 
Church and State. ``Congress probably should spend more time 
obeying the Ten Commandments and less time trying to exploit them 
for crass political purposes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Supreme Court in 1980 struck down as unconstitutional a  
Kentucky law requiring the posting of a copy of the Ten 
Commandments in each public school classroom. The court said such 
postings violated the required separation of religion and 
government. 
</P>
<P>
	Later in the day, the House rejected, 266-161, an amendment by  
Rep. Bart Stupak, D-Mich., that would have given video game 
manufacturers six months to come up with a labeling system that 
alerts parents to violent materials in their products. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote on the Aderholt amendment was a victory for  
conservatives in the debate over whether violent culture, the 
proliferation of guns or a combination of the two are responsible 
for a sudden outbreak of school shootings and other youth violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans for the most part have sided with a cultural  
solution and taken aim at the entertainment industry, pushing 
legislation to change the violent and sexual content of movies, 
video games, music and thus real life. Democrats, meanwhile, want 
more laws to keep guns out of the hands of children. 
</P>
<P>
	The House today also approved by voice vote a proposal by Rep.  
Ed Markey, D-Mass., commissioning a study of the firearms 
industry's marketing practices to children. A similar provision was 
passed by the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Aderholt's victory provided fresh evidence that the gun  
restrictions passed by the Senate stand little chance of surviving 
the House. Democrats are fighting the powerful gun lobby and the 
most senior House member of their own party, Rep. John Dingell of 
Michigan, who has proposed a shorter waiting period for gun 
purchase background checks than those proposed by the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're up against a lot of money,'' House Democratic leader  
Dick Gephardt of Missouri said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The votes today followed defeat of another cultural proposal  
that would have curbed access by children to explicit sexual or 
violent material in video games and movies. Propelled by aggressive 
lobbying by the entertainment industry, the House rejected the 
measure Wednesday on a 282-146 vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course we worked it hard,'' Jack Valenti, president of the  
Motion Picture Association of America, told reporters in a 
conference call shortly after the vote. ``I think whoever drafted 
the bill drafted it in such a way as to be simply, blatantly, and I 
guess irrefutably, unconstitutional.''	   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., said the measure was designed to ``slow 
the flood of toxic waste into our kids' minds.'' But at one point 
in the debate, Hyde acidly acknowledged that he could not compete 
with the industry's political action committee -- a reference to 
campaign contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anyone who thinks (school violence) has nothing to do with the  
media is an idiot,'' Rep. Jo Ann Emerson, R-Mo., said today on the 
House floor. 
</P>
<P>
	Pro-gun-control Democrats, meanwhile, were still fighting  
Dingell, who is pushing a National Rifle Association-backed 
amendment that would cut the waiting period for background checks 
at gun shows from three days in the Senate bill to 24 hours. If 
there's no definitive answer in that time period, the purchaser may 
take possession of the gun. Dingell said most gun checks are 
completed in a matter of hours. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton awoke at 5 a.m. in Paris to telephone four  
wavering Democrats: Reps. Gary Condit and Mike Thompson of 
California, Marion Berry of Arkansas and Ron Kind of Wisconsin. 
Clinton urged a ``no'' vote on the NRA-supported Dingell amendment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
