<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Odom Wants To Return to College </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SOUTH KINGSTOWN, R.I. (AP) -- Lamar Odom wants out of the NBA  
draft so he can return to play for Rhode Island next season. 
</P>
<P>
	John Vanner, Rhode Island's assistant athletic director,  
confirmed Odom's decision today, but added, ``I don't know why he 
changed his mind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 19-year-old player averaged 17.6 points and 9.4 rebounds  
last season. He is rated among the top five picks in the NBA draft 
on June 30 by several scouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Pulling out of the draft won't be easy because the 6-foot-9  
forward already signed with an agent. But athletic director Ron 
Petro is looking into filing an appeal with the NCAA to have Odom 
reinstated. 
</P>
<P>
	Odom signed with New York agent Jeff Klein but has since fired  
him, Rhode Island coach Jerry DiGregorio said. Under NCAA rules, 
anyone who signs with an agent is barred from returning to college 
to play. 
</P>
<P>
	If the NCAA grants Odom a waiver by an NBA deadline of June 23,  
Odom could remove his name from the pro draft and return to school. 
It is unclear what arguments Rhode Island would use to justify a 
waiver. 
</P>
<P>
	Odom's commitment to playing pro basketball next season came  
into doubt over the weekend, when he skipped a leaguewide physical. 
He then canceled a workout with the Charlotte Hornets on Wednesday, 
and turned up on Rhode Island's campus Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``If an individual signs with an agent, they are ineligible,''  
said Bill Saum, the NCAA's director of agent and gambling 
activities. ``If there are mitigating circumstances, they are 
examined.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
