<DOCNO> APW19990617.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 23:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cartoonists Confront Race Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) -- Five rich, white people wait for a  
train. One holds a newspaper that reads, ``Iverson Ignites City.'' 
Their hair is in corn rows. 
</P>
<P>
	The editorial cartoon was intended as a critique of whites'  
belated embrace of Allen Iverson, a black basketball star for the 
Philadelphia 76ers with a bad-boy reputation. 
</P>
<P>
	Not everyone got the message. A black reader wrote to say  
focusing on black hairstyles was racist, and the cartoonist, who is 
white, wasn't surprised by the reaction. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think race is such a sensitive issue that any time you do  
anything about it there's somebody who wants to take offense,'' 
said Signe Wilkinson of The Philadelphia Daily News. ``We forget 
that well into the 1950s and 1960s, racist images in America were 
ubiquitous. If you're 50 years or older, they're still in the back 
of your head.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The American Association of Editorial Cartoonists met Thursday  
in Chattanooga to discuss, among other topics, the perils of 
offending people in the process of trying to denounce racism. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Days, the deputy managing editor of the Philadelphia  
newspaper, said many complaints -- such as the one about Ms. 
Wilkinson's cartoon, which he liked -- reflect minorities' general 
mistrust of papers. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you talk about mainstream press, a lot of black folks, a  
lot of Latinos ... they put `white' in front of it,'' said Days, 
who is black. ``There is a belief it is suspect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kirk Walters, editorial cartoonist with The Blade of Toledo,  
Ohio, said he was startled when some blacks protested his 1998 
cartoon about the Ku Klux Klan. 
</P>
<P>
	The Klan had denounced the dragging murder of James Byrd Jr. in  
Jasper, Texas, and Walters, who is white, saw the move as 
hypocritical. He drew a cartoon Klansman saying his group opposes 
``tying negroes'' to truck bumpers because ``it could hurt the 
resale value of the truck.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some blacks felt the drawing made light of a gruesome hate  
crime. Thirteen of the 17 members of the Ohio Legislative Black 
Caucus signed a letter requesting an apology from the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't meant to be funny,'' Walters said. ``It was meant to  
say look what's going on. The Klan has made a deliberate effort to 
appear mainstream. ... That couldn't stand.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vanessa Gallman, editorial page editor of the Lexington (Ky.)  
Herald-Leader, said cartoonists shouldn't be surprised by an angry 
response, considering readers remember past slights, even if 
they're unrelated to a specific drawing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think editorial cartoonists should assume people think  
they're the good guy,'' said Ms. Gallman, who is black. 
</P>
<P>
	But she also said editors need to differentiate between  
legitimate complaints and those meant only to further someone's 
political agenda. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Gallman said cartoonists often know more about world issues  
than the problems in their own communities. She suggested 
``plugging in'' to local groups and also adding blacks in crowd 
scenes and in other everyday situations in drawings. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to show more that minorities exist other than when  
the cartoons are about race,'' she said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990617.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-17 17:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Robertson Warns GOP Leaders of Gore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Pat Robertson warned Senate GOP leaders  
Thursday that Vice President Al Gore is ``co-opting a number of 
Republican issues,'' and urged them to energize religious 
conservatives by holding votes on an agenda stressing faith and 
family. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview, the Christian Coalition president said he also  
brought up the Internal Revenue Service's recent denial of 
tax-exempt status for his organization in a series of meetings he 
requested with GOP senators. 
</P>
<P>
	Robertson said he suggested they conduct a ``Senate inquiry'' of  
the IRS for ``selective enforcement'' because it has granted 
tax-exempt status to liberal organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those Robertson met with were Senate Majority Leader Trent  
Lott, R-Miss.; Majority Whip Don Nickles, R-Okla., and Finance 
Committee Chairman William Roth, R-Del. He said he received no 
commitments for votes or for an IRS inquiry. 
</P>
<P>
	Robertson made his rounds on Capitol Hill a day after Gore  
formally announced his candidacy for president, stressing family, 
values and faith. 
</P>
<P>
	``Al Gore is in the process of co-opting a number of Republican  
issues,'' Robertson said, adding that the 2000 voting ``could be 
the most crucial election of the 20th century.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robertson said he told Lott that with the votes lawmakers have  
taken so far this year, ``the average person doesn't understand 
what the Republican Congress is doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he suggested votes on a proposed constitutional  
amendment to protect religious Americans from discrimination, and 
on a GOP plan to reduce taxes on married couples, many of them now 
paying more than they would if they were single. 
</P>
<P>
	Robertson also emphasized the need for the GOP to express its  
desire to win a veto-proof majority in favor of banning certain 
late-term abortions that opponents have labeled ``partial-birth 
abortions, according to Christian Coalition spokesman Mike Russell. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked why Robertson had requested the meetings at this time,  
Russell said the Christian Coalition founder was disappointed by 
``the knee-jerk reaction'' of the Senate to the shootings at 
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., this spring. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate approved some restrictions on gun sales. Russell said  
Robertson believes that Congress should instead address ``the real 
moral problems of this country'' by helping families and 
emphasizing faith. 
</P>
<P>
	Robertson said he also told the senators that his group will get  
strongly involved in next year's congressional elections. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the Christian Coalition isn't in the game, the Republicans  
are going to lose'' in 2000,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRS has concluded that some Christian Coalition activities,  
such as its distributing voter guides at churches across the 
country, were too partisan for it to enjoy tax-exempt status. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he had asked the Republican senators to intervene with  
IRS on his group's behalf, Robertson said he did not have to 
because the ruling amounts to ``only be a hiccup in our 
operation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Christian Coalition officials have said the group is  
reorganizing itself to deal with the ruling. A new Christian 
Coalition International will engage in partisan activity, including 
candidate endorsements and political contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	The Christian Coalition of Texas, a tax-exempt group, will be  
renamed Christian Coalition of America and will limit its activity 
to nonpartisan ``voter education.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
